<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PriestCharged     10-11 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Priest Charged,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest Charged in Sex Assault</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BETHEL PARK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest was charged
Tuesday with sexually assaulting two altar boys over a six-year
period.
   Police said The Rev. Robert G. Wolk, 48, former pastor of St.
Thomas More Roman Catholic Church in suburban Bethel Park, engaged
in sexual activities with the youths, now 20 and 18 years old,
between March 1981 and May 1987 at the parish house. They also
contend the activities occurred in the guest house of the Sisters
of the Holy Spirit in suburban Allison Park.
   ``Other unnamed Catholic priests, in conjunction with Father
Wolk, participated and engaged in the same sexual misconduct in
other areas of southwestern Pennsylvania,'' police said.
   ``These other unnamed Catholic priests conducted
sado-masochistic rituals on several young males,'' they said.
   Wolk, who is now a resident of St. Luke's Institute of Suitland,
Md., a psychiatric care facility for priests, was charged with four
counts of involuntary deviate sexual intercourse and two counts
each of attempted involuntary deviate sexual intercourse and
corruption of minors.
   Allegheny County District Attorney Robert Colville said he will
seek Wolk's extradition.
   Diocesan spokesman Rev. Ron Lengwin said church officials first
learned of the allegations from one of the reported victims on
Sept. 22, 1987, and Wolk was interviewed immediately and removed
from his assignment two days later.
</TEXT>
