<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 4thLd-Writethru a0807 10-11 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0807,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Dukakis Shirks Reponsibility for Prison Furloughs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To add comment that Quayle met with Baker over anonymous
sniping from Bush camp, INSERT one graf after 20th pvs, He has...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VAN WERT, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, winding through Midwestern farm land on a bus tour, said
Tuesday that Democrat Michael Dukakis had never ``owned up to his
irresponsible conduct'' in the Massachusetts prison furlough
program.
   At every stop through the flat, fertile countryside near his
home state of Indiana, speakers portrayed Quayle as a ``son of the
heartland,'' and he told flag-waving crowds that their
old-fashioned values would be preserved in a George Bush presidency.
   A crowd of several hundred supporters gave Quayle a thunderous
ovation at a homestate rally in Indianapolis on Tuesday night.
   But reporters traveling with the senator got no welcome at all.
The crowd chanted, ``Just say no!'' as they entered the hall.
Reporters were also booed after the Republican convention at a
Bush-Quayle rally in Huntington, Ind., Quayle's hometown, as they
attempted to question him about his military record.
   Quayle had a fighter's message for the Indianapolis group: ``We
plan on taking some heat but staying in the kitchen. But in the
end, we'll get the job done. We have just begun to fight.''
   Earlier in Ohio, the senator spoke of the importance of that
state, which has 23 electoral votes and is viewed as an important
swing state in the November elections.
   ``The eyes of America in this election Nov. 8 will be on Ohio
and the Midwest,'' Quayle told a rally in Van Wert.
   In Napoleon, Quayle responded to Dukakis' complaints about how
the GOP ticket was portraying the prison furlough program in
Massachusetts and the case of Willie Horton Jr., a convicted
murderer who escaped from a 1986 urlough and attacked a Maryland
couple the following year.
   Dukakis said he resented being portrayed as insensitive to the
plight of crime victims, and noted that members of his own family
had been victimized in the past.
   The Massachusetts governor said people such as Horton, who had
ben sentenced to life in prison without possibility of parole,
could not be furloughed under current state law.
   Interviewed Tuesday on NBC's ``Today'' show, Dukakis criticized
Bush for making a campaign issue of prison furloughs. ``To use
these human tragedies for your own political purposes, I think, is
really a very crass and cynical thing,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic nominee said crimes similar to the Horton case
had been committed under the federal furlough program and in
California, where furloughs were initiated in the 1970s when
President Reagan was governor of that state.
   But Quayle decried on Tuesday what he called Dukakis' ``sorry
record of dealing with violent crime.''
   ``Even after the Horton case, the governor strenuously defended
the furlough program. He did not act to change it,'' Quayle said,
adding correctly that the Massachusetts law was changed only under
pressure from the state Legislature.
   Quayle said 62 criminals are listed as missing or escapees from
Massachusetts furlough and early release programs.
   He said Dukakis had failed to heed the advice of a special state
commission which said in 1975 it could find no justification for
prison furloughs.
   State officials say there actually are 11 people classified as
escaped from a furlough program _ 10 of them from before 1979 _ and
20 more considered escaped from work release programs.
   As for the special state commission, Andrew Dreyfus, spokesman
for state Human Services Secretary Philip Johnston said there was a
commission that looked at a range of furlough issues and drafted a
bill that was pocket vetoed by the governor in 1976.
   Dreyfus said the bill changed the eligibility rules for
furloughs for first-degree-murder lifers but did not ban them.
Under the new policy adopted earlier this year, there's no furlough
for first-degree lifers whatsoever.
   ``He has not truly and sincerely owned up to his irresponsible
conduct,'' Quayle said.
   Behind the scenes, a Quayle aide who insisted on anonymity said
the candidate met with Bush campaign James A. Baker III over the
weekend and complained about anonymous quotes from within the Bush
camp that he was a liability to the ticket. Quayle had said openly
last Friday after the vice presidential debate that he would like
to find out who made those remarks, adding, ``I think I might have
some influence on their job security.''
   At rallies throughout the day-long bus tour, Quayle sounded
themes aimed at what he called ``heartland'' citizens. He accused
Dukakis of being soft on crime and belonging to a radical left-wing
organization, which is how Quayle characterized the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   ``Right and wrong is at the very core of life in this beloved
Midwest region that I grew up in and where you live,'' he told the
Napoleon crowd. ``The values of this region have not left me.''
   The trip wound through cornfields from Napoleon to Ottawa, Van
Wert, Celina and Greenville along Ohio's western border.
</TEXT>
