<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BookNominees     10-11 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Book Nominees,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Book Award Nominees Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three previous National Book Awards winners _
Don DeLillo, J.F. Powers and Peter Gay _ were among the 10 nominees
announced for the 1988 awards.
   DeLillo, who won in 1985 for ``White Noise,'' was nominated for
``Libra,'' a novel based on the life of Lee Harvey Oswald and the
events that led to President John F. Kennedy's assassination.
   Powers, who won in 1963 for his novel ``Morte D'Urban,'' is up
for the fiction honor again with ``Wheat That Springeth Green,'' a
novel about a middle-aged priest coping with a new curate.
   Gay, who won in 1967 for ``The Enlightenment: An
Interpretation,'' was again nominated for non-fiction for his
biography, ``Freud: A Life For Our Time.''
   The National Book Awards were established in 1950. Winners will
be announced in New York on Nov. 29. Awards are given for fiction
and non-fiction, with each winner receiving a $10,000 prize and a
commemorative sculpture by Louise Nevelson.
   Other nominees for fiction:
   _Pete Dexter, whose novel ``Paris Trout'' concerns the murder of
a 14-year-old black girl by a white man in a small Georgia town
just after World War II.
   _Mary McGarry Morris, whose first novel, ``Vanished,'' is about
a couple who kidnap a toddler and embark on a five-year flight from
justice.
   _Anne Tyler, whose novel ``Breathing Lessons,'' concerns a
long-married couple and the detours they take on the way to the
funeral of an old friend in Pennsylvania.
   The other nominees for non-fiction:
   _``Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863-1877,''
by Eric Foner.
   _``Nora,'' by Brenda Maddox, a biography of James Joyce's
lifelong companion and muse.
   _``Jefferson and Monticello,'' Jack McLaughlin's chronicle of
the life of Thomas Jefferson as seen through the prism of his love
for his rural homestead.
   _``A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and America in
Vietnam,'' by Neil Sheehan, which examines the war through the eyes
of one who lived most of his adult life in the midst of it.
</TEXT>
