<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-11 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disc jockey Paco Lopez has been working
at a radio station here for only four months, so he had to do a
stint on the graveyard shift.
   Now, the KICKS 106 disc jockey has agreed to be ``buried alive''
as part of a promotional gimmick.
   ``Since they won't give me a vacation, I figured the closest
thing to it was to do this,'' he said.
   He entered his plot at 7 p.m. Monday. He is scheduled to rest 2
feet underground in a specially made 3-by-6-foot coffin _ without
food, water or bathroom facilities _ until 7 p.m. Wednesday.
   ``It's nothing more than psychological,'' he said. ``It's like
lying in bed for 48 hours.''
   The coffin, buried at a car dealership, is hooked up with a
light, an air vent and a telephone over which Lopez will give live
radio reports, station promotions director Sheila Williamson said.
   The box also is equipped with a small video camera so Lopez can
be monitored continuously, she said.
   The Rev. Mike Harper, associate pastor of suburban Vestavia
Hills United Methodist Church, offered some cautionary comment
Sunday.
   ``It does seem a little tacky, although rather humorous,'' he
said. ``Needless to say, someone who recently had a death in the
family would not be overwhelmed with the appropriateness of it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 motorcyclists roared through
downtown Des Moines and surrounding suburbs, but the sight was
anything but menacing.
   Teddy bears were perched on the handlebars and Santa Claus was
leading the parade.
   The four-mile-long cavalcade Sunday marked the fifth annual
ABATE parade to gather toys for the St. Vincent de Paul Society.
ABATE stands for A Brotherhood Against Totalitarian Enactment, a
3,200-member Iowa motorcycle club.
   ``A lot of people have a negative image (of motorcyclists), and
we're trying to reject that stereotype and promote a positive
image,'' said Mike Cossitt of Des Moines, a member of the group.
   Police provided escorts for the 43-mile procession.
   ``A lot of people were out hanging on street corners cheering us
on,'' said Waldo Matejski, another ABATE member.
</TEXT>
