<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     10-11 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Gives `Final Word' on Presidency Question</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPOLEON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle, still trying to put his stumbling response at last week's
debate behind him, is giving what he says is his ``final word'' on
what steps he would take if thrust unexpectedly into the presidency.
   Even as he insisted to reporters Monday as he arrived in Ohio
that his campaign was ``on a roll,'' Quayle continued to face
questions on the issue as well as questions about whether he is a
drag on the GOP ticket.
   Quayle tries a new wrinkle in his campaign today with a
grass-roots approach: a day-long bus trip through small towns of
western Ohio.
   He gave his most detailed response to date when asked after a
Detroit speech how he now would answer the question put to him at
last week's debate with Lloyd Bentsen, his Democratic counterpart.
   During the debate, Quayle said he would say a prayer and summon
his advisers. The next day, Quayle revised the answer in speeches
by saying he would continue George Bush's policies.
   During a question-and-answer session Monday after an economics
speech in Detroit, Quayle called the debate question ``totally
inappropriate'' because it was ``completely hypothetical.''
   He said he would as a new president make a request to talk to
the nation, and he would consult with allies. But, he said, his
other responses would depend on the situation.
   ``Obviously you do different things under an assassination. The
first thing you do in an assassination _ I would still say a prayer
for myself and the nation _ but the first thing you do is you get
on the phone and call the head of the CIA and see what he thinks it
was. You don't convene a Cabinet meeting right away,'' Quayle said.
   ``You get your secretary of defense, your national security
adviser, your secretary of state and meet with them immediately. In
the situation of an illness it would be a different type of
situation,'' he said.
   Quayle said he would have ``contingency plans under different
situations.''
   ``And I'll tell you what: I'm not going to go out and hold a
news conference about it. I'm going to put it in a safe and keep it
there,'' he said heatedly.
   Speaking to reporters later aboard his campaign plane, Quayle
said of his latest response to the question: ``That's the final
word.''
   Quayle was also asked about polls indicating he continues to
bring negatives to the Bush-Quayle ticket.
   A Los Angeles Times poll released Monday showed the two tickets
were in a virtual dead heat _ 44 percent for the Republicans to 41
percent for the Democrats _ but Bush leads Dukakis 48-39 if the two
candidates are presented as running alone. The poll had a margin of
error of five percentage points in either direction.
   Quayle said he was ``absolutely not'' a drag on the ticket.
Crowds had responded positively to him after the debate, he said.
   ``We will continue to do what we're charged with doing and that
is going to the key states like Ohio, going to states where it's on
the margin ... and the reason I'm being sent to those places is
because I'm an asset to the ticket,'' he said.
   Quayle also defended his assertions, made during the Detroit
speech, that the Reagan-Bush administration ``kept our commitment
to the truly needy.''
   He had not mentioned in the speech that the Reagan
administration has consistently proposed cuts in programs for
education, health and the needy. Congress refused to go along with
some of the proposed cuts, resulting in the increases Quayle
praised.
   ``The fact of the matter is that what the president signed into
law and what we're spending today was up significantly in all of
those categories,'' Quayle told reporters on the plane.
   But the figures Quayle cited in his speech left room for debate.
He said, for example, that federal education spending has grown by
38 percent during the Reagan years. However, the Reagan
administration has asked for significant reductions in federal
education assistance in every year except for the current one.
   Quayle cited Pell grants for lower and moderate income students
_ an area he said had grown 64 percent during the Reagan years. But
the Reagan administration proposed a 38 percent cut in Pell grants
for fiscal 1983, 30 percent for 1986 and 30 percent for 1988, cuts
that Congress refused to go along with.
   Quayle noted that the Aid to Families with Dependent Children
program grew about 32 percent during the Reagan years. However,
fewer families are eligible for such assistance because of tighten
eligibility requirements proposed by the administration.
   The figures also do not take into account inflation, which for
the 1981-88 period was a cumulative 29.9 percent.
</TEXT>
