<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-11 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollars Drops, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged Tuesday against the Japanese
yen, while share prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 85.93-point
winner Friday, closed at 27,469.60, gaining another 211.33 points
or 0.78 percent.
   The dollar finished trading at 131.15 yen, down 2.35 yen from
Friday's close of 133.50 yen. After opening at 132.20 yen, the
currency moved between 130.95 yen and 132.23 yen.
   Japan's stock and foreign exchange markets were closed Monday
for a national holiday.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's slide below the 132-yen mark to
technical selling, because there was no fresh market-affecting news
to induce dollar-selling.
   ``The dollar in Tokyo fell following its plunge in London,''
said Takamasa Yamasaki with Daiwa Bank.
   The dollar declined Monday in London after a statement by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who said the British
government would keep interest rates high ``as long as it is
necessary to fight inflation,'' market participants said.
   Lawson also said in a television interview he would push
interest rates higher if sterling falls. Higher British interest
rates would increase the investment attractiveness of the British
currency, possibly at the expense of the dollar.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking anonymously, said the
dollar remained weak but added a slide below 131.50 yen was
unlikely.
   On the stock exchange, ``share prices were higher almost across
the board,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``The index rose sharply following the Dow Jones' higher close
in New York (overnight),'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   But trading was light because some participants were cautious
ahead of the report of U.S. trade figures for August, due out
Thursday in Washington, the analyst said.
</TEXT>
