<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-UtahGovernor Bjt   10-11 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Governor, Bjt,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah Governor Underdog In Bid For Second Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hobbled by an independent challenge that
has siphoned off some of his conservative support, Republican Gov.
Norm Bangerter is a distinct underdog in his bid for a second term.
   Democrat Ted Wilson holds a double-digit lead in the polls, and
independent Merrill Cook commands the loyality of Republicans who
blame the governor for the biggest tax increase in Utah history.
   However, Bangerter and his supporters contend there is time
before November's election to reclaim the support that swept him
into office four years ago as Utah's first Republican governor in
two decades.
   ``The polls are tightening and I think Norm could pull this
out,'' Charles Akerlow, former state GOP chairman, said recently.
``He's running hard and running scared and, consequently, running
very well.''
   ``We think we can win it with a good turnout and a good showing
by (Vice President George) Bush and (Republican Sen. Orrin)
Hatch,'' said campaign manager Dave Buhler.
   Bangerter's biggest problem has not been Wilson, former mayor of
Salt Lake City, but his own record.
   Elected in 1984 with 56 percent of the vote, Bangerter saw his
popularity plummet two years later after he cajoled a bipartisan
majority in the Legislature into passing a record $166 million tax
increase.
   He also has been sharply criticized for a $60 million pumping
project _ launched just as the state entered a long dry spell _ to
control flooding on the Great Salt Lake, and for the slow recovery
of Utah's lackluster economy.
   The higher taxes spawned a movement that drafted Cook, owner of
a mining explosives company, to carry its tax-limitation message to
voters.
   Despite an $80 million refund and tax cut approved by the
Legislature in August, support for Cook has grown from around 9
percent last spring to 16 percent in a Sept. 25 survey published by
The Salt Lake Tribune.
   The survey of 600 voters gave Wilson a 49-29 lead over Bangerter
with 5 percent undecided. The margin of error was plus or minus 4
percentage points.
   Bangerter said Cook's support among Republicans and conservative
independents has made it difficult for him to highlight his
differences with Wilson.
   Cook's supporters ``are conservative voters and conservative
voters generally vote for Republicans. I think it's been proven I'm
much more conservative fiscally and in every other way than Ted
Wilson, and so it skews that,'' Bangerter said.
   Bangerter also has been hurt by three tax-limitation
initiatives, endorsed by Cook, that will be on the ballot.
Bangerter and Wilson oppose the measures, which would reduce state
and local government revenue by about $300 million or more.
   ``They sort of remind everybody that it was Norm who raised
taxes in the first place,'' said Akerlow.
   Akerlow said that Bangerter also might actually benefit from
Cook's candidacy if Cook continues to pull support from Wilson and
splits the vote enough for Bangerter to win without a majority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
