<DOCNO> AP881011-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PaperStrike     10-11 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paper Strike,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paperworkers Call Off Strikes In 3 States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAY, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking workers at International Paper Co.
mills in three states concede they lost their sometimes violent
16-month battle with the company but vow to continue pressing for
better working conditions.
   The United Paperworkers International Union abruptly announced
an end to strikes at International Paper mills in Maine, Wisconsin
and Pennsylvania, saying the move would give the 2,300 strikers the
first shot at any jobs vacated by the non-union workers running the
mills.
   ``This stage of the war is over,'' said Felix Jacques, executive
vice president of Local 14. ``We have lost this battle but the war
for justice in the workplace is not over.''
   The workers, including 1,200 at the Jay plant, went on strike
June 16, 1987, when the union rejected a concessionary contract.
The company imposed the contract and kept the plants open with
replacement workers.
   The key unresolved issues included the company's demand to end
double time for employees who worked Sundays and holidays, and to
eliminate more than 175 jobs by changing work rules.
   William Meserve, the local's president, said the strikes were
halted because the company was willing to spend ``hundreds of
millions of dollars to try to break the unions or make them
ineffective.''
   Jacques said the national union could not provide the support
needed to continue the strike much longer. The $55 weekly payments
to the strikers were scheduled to be suspended in six weeks, he
said.
   ``It's not that we don't want to fight _ it's just that we
can't,'' said striker Roland Samson. ``We have nothing to fight
with.''
   Jacques notified his grim-faced members at a news conference
Monday, one day after presidents of UPIU locals at the three mills
had reached their decision at union headquarters in Nashville,
Tenn. The 1,200 union members in Jay comprised the largest group of
strikers.
   A mill spokesman here acknowledged that by calling off the
strike, the union members gained the right to be given preference
for any openings. But he said the mill was ``at full complement''
and hires new employees at an average of only three per week.
   ``As openings occur, we will welcome workers who have been on
strike who qualify for those openings,'' said the spokesman,
Richard White. He emphasized that no replacements would be asked to
leave.
   International Paper, one of the world's largest paper companies,
has said the strike had little effect on production. Shareholders'
net earnings during the first half of 1988 were $347 million,
compared with $180 million for the period last year, White said.
Net sales rose from $3.7 billion for the period last year to $4.7
billion this year.
   Strikes also were halted at International Paper mills in De
Pere, Wis., and Lock Haven, Pa. The action had no direct impact on
the Mobile, Ala., mill, where the company has locked out more than
1,000 union members.
   The union had sought to consolidate the disputes at the four
mills, but with little success.
   During the strike, this mill in this central Maine town of 4,000
had been the scene of boisterous rallies, marches, and occasional
violence and vandalism that led to court orders limiting activities
on the picket line.
   A series of chemical leaks and accidents at the mill heightened
tensions in recent months, with the union blaming the problems on
the new workers' inexperience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka     10-11 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Injured In Bomb Explosions In Colombo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded in the capital
and injured at least six people today, a day after five people died
during a nationwide strike to protest the government's peace
overtures to Tamil rebels.
   Authorities believe the bombs were planted by the People's
Liberation Front, a radical Sinhalese group that called Monday's
strike, said A.S. Seneviratne, deputy inspector-general of police.
   ``Troops and police cordoned off the area of the blasts and
conducted search operations,'' Seneviratne said. ``A number of
suspects have been taken in for questioning.''
   Two bombs exploded in the business center of Colombo, while a
third went off near a supermarket in a suburb of the city, he said.
   The People's Liberation Front says a peace accord aimed at
ending the 5-year-old civil war grants too many concessions to the
Tamils, who are fighting for an independent homeland in the
northeastern province.
   The group has vowed to kill all supporters of the accord and is
blamed for at least 500 deaths since the agreement was signed on
July 29, 1987.
   Tamil insurgents have been fighting for a separate state since
1983, claiming they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese. At least 8,500 people have been killed in the fighting.
   Two bombs had exploded in Colombo on Monday during the strike,
injuring four people, including two soldiers.
   Five people died and four others were injured Monday when police
opened fire on a group of Sinhalese demonstrators who attacked a
police station in the town of Matara, about 85 miles south of
Colombo.
   Meanwhile, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest and
most militant rebel group, said it was not responsible for the
killing Sunday of 47 Sinhalese villagers in a northern village.
   ``The aim of this malicious report is to discredit our
organization,'' said a statement from the Tigers' office in London.
   The victims, including 13 women and 18 children, were killed
while they slept in the village of Ulukulama, 150 miles northeast
of Colombo. One military official, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules, had said the massacre was ``clearly the work of the
Tigers.''
   The killings were the worst burst of violence in the
ethnically-divided island for the past year and came a day before
nominations to a local administrative council in the
Tamil-dominated northeastern province closed.
   The council is a key part of the India-brokered peace accord
under which the Tamils agreed to give up arms in exchange for
limited autonomy. The Tigers accepted but later rejected the
agreement, saying it did not meet enough demands.
   India sponsored the accord because 60 million Tamils living in
southern India are sympathetic to the rebel cause. It sent an
estimated 47,000 peacekeeping troops to Sri Lanka on Oct. 10, 1987,
to implement the plan after the Tigers reneged.
   Other rebel groups which accepted the accord have filed
nominations to the administrative council despite a call by the
Tigers for a boycott.
   Election Commissioner Chandrananda De Silva said today that
members of the moderate Tamil groups already had been elected to 36
of the 71 seats because they were uncontested. Polls are scheduled
to be held on Nov. 19 for the other 35 seats, which are being
contested by Tamil groups, the governing United National Party and
the opposition Sri Lanka Moslem Congress, he said.
   Tamils, who are mainly Hindus, form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. The mostly Buddhist Sinhalese make up 75 percent of
the population and control the country's government and military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
