<DOCNO> AP881011-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Red-EyedFly     10-11 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Red-Eyed Fly,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red-Eyed Fly Is Set To Help Reduce Destructive Insect's Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Brazilian red-eyed fly, which has a
fatal attraction to the pesky and destructive mole cricket, is
successfully breeding in Florida, scientists say.
   Red-eyed flies, introduced in April to help control the
crickets, have been found in traps set for them around Bradenton,
south of Tampa, an entomologist at the University of Florida said
Monday.
   ``We were a little worried until we finally found several
pregnant flies in our traps in late August,'' said Tom Walker.
``But now it looks like we've established a new enemy of the mole
cricket.''
   Mole crickets do at least $46 million worth of damage every year
to Florida vegetable fields, commercial turf operations, pastures
and golf courses, according to university scientists.
   ``We're working toward reducing the mole cricket population to a
point where it is no longer damaging,'' said Howard Frank, project
coordinator at university's Institute of Food and Agriculture
Sciences.
   ``We can't tell any difference yet in mole cricket populations.
We'll have to measure changes over several years to quantify the
effects,'' Frank said.
   The red-eyed Brazilian fly is about the size of a house fly.
Females respond to the male mole cricket's mating call and lay
larvae on or near the male mole cricket.
   The larvae burrow into the male mole cricket. They come out
about 10 days later after killing it.
   Now that the flies are breeding, the control project's next
obstacle is winter. Mole crickets are less active then and
scientists are unsure whether the flies will survive the winter.
   Walker is optimistic.
   ``We're 90 percent sure we'll have flies next spring,'' he said.
</TEXT>
