<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Arias-Peace     10-11 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arias-Peace,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arias Says Next U.S. President Should Support Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. election has stalled progress
on the Central American peace plan and parties to the agreement are
running out of time to fulfill the pact, Costa Rican President
Oscar Arias Sanchez said.
   Arias, here to announce the creation of a private peace
foundation financed with the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize he won for
sponsoring the peace plan, was careful to avoid blaming either U.S.
presidential candidate. He said Monday he believes either would
bring more understanding to the region.
   He urged the next U.S. president to support the plan and warned
against seeking military solutions in Central America.
   ``Whoever is elected to the White House, if they support the
peace plan, this plan is incompatible with warlike action,'' Arias
said.
   The five Central American presidents who signed the original
peace agreement are tentatively scheduled to meet again after the
U.S. elections, possibly Nov. 12-15 in El Salvador, to give the
plan a push, Arias said.
   ``Almost 14 months have gone by and we cannot feel satisfied _
there has not been the will to fulfill the agreement,'' Arias said.
``We are running out of time.''
   He did emphasize that the plan has accomplished a truce in
Nicaragua and started a dialogue among the participants, though.
   Arias blamed Nicaragua's leftist Sandinistas for being
inflexible on choosing a site for future negotiations with Contra
rebels and for hiding behind judicial technicalities in failing to
release 38 opposition leaders arrested in violation of the plan
during an anti-government demonstration.
   The Costa Rican president again rejected calls by the
Sandinistas and the Contras to put an international peace-keeping
force on the border between Honduras and Nicaragua, and perhaps
elsewhere, to separate the feuding sides.
   ``I do not believe it is necessary to introduce third
countries,'' Arias said. ``The greatness of the agreement is that
it is a Central American plan.''
   Arias also said he would welcome efforts by Fidel Castro to
achieve peace in Central America, noting the Cuban president has a
``very strong moral commitment'' to leftist guerrillas in El
Salvador and Guatemala and the Sandinista government in Nicaragua.
   The Costa Rican president stopped in Coral Gables on his way to
Spain to receive the Prince de Asturias Award, that nation's
highest honor, from King Juan Carlos. He was expected to stay at
least one day in the Miami area before flying to Spain.
   With his wife Margarita Penon de Arias at his side, he also
announced the creation of The Arias Foundation for Peace and Human
Progress. Arias said the $400,000 he received for the Nobel Prize
will be the seed money for the organization.
   Mrs. Arias, who will head the foundation, said it was aimed
particularly at saving families victimized by war and poverty in
Central America.
   The foundation will support research, design projects to benefit
children and families, provide scholarships and organize
international conferences.
</TEXT>
