<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew Curtailed in Southern Soviet Enclave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said they would ease a curfew today in
a southern enclave to help workers return to their jobs, but they
acknowledged that nearly yearlong strikes over Armenian demands
have ruined the region's economy.
   Production of goods and services in the enclave,
Nagorno-Karabakh, and the surrounding republic of Azerbaijan has
dropped below 1970 levels, the Communist Party daily Pravda said
Monday.
   The Armenian Christian majority in Nagorno-Karabakh wants the
area transferred from the jurisdiction of the republic of
Azerbaijan, which is predominantly Moslem, to neighboring Armenia.
   The news agency Tass said Monday that party and state
representatives, using personal persuasion, succeeded in drawing
workers back to 80 percent of the construction collectives in
Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Tass also said authorities would ease a curfew imposed Sept. 21
on Stepanakert, where troops and tanks were sent to quell ethnic
violence. To allow late shift workers to travel, the curfew in
Stepanakert will run from midnight to 5 a.m. rather than 9 p.m.-6
a.m., starting today.
   Soviet television on Monday night offered an upbeat report on
conditions in Armenia, showing smiling grape pickers and saying
that all 227 businesses in the capital, Yerevan, were operating.
   The Pravda article blamed the unrest on years of corruption and
economic problems.
   In a startling aside, however, it quoted the former Communist
Party chief in Sumgait, Azerbaijan, as blaming ethnic rioting that
killed 32 people in that industrial city in February on ex-convicts
and local wrath over air pollution. The official, D. Muslim-Zadye,
said the former convicts were sent to the area after their release
from prison.
   ``Speaking honestly, I expected an explosion,'' he said. ``It
had been ripening for a long time and just needed a spark. It found
one in the events in Nagorno-Karabakh.''
</TEXT>
