<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Mutineers,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Arrested Rightists In Raids Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops arrested four alleged
right-wing extremists during a series of raids ending early today,
and the military said the suspects were linked to an attack on a
military armory last June.
   In another development, the armed forces announced that
Communist rebels raided a police station in Davao del Norte
province Monday and kidnapped four policemen.
   Col. Manuel Oxales, deputy commander of the Manila district,
said the four rightists were arrested separately between Saturday
and Monday night.
   A fifth alleged extremist escaped from a window as troops burst
into his home in suburban Caloocan City early today, Oxales said.
   Heavily armed troops in full battle gear also surrounded a hotel
near military headquarters before dawn Tuesday. But Oxales denied
published reports that the troops were looking for former Lt. Col.
Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan, renegade leader of the bloody Aug. 28,
1987, bid to topple President Corazon Aquino.
   Oxales said the four face charges of conspiracy to commit
rebellion, robbery and sedition in connection with the June 11 raid
on the armory at Camp Crame, headquarters of the Philippine
Constabulary.
   The military said the raid was staged to free a former
provincial governor, Orlando Dulay, who is charged with murder in
the deaths of several campaign workers employed by Mrs. Aquino when
she ran for president against Ferdinand Marcos in 1986.
   The raiders failed to release Dulay but made off with 24 M-16
rifles, the military said.
   The four were presented to reporters at a press conference,
where one of them, Hai Buivanvan, admitted he was part of the
raiding force. Another suspect, Robert Taguda, said he joined the
rightist force because he was told it was an ``anti-Communist
group.''
   The latest arrests brought to nearly 80 the number of alleged
rightists whom the military claims to have apprehended in recent
weeks.
   Shortly before midnight Monday, soldiers set up roadblocks on
streets leading to the Camelot Hotel, and about an hour later,
armed troops wearing gas masks were seen entering the building in
suburban Quezon City.
   Officers refused to give any reason for the move nor would they
speak with reporters. The soldiers left about 1:30 a.m. without
explanation and without apparently having made any arrest.
   Peoples Journal Tonight and The Evening Star said the raiders
were looking for Honasan. The charismatic former colonel was
arrested last December but escaped from a prison ship in Manila Bay
the following April.
   Oxales said the raiders were looking for ``rightists elements''
reportedly seen at the hotel but none were found. Asked if the
``elements'' included Honasan, Oxales replied: ``Actually, we were
not looking for him there.''
   Mutineers occupied the Camelot Hotel and nearby Camp Aguinaldo,
headquarters of the Armed Forces of the Philippines, during the
failed coup. They were driven off by loyal forces after at least 53
people were killed and more than 300 were wounded.
   Monday's raid by Communist rebels took place in Santo Tomas, a
town of about 44,000 people located about 590 miles south of Manila
on Mindanao island.
   The report said four high school students were also injured
during the raid. It said the rebels fled with weapons, two
typewriters and the kidnapped policemen.
   The rebel New People's Army has been waging a 19-year insurgency
to establish a Marxist state in the Philippines.
