<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0504EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy     10-11 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Stakes Italian Government On Parliamentary Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Vote Scheduled To Begin About 11:30 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita has staked the future of his
6-month-old government on the outcome of a proposal to abolish most
secret voting in the legislature.
   But a vote on that proposal, scheduled for today, is itself
secret, opening the way for so-called secret ``snipers'' to go into
action.
   ``Snipers'' are lawmakers who vote against their own party. The
practice erodes party solidarity and has weakened many of Italy's
48 postwar governments.
   However, supporters of closed voting contend that because of the
tight discipline demanded by most parties, a lawmaker can only
maintain independence in secret.
   Closed voting can allow the Communists, Italy's second largest
party after de Mita's Christian Democrats, to muster a majority.
Indeed, Communists initially backed a proposal to make voting
public only on financial questions.
   On Friday, in the Chamber of Deputies, Parliament's lower house,
snipers were in fine form as the government won narrowly won votes
to include certain elements in its proposal. Their vote on the
overall package is scheduled for today, and the Italian Senate will
consider its own version of the proposal separately.
   De Mita, a Christian Democrat, formed his coalition government
in April, establishing the curtailment of secret voting as a key
platform plank. The other coalition members are the Socialists,
Republicans, Liberals and Social Democrats.
   The Socialists, who rank as the coalition's No. 2 member, have
pushed hard for the reform.
   On Saturday, De Mita referred to the snipers when addressing a
gathering of young Christian Democrats in the southern province of
Lecce.
   ``If the majority is no longer there, I'll have to take note of
it,'' he said. Journalists and other politicians took the remark to
mean he would resign if the reform measure fails.
   Snipers could be critical in the vote. Of the 630 deputies in
the chamber, 377 belong to coalition parties, normally giving the
government a comfortable margin, since 316 votes would be needed
for passage.
   However, on Friday, defecting deputies from coalition parties
joined with opposition Communists to water down the proposal by
adding exceptions which allow secret voting.
   After Friday's voting, the proposed exceptions included voting
on chamber rules, substantive constitutional changes, and special
investigative bodies, such as a national anti-Mafia commission.
   The government originally wanted the only exceptions to be
voting on fundamental liberties and issues of conscience, such as
abortion and genetic experimentation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     10-11 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Laundering,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Undercover Agents Arrest Suspects In Money-Laundering Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal undercover agents lured nine people
to a fake wedding and then arrested them in connection with an
international money-laundering scheme, a newspaper reported today.
   The U.S. Attorney's office has scheduled a news conference today
to discuss the case and announce the indictments handed up earlier
this month, according to unidentified sources cited by The Tampa
Tribune.
   Top drug enforcement officials from Britain and France have
investigated the case, a reputed $40 million money-laundering
operation, in cooperation with U.S. agents, the newspaper said.
   The nine people arrested Sunday were invited to the wedding by a
U.S. Customs agent playing the role of a drug financier seeking
advice on money laundering, the newspaper said
   ``It was a Cecil B. DeMille production,'' the unidentified
federal official said of the fictitious wedding.
   Five of the nine are past or present employees of the
multi-national Bank of Credit and Commerce International, said bank
attorney Marty Steinberg in Miami.
   ``We haven't been provided with any specific allegations. We're
anxiously waiting to see what the charges are,'' said Steinberg.
   Iqbal Ashraf, a Pakistani-born British citizen, opened the Tampa
branch of the bank in late 1984.
   The bank's major business was providing letters of credit and
helping finance international business deals, he said.
   Ashraf said the bank was founded in the early 1970s and is owned
by a holding company in Luxembourg.
   Federal officials declined to comment on the case Monday.
   The nine people arrested Sunday were being held in the
Hillsborough County Jail without bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
