<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachCleanup     10-11 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Cleanup,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Beaches Full of Plastic, Not Medical Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national beach cleanup has removed about 1.5
million pounds of garbage so far from shorelines, but the cleanup's
coordinator says the all-volunteer effort found that the country's
coasts ``aren't awash with medical waste.''
   Instead, Kathy O'Hara, a marine biologist with the Center for
Environmental Education, said Monday that volunteers mostly picked
up hundreds of tons of plastic, garbage from foreign countries and
traceable debris from cruise ships.
   Data from more than 1,800 miles of beaches in 16 states and
Puerto Rico has been collected, she said. Information from eight
other states and from Costa Rica remains to be compiled.
   ``We found medical wastes in most states, but we are not going
to see an overwhelming amount of it,'' O'Hara said, adding that
such wastes amount to a ``minuscule'' percentage of beach debris.
   This summer, hundreds of thousands of people stayed away from
East Coast beaches after reports of syringes and AIDS-tainted blood
in vials washed ashore. In New York alone, 7,000 items of medical
waste have been collected this year.
   But O'Hara said plastics are the No. 1 beach debris problem as
some types are not expected to disintegrate for up to 400 years. It
also can kill marine life when ingested or when fish and mammals
become entangled in it.
   About 40,000 volunteers have participated in the cleanup effort,
and O'Hara said in most cases they were very specific in
documenting what was found.
   Her organization's purpose in the cleanup is not only to clean
the beaches, but to compile a data base of how much and what kinds
of wastes wash ashore. She said many volunteers picked up items
that had on them the names of cruise ships. Thousands of deflated
balloons were found on the coastlines, evidence that promotional
helium balloon launches are not harmless events, she said.
   Next year, an international treaty that bans dumping plastics in
oceans takes effect. U.S. violators face up to a $25,000 fine. She
said the 1989 national cleanup, when compared to this year's data,
will help document whether the treaty is working.
   Last weekend, thousands of volunteers in New York, New Jersey
and Oregon helped pick up garbage on beaches. The final two states
to participate in the cleanup _ Hawaii and New Hampshire _ will
hold their efforts later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0643EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma-Economy     10-11 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Economy,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gasoline Prices Surge, Banking Only Partially Restored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices in the capital surged to
the equivalent of $33 a gallon today as government efforts to
restart Burma's two major oil refineries appear stalled.
   A gallon cost about $25 last week while the official price
before rationing was stopped Aug. 25 had been 58 cents.
   Official sources indicated that the refinery in nearby Syriam
had been damaged during a nationwide, anti-government strike and
would take some time to restore. The refinery at Mann, in central
Burma, also appeared not to be functioning.
   Military officers seized power Sept. 18, crushing a popular
uprising against 26 years of authoritarian rule and have since
attempted to revive the shattered economy and administrative
apparatus.
   The state-owned Working People's Daily said today that five
suburban banks would reopen Oct. 17 for partial business. Banks in
downtown Rangoon, closed for nearly two months, resumed operations
last week.
   The newspaper said each customer would only be allowed to
withdraw a maximum of $1,666 a week. They will be allowed to
deposit any amount.
   Most vehicles seen on the road belong to the military or
government which has been drawing on reserve fuel stocks.
   In Mandalay, 440 miles north of Rangoon, gasoline sold for $21 a
gallon although fuel prices in that central Burma city are normally
higher than those in the capital. Residents said the lower price
was accounted for by supplies of gasoline coming across the border
with China.
   Burma's economy, already in a downward spiral before the
political upheaval began last July, has come to a virtual
standstill. Protesting the military suppression, Japan, West
Germany, the United States and others have frozen aid to a country
where the per capita income is estimated at below $200 a year.
   ``You can argue that the annual half billion dollars in foreign
assistance was playing a major role in propping up the official
economy,'' a Western diplomat based in Rangoon said this week.
   Experts say Burma has exhausted its foreign exchange reserves
and owes more than $4 billion to foreign creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
