<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ElRukns-Fort     10-11 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-El Rukns-Fort,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial of El Rukn Leader Jeff Fort Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder trial of the leader of what has been
called one of the nation's deadliest street gangs and four
associates has begun amid tight security and fears of disruptions
by gang members.
   In opening arguments Monday, the prosecution said it would prove
its case against gang leader Jeff Fort and the others from the
testimony of three former El Rukns members involved in the shooting
of a rival gang member.
   But defense lawyers said the government's key witnesses were not
credible.
   Security at the Cook County Circuit Court was unusually tight.
Besides the standard metal detector in the front lobby, spectators
were asked to empty their pockets and were checked with hand-held
metal detectors at two other checkpoints.
   Inside the courtroom, the gallery was separated by a bulletproof
glass wall _ constructed for the trial _ from the judge, jury,
attorneys and defendants with their horde of guards.
   ``Let me introduce you to five members of an evil enterprise,''
prosecutor Randy Rueckert told the jurors.
   ``There's one issue in this case, and that's credibility,'' said
Mike McInerney, attorney for defendant Ray Ferguson. ``The defense
contends that these people can't be believed.''
   Fort's attorney, Tom Peters, said his client is a high-profile
scapegoat.
   ``This case is not about anything (Fort) did, or said or
thought. He's here because of who he is,'' Peters said.
   He said his client is a scapegoat for prosecution witnesses who
are cooperating in hopes of getting lighter sentences for their own
crimes.
   Fort, 41, is serving an 80-year federal term for conspiring to
commit acts of terrorism on the United States on Libya's behalf. He
is charged with his four co-defendants in the 1981 death of rival
gang member Willie ``Dollar Bill'' Bibbs, of the gang called the
Titanic Stones.
   Last year Fort and four El Rukns received terms ranging from
nine to 80 years for conspiring to get $2.5 million from Libya in
exchange for acts of terrorism in the United States. The government
said the group had offered to blow up planes and U.S. buildings for
Libya, but committed no terrorist acts.
   The El Rukns, named after the cornerstone of Islam's sacred
shrine in Mecca, claimed their organization is a religious one that
planned no violence and met with Libyans to raise money for a
mosque.
   About 50 of the 250 to 300 hard-core members of the South
Side-based gang have been charged or convicted of state and federal
crimes, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
