<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TropicalWeather     10-11 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecasters: Conditions Favor Strengthening Of Mid-Atlantic
Depression</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mid-Atlantic tropical depression moving slowly
toward the Caribbean may be gathering steam to become a tropical
storm, a forecaster says.
   Satellite pictures indicate the tropical depression could become
better organized today and grow to a tropical storm by late tonight
or early Wednesday, the National Hurricane Center reported.
   At 6 a.m. EDT, the depression was centered near 10.0 north
latitude and 45.6 west longitude, or about 950 miles east-southeast
of Barbados, moving west-northwest at 15 mph with winds near 35
mph, the center said.
   The same motion was expected for the next 24 hours, but
hurricane specialist Hal Gerrish said conditions were favorable for
strengthening into a named storm within 12 hours.
   The depression is the 17th of the Atlantic season, which runs
from June through November. Depressions become named tropical
storms when sustained winds reach 39 mph and hurricanes when winds
hit 74 mph.
   Four hurricanes have formed this season, including Hurricane
Gilbert, which killed more than 300 people and caused billions of
dollars damage as it ravaged Jamaica, the Cayman Islands and Mexico.
</TEXT>
