<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CouchPotato     10-11 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Couch Potato,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Networks To Air Warning Against Watching Too Much TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC and CBS will broadcast an animated public
service announcement in which two children become ``couch
potatoes'' while watching TV, as a warning to avoid too many hours
in front of the set, network spokesmen say.
   The 30-second cartoon is being offered to the three major
networks and 400 local stations by the American Academy of
Pediatrics.
   It is the academy's first public service announcement designed
to speak directly to children, said Jeff Molter, director of the
group's communications division.
   ``It says be choosy in what you watch, and we think it's good
for children to be choosy in what they watch,'' said CBS Broadcast
Group executive Matthew Margo.
   ABC's director of press relations, Janice Gretemeyer, said the
spot's message ``is consistent with the position that ABC has long
held, that children should be selective in their television
viewing.''
   An NBC spokesman said his network had not yet received the spot
for review.
   Over a toe-tapping instrumental backup and a chorus singing
``couch potato,'' the announcement tells children to ``avoid this
dread disease, be choosy in what you watch. ... Don't just plop in
front of the TV 'cause you've got nothing else to do.''
   It also admonishes children to ``watch out for overeating.''
   On screen, the boy couch potato pleads, ``Leave me alone, just
let me groove with my tube.''
   The girl couch potato gazes at the television and says, ``Got to
have that. ... Mamma, can I buy that?'' while chowing down on a
bowl of snacks.
   The spot ends with a family of couch potatoes turning back into
two children and their parents. The viewer hears: ``Don't be a
couch potato. Couch potato. Not me!''
</TEXT>
