<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Netherlands-American     10-11 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Netherlands-American,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Air Force Sergeant Imprisoned For Killing His Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court today sentenced a U.S. Air
Force sergeant to six years in prison for killing his wife.
   Sgt. Charles Donald Short, 34, of Highwood, Ill., was convicted
of murdering his wife Esin Hasturk, 31, his attorney, Leo Puts,
said.
   On March 25, Short beat and stabbed his Turkish-born wife to
death, then cut her body into pieces and hid them in plastic
garbage bags.
   The court also committed Short to a mental asylum as his
request, Puts said. The court ruling said there was a real danger
Short might commit similar offenses in the future, Puts said.
   ``The court took into consideration the way he disposed of the
remains of her (his wife's) body'' after the killing, Puts told The
Associated Press.
   Short, who had been serving with the Air Force's 32nd Tactical
Fighter Squadron near the central Dutch town of Soesterberg, killed
his wife because she threatened to leave him and take their
8-month-old son, Puts said.
   The couple had married in 1986 in the Turkish capital Ankara,
where Short was serving at the time.
   Short was arrested March 30 by U.S. military police at
Soesterberg, but handed over to Dutch authorities a day later.
   In July, Short won a Dutch court order barring his transfer back
to U.S. jurisdiction because he could have faced a death sentence
if convicted in the United States. Dutch law bans capital
punishment.
</TEXT>
