<1ST_LINE>u i PM-HamadiTrial     10-11 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hamadi Trial,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Describes Beating Of Stetham Aboard Hijacked TWA Jetliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was held captive on a
hijacked TWA jetliner testified today that a Navy diver killed
during the ordeal was beaten so severely he could barely walk.
   Sarah Ashmore, testifying during the murder and air piracy trial
of Mohammed Ali Hamadi, also said that Hamadi robbed her shortly
after the flight was commandeered June 14, 1985 on a flight from
Athens to Rome.
   Thirty-nine Americans were held on the plane for 17 days, and
Navy diver Robert Stethem, of Waldorf, Md., was beaten and shot to
death.
   Referring to the beating of Stethem, Ms. Ashmore said:
   ``He was mobile, but he was staggering in his walk and was being
supported by (chief flight attendant) Uli Derickson. He was moaning
and groaning and Uli was trying to keep him quiet.''
   Ms. Ashmore frequently pressed her hands against her head during
the testimony in the heavily guarded courtroom inside the
Preungesheim prison.
   Outside, police were on patrol, some with machine guns.
   Ms. Ashmore told the court she heard the shot that killed
Stethem but did not see who fired it.
   ``I heard the shot and the body drop, but I couldn't see
anything because the curtain (to first class) was shut,'' Ms.
Ashmore said.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, confessed to being one of the
two gunman who seized the plane but denied killing Stethem.
   Earlier in her testimony, Ms. Ashmore said Hamadi had robbed her.
   Looking directly at Hamadi, she said: ``This is the man who
searched me. This is the man who took my jewelry.''
   Court documents indicate that the hijackers stole jewelry, cash,
cameras and other valuables from passengers after the flight was
seized.
   Ms. Ashmore, 50, who spoke with an American accent, said she had
no doubt about the identities of the two hijackers.
   ``I spent a long time staring at them,'' she said.
   The other hijacker is still at large.
   Ms. Ashmore was not asked to reveal her nationality or residence
under court guidelines designed to protect witnesses.
   During the trial, which began July 5, witnesses have given
gruesome accounts of how Stethem died.
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem, have attended
each trial session. The elder Stethem usually takes notes during
the proceedings.
   The TWA jetliner was hijacked shortly after it left Athens.
During the hijacking, it was forced to land three times in Beirut
and twice in Algiers.
   Stethem was slain in the early hours of June 15, after the plane
landed in Beirut on its first return flight from Algiers.
   U.S. forensic expert Michael Clark told the court last week that
Stethem lived up to 10 minutes after he was shot and tossed out of
the plane.
   Another U.S. Navy diver, Clinton Suggs, was on the plane and
testified he heard the hijackers shoot Stethem and toss him onto
the runway still moaning.
   Pilot John Testrake told the court he believes Hamadi shot
Stethem but that he did not see who pulled the trigger.
   Hamadi was arrested Jan. 13, 1987 at Frankfurt airport after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   In the week after Hamadi's arrest, two West Germans were
kidnapped in Beirut in what officials said was an attempt to force
Hamadi's release.
   Hamadi's brother, Abbas Hamadi, who was arrested at Frankfurt
airport on Jan. 27, 1987 after a flight from Beirut, was convicted
by a Duesseldorf court in April on charges related to the
kidnappings of Alfred Schmidt and Rudolf Cordes. He was sentenced
to 13 years imprisonment.
   Both Alfred Schmidt and Rudolf Cordes have been freed.
</TEXT>
