<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GreenwoodTeacher     10-11 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greenwood Teacher,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protecting School's Pupils Was Foremost in Teacher's Mind, She
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher who followed a distraught
gunman through an elementary school and tried to persuade him not
to shoot says protecting the school's pupils was uppermost in her
mind.
   ``I was trying to be real calm,'' physical education teacher Kat
Finkbeiner told reporters Monday, two weeks after a youth went on a
rampage at Oakland Elementary School. ``I knew I had to be. Those
were kids in there _ they were helpless.''
   Two 8-year-old girls were fatally shot and seven children and
two teachers were wounded, including Mrs. Finkbeiner, who was hit
in the mouth and whose jaw remained wired shut.
   Despite her injury, Mrs. Finkbeiner ran in an 8-kilometer (about
5-mile) race this weekend and already has visited the school and
talked with the children. She said she cannot wait until her doctor
lets her return to work, which she hopes will be in the next couple
of weeks.
   The thought of children's questions about what happened doesn't
bother the 17-year teaching veteran. She said she wants to discuss
it openly with the children and help them heal.
   ``Kids will learn to get over this. Kids will talk about it,''
she said.
   Mrs. Finkbeiner said she was just sitting down for lunch shortly
before noon when a gunman walked into the cafeteria and opened fire
on a crowd of about 100 students and teachers. Teacher Eleanor
Hodge was one of the first hit by gunfire as she stood up and held
her hand up at the man.
   Mrs. Finkbeiner said she noticed one little girl left alone in
the cafeteria after the other children ran out the building's back
door. She said shielded the little girl with her body and pushed
her out the door while the gunman held the pistol on them.
   The gunman then left the lunchroom, and Mrs. Finkbeiner said she
followed him down the hall to a restroom, where he stopped to
reload. She tried to hold him in the restroom, but he forced his
way out and trained the gun on her.
   He told her, ``They are trying to kill me,'' she said.
   ``They are just little people. They are not going to hurt you,''
she replied.
   But the man walked away from her and entered a third-grade
classroom at the 600-student school.
   When Mrs. Finkbeiner arrived, the man had the revolver held to
the neck of an 8-year-old boy. She began talking to him, and he
pulled the gun away from the youngster.
   Details are fuzzy after that, she said.
   Apparently the man fired at her, striking her in the mouth and
shattering her jaw. He then began shooting at the pupils,
apparently aiming at children who screamed.
   One girl, Shequila Bradley, died soon after the shooting.
Tequila Thomas died several days later.
   Mrs. Finkbeiner said she carried Shequila to the school's office
and tried to stop the flow of blood from a wound to the girl's neck.
   James W. Wilson, 19, of Greenwood has been charged with murder
and assault and battery with intent to kill. He is undergoing
psychiatric evaluation in the state mental hospital in Columbia.
   Mrs. Finkbeiner said she was thankful to have survived and now
cherishes time with her husband and 2-year-old daughter.
   ``You can bet me that life means more to me,'' she said.
</TEXT>
