<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxGlance     10-11 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Glance,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some provisions of the catchall tax
bill on which a final Senate vote was expected tonight:
   _CORRECTIONS: The bill corrects hundreds of errors in the 1986
tax overhaul.
   _DIESEL: Farms and other businesses that use diesel fuel for
off-road purposes would be relieved from paying the federal tax and
then applying for a refund.
   _BILL OF RIGHTS: Taxpayers would be given new protections in
dealings with the Internal Revenue Service; the IRS would be barred
from using collections quotas to promote workers.
   _FREE-LANCERS: Certain writers, photographers and artists would
be allowed to deduct expenses even before a project produces income.
   _HIGHER EDUCATION: Families could avoid tax on interest earned
on U.S. savings bonds that are redeemed to pay for colllege or
vocational school.
   _TELEPHONE: No deduction would be allowed for the basic monthly
charge for a home telephone.
   _EXTENSIONS: Several expiring provisions would be extended for
brief periods, including an exemption for bonds that help
lower-income families buy their first home; a credit for increased
business research, and a benefit for workers who receive
employer-paid legal or educational assistance.
   _``HEIFER TAX'': Individual livestock farmers would be relieved
from this tax, which prohibits them from deducting costs of
producing an animal until the animal produces income.
