<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hostage-Home     10-11 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage-Home,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friends Say Former Hostage Plans To Return To Grand Junction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neighbors of a recently freed
Lebanon hostage cleaned up the yard of his house in preparation for
his homecoming and said they were eager to see him and his wife.
   Mithileshwar Singh, who was released eight days ago by Shiite
Moslem extremists after 21 months in captivity, told a friend he
will be returning here after a few more days of rest.
   ``He indicated he was staying in New York at a complex owned by
American Beirut University,'' said Sybil Curtis, who received a
telephone call from Singh and his wife on Monday. ``Dr. Singh says
they were coming home in a few days but just needed some time to
rest in seclusion.''
   Singh, 60, an Indian who is a resident alien of the United
States, was abducted Jan. 24, 1987, at Beirut Univerity College
with three American colleagues by a group calling itself the
Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine. He was chairman of
the school's business department.
   After his release Oct. 3, Singh was taken to Wiesbaden, West
Germany, for medical checks and debriefing at the U.S. military
hospital there. He left Sunday for the United States.
   Singh had taught at Western Colorado University, living in a
rented home. The house is now vacant and things have run down, said
neighbors, who decided to hold a yard clean-up Monday before Singh
and his wife, Lala Mani, arrive.
   ``The weeds have just really taken over. We felt we wanted to
get the yard up in shape because it was so nice when he lived
there,'' said Ginger Duffy.
   She said Singh and his wife were good neighbors and everyone on
the block would welcome him back.
   Three others kidnapped with Singh _ Jesse Turner, 41; Alann
Steen, 49; and Robert Polhill, 54 _ continue to be held. Six other
Americans also are being held in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
