<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CoolingCosts     10-11 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cooling Costs,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summer Cooling Costs Up in Northern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This summer's heat cost residents of the
northern plains states more than $40 each in added air conditioning
expense, according to a new government study released today.
   The typical American home spent $422 on electricity during the
May-September cooling season, but the expense ranged widely from
area to area, according to monthly climate impact assessments
issued by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   ``Very high summer temperatures in the Midwest and Northeast
were tempered by near-normal readings in the southern states, where
the cooling customers are concentrated,'' the report noted.
   Thus, the national summer electricity costs, which are largely
affected by air conditioning demand, were only 4 percent above
normal for the season.
   Even so, that spending totaled $17.4 billion, some $712 million
more than would have been expected had average summer weather
prevailed across the nation.
   The $422 average summer electricity bill for this year was $17
more than normal, the report said.
   Here is a region-by-region rundown of seasonal electricity
costs, per household, and the difference from what would have been
expected in normal weather.
   _West North Central, $434, $46 more than normal. Includes North
Dakota, South Dakota, Minnesota, Nebraska, Iowa, Kansas and
Missouri.
   _East North Central, $387, $40 more than normal. Includes
Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio.
   _Mid-Atlantic, $355, $23 more than normal. Includes New York,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   _Mountain, $371, $21 more than normal. Includes Montana, Idaho,
Wyoming, Nevada, Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico.
   _New England, $258, $15 more than normal. Includes Maine,
Vermont, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island.
   _East South Central, $438, $12 more than normal. Includes
Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Alabama.
   _South Atlantic, $473, $5 more than normal. Includes Maryland,
Delaware, District of Columbia, West Virginia, Virginia, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and Florida.
   _West South Central, $566, $2 more than normal. Includes
Oklahoma, Arkansas, Texas and Louisiana.
   _Pacific, $239, normal. Includes Washington, Oregon and
California.
   The monthly climate analysis does not calculate energy costs for
Alaska and Hawaii.
</TEXT>
