<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeTakeover     10-11 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Takeover,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Occupy Administration Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINFIELD, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Goddard College students
continued to occupy the school's administration building today
after pledging to remain until its demands on school and global
issues are met.
   Eight to 10 students took over Goddard's Community Center on
Sunday evening, and issued a list of demands on Monday. They were
still there this morning, said college President Jack Lindquist,
adding that he was considering calling in the police if the sit-in
continued.
   ``A police presence on the campus tends to excite some students,
and so I would prefer not to do that if I don't have to,'' he said.
   He said he and most staff members were sympathetic to the
students, though the college could do little about demands related
to national and world problems. So far, he said late Monday, the
protesters had not agreed to meet with him.
   The students' demands range from school issues, such as
increasing student participation in the administration of the
college and full disclosure of the school's financial records, to
freeing South African activist Nelson Mandela, ending homelessness
in America and stopping nuclear testing.
   Goddard, with an enrollment of 370, is regarded as a haven for
the counter-culture, praised by friends for innovation and damned
for what critics term academic laxity.
   ``We feel the time time has come to take serious and definitive
action to arrest apathy at our school, to arrest mediocrity, to
address why our school has become dysfunctional,'' a student
protester who gave his name as Zenzile said Monday. He spoke from
behind a second-floor doorway blocked with chairs and bedsprings.
   Lindquist said the demonstration was ``in many, many ways very
healthy'' and said most college faculty and staff members were
sympathetic with the students' goals.
   ``That's one of the reasons I have hope this thing will work
itself out,'' he said.
   He added: ``Of course, some of the staff are very irate about
being denied access to their place of work.'' A continuing protest
could delay staff paychecks, he said.
   While the students were inside the administration building,
another student group met throughout the day Monday to identify its
goals and see whether it could help resolve the grievances of the
protesters.
</TEXT>
