<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-DividedLove     10-11 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Divided Love,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sends Balloons Across Berlin Wall To Her Lover</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto BER2</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German authorities have succeeded in
separating an East Berlin man from his West Berlin lover, but that
hasn't stopped the woman from sending airborne love messages over
the Berlin Wall.
   To dramatize her plight this past weekend, Kerstin Vockert
launched balloons on the breeze to East Berlin carrying scraps of
paper with a message of love drawn from Shakespeare's Romeo and
Juliet to her fiance Peter Rozinat.
   The romantic message is from a German translation of
Shakespeare. The original English version of the passage reads:
``With love's light wings did I o'er-perch these walls ... for
stony limits cannot hold love out.''
   The couple's troubles began when they met a year ago in East
Berlin.
   Ms. Vockert, 29, said: ``It was love at first sight.''
   They soon decided to marry, but bureaucracy and East Germany's
tough emigration policies proved insurmountable, Ms. Vockert said.
   ``I am no longer allowed to go over and see him and Peter can't
get out,'' Ms. Vockert said.
   She said his requests to marry and leave the country have been
refused and that he was warned by authorities not to press the
issue.
   Ms. Vockert said officials denied the request because Rozinat
recently left the military and wasn't allowed to leave the country.
   But she added that authorities gave no indication how long
Rozinat will have to wait before he can join her in the West.
   ``The East German officials are treating us like criminals. We
are being lied to everywhere,'' Ms. Vockert said.
</TEXT>
