<2ND_LINE>PM-Cadets Stricken,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadet Stricken At Controversial Cop School Is Hospitalized Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the 16 cadets hospitalized
after strenuous physical training in the first week of a class at
the Agawam police academy was readmitted to a hospital today with
intestinal bleeding.
   Another cadet has been hospitalized since he collapsed from heat
stroke on the first day of a new class at the regional academy for
municipal police departments in western Massachusetts. Timothy
Shepard of Pittsfield underwent a liver transplant two weeks ago.
   In the wake of the allegations of abuses at the academy, the
state's chief medical examiner has reopened an investigation into
an earlier death of a cadet at an academy in eastern Massachusetts.
   A lawyer for the family of Cadet James Whitehouse of Braintree,
who died in 1985, said Monday he would call for an inquest if he
was not satisfied with investigations by the medical examiner's
office, the attorney general's office and the Criminal Justice
Training Council, which runs the state's six police academies.
   Cadet Joseph Metcalfe of Ludlow was in serious condition today
at the intensive care unit at Baystate Medical Center and may have
to undergo surgery, said spokesman Joseph Bradley.
   A nursing supervisor who asked not to be identified said early
this morning after Metcalfe was admitted that he was ``bleeding
heavily and is pretty bad.''
   However, Bradley said Metcalfe appeared to be improving.
   Metcalfe was among the class of 50 cadets who apparently
underwent a strenuous exercise regimen with little water the first
day of class, Sept. 19. He was treated for kidney problems that
required dialysis treatment.
   Metcalfe's boss, Ludlow Police Chief John Jorge, said Metcalfe
had been allowed back to the academy last week by his doctor.
   The state Department of Public Safety had suspended physical
punishment at the police academies, but it was unclear if physical
training had resumed. Spokesmen for the department could not be
reached this morning for comment.
   The nursing supervisor said he didn't know if the cadet's latest
health problems were related to his police training, but said he
had been healthy before beginning his training.
   ``Common sense would tell you there's probably some
relationship,'' the supervisor said.
   North Adams Mayor John Barrett III blasted a state agency
spokesman Monday for his suggestion that the state would not help
cover the medical bills of cadets who fell ill at the state-run
academy. One of the cadets from his town spent a week in the
hospital.
   ``The state has messed this whole thing up,'' Barrett said.
``We're self-insured, but we're looking for somebody to pick up the
tab for these guys if it doesn't cover 100 percent.''
   State Attorney General James Shannon, whose office is
investigating the illnesses, said the payment will be worked out
between the city and state.
</TEXT>
