<HEAD>Arson Attack On Pro-Independence Newspaper in Namibia</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ A fire set by arsonists
gutted the offices of a pro-independence newspaper, the paper's
staff said today.
   Gewn Lister, editor of The Namibian, said the weekly newspaper
would continue publishing despite the destruction of computers,
telephones and furniture in the fire Monday night.
   The Namibian, which has a circulation of 9,500, was founded
three years ago with financial assistance from the European
Economic Community.
   The newspaper has supported the South-West African People's
Organization, which wages a political and military campaign to end
South African rule over South-West Africa, commonly known as
Namibia.
   Reporters said a window of the newspaper office was broken and
kerosene-soaked packets were thrown inside.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
