<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArkansasTeachers     10-11 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arkansas Teachers,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike in Arkansas Idles 21,000 Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in Arkansas' second-largest
school district walked off the job today after the board of
education rejected a mediation committee's recommendation that they
be given a 3 percent raise.
   Classes for 21,000 students in the Pulaski County Special School
District were canceled. The district covers all the schools in the
county, where Little Rock is located, except the Little Rock and
North Little Rock schools.
   Elsewhere, teachers strikes in Pennsylvania, Illinois and
Michigan disrupted classes for an additional 14,000 students.
   The Arkansas strike was only the second in the state in recent
history.
   ``We are very disappointed with the decisions that have brought
us to this point,'' Pulaski Association of Classroom Teachers
spokesman Dan McElderry said as teachers gathered at a park before
sunrise for a rally.
   ``We'd much rather be in the classroom, doing what we've been
trained to do,'' said McElderry, chairman of PACT's Crisis
Committee. ``But we have taken all that we can take, and it's time
that the public knew that we intend to support what we've been
saying for the last several months.''
   On Monday night, the school board voted to deny the district's
1,300 teachers the recommended 3 percent raise, saying the system
couldn't afford it because it already faces a $1.9 million deficit.
The raise would have cost an estimated $1.03 million.
   Teachers had warned that they would strike if the recommendation
was rejected, and PACT President Joyce Elliott said that they would
picket every school in the district except an elementary school at
Little Rock Air Force Base. The union had said teachers would not
attempt to picket on federal property.
   School board president Sheryl Dunn said she was ``absolutely
devastated'' by the teachers' decision to strike. ``We tried so
hard to come to a point that we could agree on something to find
the money for the teachers. They just won't wait, and all I can say
is how desperately sorry I am.''
   School Superintendent Bobby Lester said the board would be
willing to reopen negotiations when more money is available for
teacher salaries. That could come if a $2.5 million lawsuit against
the state is settled.
   District voters rejected a property tax increase in May.
   The state with the most teachers on strike today was
Pennsylvania, where 600 teachers and 10,000 students were affected
in five districts. In the Spring-Ford district, the strike resumed
today after a 30-day cooling-off period expired. That strike
affected 200 teachers and 3,300 students.
   Illinois had one strike affecting 65 teachers and 1,000
students, while Michigan had one strike affecting 150 teachers and
3,000 students.
</TEXT>
