<HEAD>Former AP Newsman & Governor's Aide Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREEPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence A. Spiegel, a former Associated
Press newsman and aide to Gov. Joseph E. Brennan, has died at his
home after a long illness. He was 40.
   Spiegel, who died Monday, most recently was a partner in a
public relations firm in Portland and a member of the Wicked Good
Band, a folk group that formed when its members were in high school.
   A 1966 graduate of Deering High School in Portland, Spiegel
attended Amherst College before joining the Portland Press Herald
as a reporter in 1970. He joined The Associated Press in Augusta in
1972, going on to become correspondent in Springfield, Mass., in
1973, and in Providence, R.I., in 1974 before leaving the AP at the
end of that year.
   He served as press secretary, speechwriter and special assistant
to Brennan between 1978 and 1984.
   Spiegel is survived by his wife, Nancy Cohen Spiegel, and a son,
David Lee. Funeral services were set for Wednesday in Portland.
</TEXT>
