<HEAD>Tyson's Wife Hires New Divorce Lawyer; He Intends To Seek
Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `He said...', to CORRECT described to
prescribed.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new divorce lawyer for actress Robin
Givens says he would like to negotiate a settlement with her
husband, heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson.
   New York attorney Raoul Felder told The Associated Press on
Monday that Miss Givens loves the millionaire prizefighter, whom
she accused of beating her and threatening to kill her, but there
appears no chance to save the eight-month marriage.
   Miss Givens, who last week hired famed ``palimony'' lawyer
Marvin Mitchelson to oversee the breakup of her marriage, changed
lawyers Monday, hiring Felder.
   Meanwhile, Tyson charged that his wife and her mother had seen
to it that he was sedated on prescription drugs during his
appearance on ABC television late last month.
   ``They were giving the medicine to my friend ... to give to
me,'' Tyson told the New York Post in a story published today.
``They wanted him to make sure I took it.''
   He said the drugs had been prescribed by a psychiatrist to tame
his allegedly manic-depressive behavior. Other experts have
concluded that Tyson is not manic-depressive.
   On the television show, ``20-20,'' Tyson was seen sitting and
watching while Miss Givens claimed that he had abused her and made
married life ``torture ... pure hell.'' Two days after it was
aired, police were called to the couple's New Jersey mansion after
a reportedly violent episode involving Tyson, but no charges were
filed.
   Felder said in a telephone interview from New York the case
filed Friday in Los Angeles Superior Court would be handled by one
of his West Coast associates rather than by Mitchelson.
   ``I don't like to say `fired','' Felder said. ``She severed her
relationship (with Mitchelson) and hired me.''
   Sources, however, told the Daily News in New York that Miss
Givens and her mother, Ruth Roper, were angered because Mitchelson
agreed to appear on the CBS-TV ``This Morning'' program. A
Mitchelson spokesman said the appearance was canceled after the two
women ordered the lawyer to stop talking about the divorce, the
newspaper reported today.
   Mitchelson, who established a live-in companion's right to
alimony-type payments in the celebrated ``palimony'' case against
the late actor Lee Marvin, refused to comment on reports of his
firing. He referred questions to Felder.
   According to the New York newspaper, Miss Givens told friends
that she urged Felder to try to settle out of court.
   ``She said she wants to settle,'' an unidentified friend told
the Daily News. ``She said it could be easily resolved `if Michael
apologizes to me'.''
   Tyson, whose worth is estimated at $40 million, is looking look
for a home in Cleveland so he can work out at promoter Don King's
training camp east of the city, a spokesman for King said Monday.
   Tyson, who lives in New Jersey, and King met for much of the day
at King's home in Windsor, east of Cleveland, said spokesman Paul
Sciria.
   Friends reportedly are advising Tyson to try to have the
marriage annulled to protect his assets. Grounds for the annulment
would be that Miss Givens duped him into marriage by claiming she
was pregnant. Miss Givens denies that.
</TEXT>
