<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Contingency     10-11 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Contingency,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Review Award of Fees Lawyers' Fees in Kansas City
Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review the
award of more than $4 million in fees to lawyers who won a Kansas
City school desegregation lawsuit.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Missouri officials who
want to reduce the amount.
   State and city officials were held responsible for segregation
in the city school system, and were ordered in 1985 to spend $87.7
million to improve and integrate the schools.
   A federal judge then ordered the state to pay more than $1.7
million to Arthur A. Benson II of Kansas City, the leading attorney
for the suing students, and $2.3 million to the NAACP Legal Defense
Fund for its work.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the attorneys' fees
in January under a federal civil rights law which awards them to
lawyers who win such cases.
   The appeals court rejected claims by the civil rights lawyers
and by state officials who said, respectively, the fees were too
low or too high.
   Benson said he and his staff were not compensated adequately for
what was described as an extraordinary commitment of time and
energy.
   For three years Benson worked full-time on the case and devoted
substantial portions of five additional years to the suit. He said
he borrowed more than $730,000 to help pay the cost of the
litigation.
   Also, Benson argued that his fees should be higher because he
took the case on a contingency basis _ meaning he would get paid
only if he won the suit.
   But the appeals court noted that the judge who declined to order
higher fees said there was a ``high likelihood of success'' for the
segregation suit, minimizing the risk to Benson.
   One of the reasons for ``enhancing'' fees in contingency cases
is to assure there will be lawyers available to take difficult
civil rights suits.
   But the 8th Circuit court said there was insufficient proof the
Kansas City students would have had trouble finding another lawyer
if Benson had refused the case.
   Missouri officials argued that the legal fees were inflated
improperly because Benson and the Legal Defense Fund were paid
extra to compenate them for waiting years for their fees.
   The state appeal also said that the civil rights lawyers were
compensated improperly for the time they spent on segregation
claims not upheld by the courts. The fees should be less because
the lawyers achieved only partial success, they said.
   The state appeal said Kansas City should share in reimbursement
of the attorneys' fees.
   The appeals court rejected all of the state's claims.
   The Legal Defense Fund did not appeal to the Supreme Court.
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear Benson's appeal for
additional compensation.
   The case is Missouri vs. Jenkins, 88-64.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
