<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0435 10-11 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Accuses Dukakis of Scare Tactics on Foreign Investments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Bush speech in Seattle; picks up pvs
5th graf bgng, The campaign.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush accused Democratic rival
Michael Dukakis today of being ``willing to scare people'' for
political gain by engaging in ``protectionist demagoguery'' about
foreign investments in the United States.
   In a prepared speech for Seattle University Business School
students, the vice president said Dukakis is ``stoking fears about
foreign influence'' in the United States.
   ``My opponent needs an issue and he's willing to scare people to
find it, so like the `Know Nothing Party' a century before him,
he's turned to fear of foreigners,'' Bush said.
   ``He's not a Know Nothing _ he knows better. But perhaps he's a
feel nothing candidate, or maybe, with this later flip-flop, he's
become a believe nothing candidate,'' he said.
   ``Frankly, I've been surprised at my opponent's recent turn to
protectionist demagoguery. I don't think he really believes it. He
ran against this so-called economic nationalism in the primaries.''
   Bush, who is heading for Los Angeles for his second and final
debate with the Democratic nominee Thursday night, also promised to
``throw the book at insider traders and other white-collar
criminals.''
   ``We must not let Wall Street steal from Main Street,'' he said.
   Bush added that most of those who work on Wall Street are
``honest, hard-working people'' and that ``much of the money made
there is recycled to foundations to help the poor, universities and
other worthy causes.''
   On Monday in Trenton, N.J., Bush portrayed Dukakis as soft on
crime and promised as president to show more sympathy for victims
of crimes than for criminals.
   ``I think there is something very wrong when there is so much
sympathy for criminals and very little left over for victims,''
Bush said, who has made a major campaign issue of the Massachusetts
prison furlough system under Dukakis as governor.
   The campaign trip to the West Coast begins an eight-day swing
concentrating on California, the nation's biggest Election Day
prize with 47 electoral votes.
   Campaigning before Thursday's debate will be light to give Bush
time to prepare for his last face-to-face confrontation with his
rival. However, the GOP nominee is planning another tough-on-crime
event in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
   Targeting Democratic ``swing voters'' in New Jersey, which is
seen as a state winnable by either candidate, Bush proposed on
Monday to increase criminal penalties and give victims an expanded
role in criminal proceedings.
   Bush said victims of crime ``should have the statutory right to
be informed of, be present and be heard at every critical stage of
the criminal justice process.''
   He also called for expanding a federal fund created to
compensate victims of crimes.
   ``I'm going to bring an attitude to the White House that has
more sympathy for the victims of crime than for the criminals,''
the vice president said in his Columbus Day address.
   Bush had been speaking at length about the gang and drug
problems, although none of his campaign stops have been in inner
cities and heavily minority communities where those problems are
most rampant.
   As to why Bush has visited almost all-white, suburban
communities while hitting the anti-crime theme, press secretary
Sheila Tate said, ``The strategy is determined by the political
numbers crunchers that know where the vice president has to go to
have the greatest impact on that state.''
   The speech today was dealing with white-collar crime and thus
the business-student audience was appropriate, Ms. Tate said.
   On Monday, Bush walked for a few blocks in an Italian-American
neighborhood in Trenton, stumping for ethnic votes.
   Bush's political director, Rich Bond, said the New Jersey swing
was aimed at Democrats who crossed party lines to vote for
President Reagan in 1980 and 1984, a group being ardently courted
by both Bush and Dukakis.
   ``We're going after Reagan Democrats. You're not going to see
many Republicans here,'' said Bond.
   Bush aides were heartened by a poll in Monday's Bergen Record
showing him leading Dukakis by eight percentage points in New
Jersey.
   Earlier, Bush told reporters traveling with him aboard Air Force
Two that he favors review of the federal prison furlough program,
although he has no specific revisions in mind. ``I just ... want to
be sure it never slips into the Massachusetts model,'' he said.
   Bush's criticism of the program, which until modified allowed
convicted murderers to be released on weekend passes, has prompted
Dukakis to criticize the federal furlough system.
   And Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen, in a
statement released Monday, criticized Bush's comments.
   ``After 2818 days of sitting on the sidelines, George Bush has
finally admitted that there is something wrong with a federal
furlough program that gives 45-day vacations to drug traffickers,''
Bentsen said.
   ``We don't need another review; we need the vice president to
take responsibility for his failure in the fight against drugs and
crime.''
</TEXT>
