<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0526 10-11 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Opponents Urge Boycott as Municipal Elections Begin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, ``The government...'' to
identify those who signed letter. Pickup 8th graf pvs,
``Information Minister...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight academics and
clergymen violated emergency regulations today by urging people to
boycott nationwide municipal elections.
   The first votes were cast Monday, and the state radio said
voters ``showed great interest.''
   The elections for racially segregated municipal councils are
scheduled by law for Oct. 26, but the government passed an
emergency bill allowing people to begin voting on Oct. 10 in a
system called ``prior voting.''
   The government has said the early voting, which lasts until Oct.
22, is designed to make it easier for people to vote in rural areas
and to cut down on the possibility of harassment.
   In several black townships, no candidates are running for
office, and in others only one candidate has sought each post.
Candidates' homes have been fire-bombed and in Soweto, the largest
black township in the country, a candidate was killed.
   The government has billed the municipal elections as a major
move toward extending democracy because for the first time all
races will vote at the same time. The Bureau for Information has
conducted an extensive television, billboard and newspaper
advertising campaign, urging people to participate in the elections.
   The government issued an emergency regulation making it illegal
to call for a boycott of elections, print advertisements or quote
statements carrying that view. But Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu
of Cape Town, and the Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World
Alliance of Reformed Churches, have joined other church leaders in
repeatedly defying the regulation, calling publicly for a boycott
of elections they say will entrench apartheid.
   Tutu, Boesak and other church leaders, black and white, were
among the 38 people signing today's statement urging a boycott.
Others included the leader of an anti-evictions group and eight
faculty members from the University of South Africa, one of the
world's largest correspondence universities.
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe said Friday that
Tutu, Boesak and other prominent church leaders who violated the
law by calling for boycotts would not be arrested because such an
action would give South Africa bad publicity. But lesser known
clergymen and election opponents have been detained.
   The black majority of 26 million has no vote in Parliament. Less
than 10 percent of blacks voted in the last municipal elections in
1984, which preceded two years of unrest and more than 2,000 deaths.
   The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said today,
``voters throughout the country showed great interest in prior
votes.'' It gave no voting figures.
   ``The election in fact began Monday,'' said Sam Basch, an
elections spokesman for the government's Bureau for Information. He
said that until Oct. 22, voters can go to any municipal office,
show their identification, fill out an application for an early
ballot, mark the ballot there and place it in a ballot box. Then
the voting will stop for four days and resume on Oct. 26, the
official election day.
   Government opponents say the new system is open to abuse, since
there is no secret voting booth, no monitoring of the voting by
delegates from various parties and no immediate counting of the
ballots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
