<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Boeing     10-11 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Boeing,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Kill Age-Bias Lawsuit Against Boeing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to kill a
lawsuit charging the Boeing Company with illegal age bias because
it bars pilots from active flight status when they reach 60.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that reinstated
the suit.
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission sued Boeing in 1984
in federal court in Seattle, charging that Boeing's policy of
removing its pilots from active flight status at age 60 violates
federal law.
   Boeing, one of the world's leading jet manufacturers, defended
the policy as a ``bona fide occupational qualification'' exception
to the law.
   The company rested its case on a regulation of the Federal
Aviation Administration that requires commercial pilots to be under
60.
   A federal judge threw out the suit before trial, ruling there is
almost ``perfect congruity'' between the FAA rule and Boeing's
policy.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the suit in
April, ordering a jury trial.
   Boeing said its pilots perform a variety of flight duties. They
conduct extensive flight operations to test the design and
performance of jets, and also fly passenger flights for commercial
airlines and on corporate jets, the company said.
   Boeing said test flying involves numerous risky procedures, such
as purposely depressurizing aircraft and shutting down engines or
other systems to determine if they will restart in mid-air.
   The FAA in 1959 said pilots must be under 60 on commercial
flights. The policy is based on the belief that after 60 skills
deteriorate, and that exceptions cannot be allowed due to the
difficulty in predicting individual performance or likely
disabilities.
   The 9th Circuit court said the ``critical issue of fact in this
case was the detectability on an individual basis of deterioration
in a Boeing pilot aged 60 or over that might diminish that pilot's
capacity to discharge safely his or her duties.''
   The appeals court added, ``This was an issue for the jury to
decide if the facts were disputed or for the (trial) court if they
were not.''
   The 9th Circuit court said the judge should not dismiss the suit
unless the dismissal were based on the evidence ``no reasonable
jury could have decided that it was practical to test pilots age 60
and over for disabling conditions.''
   The appeals court also noted that before Boeing adopted its age
policy in 1980 pilots over 60 had flown for the company without
incident.
   It also cited a 1985 Supreme Court ruling that said the FAA's
age-60 rule does not automatically cover flight engineers for
commercial airlines.
   The appeals court added that the FAA's rule has never been
tested specifically in court as to whether being under 60 is a bona
fide occupational requirement even for commercial pilots.
   Boeing said the appeals court ruling places the company _ and
possibly commercial airlines _ between two conflicting federal
agency interpretations of federal law. Its appeal said the FAA
believes accurate individual testing of pilots over 60 cannot be
done and the EEOC says it must be done.
   The Reagan administration urged the Supreme Court to reject
Boeing's appeal.
   Justice Department lawyers noted, for example, that the FAA
itself and the Navy do not force their own pilots to stop flying at
age 60.
   The FAA rule for commercial pilots is evidence in Boeing's favor
but is not the only evidence a jury could weigh, the government
lawyers said.
   The case is Boeing vs. EEOC, 88-53.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
