<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalFires     10-11 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Fires,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Doused Three Blazes That Burned 2,425 Acres</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEMET, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters have doused three Southern
California fires that blackened 2,425 acres and injured two
firefighters, one of them severely, officials said today.
   Arson, a poorly tended campfire and sparks kicked up by target
practice shots were blamed for the blazes, which were aggravated by
dry desert wind and temperatures topping 100 degrees.
   A Riverside County fire near Winchester blackened 1,800 acres
after a campfire spread to brush Sunday, said California Department
of Forestry spokesman Tim Span.
   About 300 firefighters surrounded the blaze Monday morning, and
it was extinguished at midnight. A female jail inmate digging a
fireline suffered burns over a small area of her body, Span said.
   The last hot spots were mopped up Monday evening on a 425-acre
fire believed to have been intentionally set along a road Sunday
near Hemet, about 85 miles southeast of Los Angeles, CDF
spokeswoman Joanne Evans said.
   CDF Capt. Dave Howard was caught in a firestorm while battling
the blaze and suffered severe burns on about half his body, CDF
spokesman Tim Span said. Howard, one of about 200 firefighters
working the blaze, was listed in critical but stable condition at
Sherman Oaks Community Hospital in Los Angeles, Span said.
   In San Bernardino County near Hesperia, 65 miles northeast of
Los Angeles, a 200-acre brushfire, sparked Sunday by target
practice bullets ricocheting off scrap metal, briefly threatened
homes before it was encircled early Monday and put out later in the
day, CDF spokeswoman Holly Kress said.
</TEXT>
