<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-RapeVictim 1stLd-Writethru a0577 10-11 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Rape Victim, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0577,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Decide Rape Victim Identification Issue in Florida Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 16-26, In other action, with other cases</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states may bar publication or broadcast of a rape victim's
name that reporters get from law enforcement officials.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by a weekly Florida
newspaper ordered to pay $97,500 to a rape victim for what the
paper said was inadvertent publication of her name.
   Lawyers for The Florida Star, a newspaper primarily serving the
black community in Jacksonville, said it will be put out of
business if forced to pay the award.
   The Star obtained the rape victim's name from a report posted by
the Jacksonville Sheriff's Department in its press room in October
1983.
   The newspaper said a reporter trainee copied the sheriff's
report, including the victim's name. It was published even though
the newspaper has a policy against identifying rape victims.
   ``There was no factual dispute that the name was published in
error and in violation of the Star's own policy,'' the newspaper
said.
   Publication of the name violated a Florida law that makes it a
misdemeanor to publish or broadcast names or other identifying
information of ``the victim of any sexual offense.''
   The victim of the 1983 assault sued Sheriff Dale Carson and the
Star. She was awarded $2,500 from the sheriff and $97,500 from the
newspaper.
   Lawyers for the Star said a 1986 state appeals court ruling that
upheld the award ignored a series of Supreme Court decisions,
including a 1975 ruling that states may not outlaw the broadcast of
rape victims' names.
   In that case, the victim's name was used in an open court
hearing in which five men pleaded guilty to the attack.
   In that 1975 ruling, the Supreme Court said the Constitution's
First Amendment does not allow states to ``impose sanctions for the
publication of truthful information contained in official court
records open to public inspection.''
   Lawyers for the Florida rape victim, a nurse's assistant with
four children, said there is a distinction between court records
and the report provided by the Jacksonville sheriff.
   The lawyers said the sheriff mistakenly made the victim's name
available and therefore ``the report was not a public record in the
sense that it was available for inspection by the public.''
   The Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press and the Times
Herald Printing Co., publisher of The Dallas Times Herald, urged
the Supreme Court to overturn the Florida court ruling.
   The justices, seeking assurances that they have authority to
rule in the case, sent it back to the Florida Supreme Court last
December. The state court then removed any procedural obstacle.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Refused to kill a lawsuit charging the Boeing Company with
illegal age bias because it bars pilots from active flight status
when they reach 60.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that reinstated
the suit.
   _ Refused to revive a challenge to the way Laurence A. Tisch
became president of CBS Inc.
   The justices, without comment, let stand ruling that Tisch's
assumption of power did not amount to a transfer of control
requiring prior approval by the Federal Communications Commission.
   _ Agreed to review the award of more than $4 million in fees to
lawyers who won a Kansas City school desegregation lawsuit.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Missouri officials who
want to reduce the amount.
   _ Allowed California officials to block a private club's
beach-front development unless the club vows not to discriminate
against minorities and women.
   The court, citing a lack of a substantial federal issue,
rejected arguments that the anti-bias requirement violates club
members' right to associate with whom they please.
   _ Turned down an appeal by former New York Yankees pitcher Art
Ditmar who was mistakenly identified in a beer commercial as having
surrendered a famous World Series homerun .
   The court, citing a lack of jurisdiction, let stand a ruling
that wrongly being branded a ``gopher ball'' pitcher generally is
not a serious enough matter to sustain a libel lawsuit.
   The rape-victim case is The Florida Star vs. B.J.F., 87-329.
 
</TEXT>
