<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Gathers     10-11 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Gathers,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Reinstating Death Sentence of South Carolinian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating the death sentence of South Carolina murderer Demetrius
Gathers, convicted of a 1986 killing in a Charleston city park.
   The justices said they will review a South Carolina Supreme
Court ruling that threw out Gathers' sentence last June 6.
   Gathers was convicted of killing Richard Haynes, 32, during a
Sept., 13, 1986, attack in which Haynes was beaten and stabbed.
   The state's highest court upheld Gathers' conviction but ruled
that during the sentencing trial jurors wrongly were told that
Haynes was a religious man.
   The state court said such comments by a prosecutor focused on
the victim's characteristics, which it said is prohibited by a 1987
Supreme Court decision in a Maryland case.
   In it, the justices ruled that a murder's impact on the victim's
family may not be considered when the killer faces a possible death
sentence.
   The justices also said in the 1987 ruling that there is no
justification for letting a life-or-death sentencing decision
``turn on the perception that the victim was a sterling member of
the community rather than someone of questionable character.''
   In Gathers' case, the South Carolina court said the prosecutor
acted unconstitutionally ``by focusing extensively on the personal
characteristics of the victim.''
   The state court said the prosecutor's remarks ``conveyed the
suggestion (Gathers) deserved a death sentence because the victim
was a religous man and a registered voter.''
   In his closing argument, the prosecutor told jurors that among
the things found at the murder scene were various religious items
and a voter registration card belonging to Haynes.
   ``We know from the proof that ... Haynes was a religious person
... (he) believed in this community. He took part,'' the prosecutor
had said.
   In the appeal acted on today, South Carolina Attorney General T.
Travis Medlock argued that the state court misinterpreted the
justices' 1987 decision.
   And he urged the justices to reverse their 1987 ruling, stating,
``The Eighth Amendment (banning cruel and unusual punishment) does
not preclude comments on victim characteristics related to a
crime.''
   The case is South Carolina vs. Gathers, 88-305.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
