<HEAD>Four Opposition Parties Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four opposition parties merged Tuesday
as the People's Party and chose a bitter adversary of Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi as its leader, news reports said.
   V.P. Singh, who once served as finance and defense minister in
Gandhi's Cabinet, was chosen unanimously to head the new party
after a meeting of opposition leaders in the southern city of
Bangalore.
   Singh was dismissed from the Cabinet in 1987, and newspapers
said he was fired for investigating alleged kickbacks on lucrative
defense contracts. He later was dismissed from Gandhi's Congress
Party.
   ``I am happy and proud that a new baby has been born,'' S.R.
Bommai, chief minister of the southern Karnataka state told members
of the new party. ``It is a very, very healthy baby.''
   The new party is made up of the old People's Party, as well as
the Lok Dal, Jan Morcha and the Socialist Congress parties.
   On May 1, 1977, four regional groups merged to become the
People's Party. Later that year, the party ousted the ruling
Congress Party and governed India for 29 months.
   Gandhi must call elections before January 1990.
