<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-FarmWorkers     10-11 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Farm Workers,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Awards $2 Million For Migrant Retraining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department awarded $2 million in
emergency grants Tuesday to programs in four states for retraining
migrant and seasonal farm workers whose jobs were lost to the
effects of the summer drought.
   The funds are from a special $5 million account established
under the Job Training Partnership Act when it became clear that
the dry summer weather would have a devastating effect on fall
harvest employment.
   ``These workers are caught in an adverse situation beyond their
control,'' said Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin. ``We want to
provide them with the necessary skills training so they can quickly
return to being productive.''
   Five areas of Texas will get a total of $1.5 million to assist
some 1,100 migrant workers returning to the state, their home in
the winter, with little or no income because of the effects of the
drought on crops. The five areas are Rural Costal Bend, Middle Rio
Grand, South Texas, Cameron County and Hidalgo and Wallacy Counties.
   Oregon will get $824,500 to help up to 360 of some 12,000
surplus farm workers because water shortages in the eastern part of
the state decimated sugar beet, onion, potato and bean crops.
   The Rural Alabama Development Corp. was awarded $200,000 to help
up to 155 seasonal farm workers. The money will go to providing
them with child care, health and medical services and, in some
cases emergency shelter, clothing and food while they are in
on-the-job training programs.
   Indiana's Department of Human Services will receive $169,760 to
finance, among other things, a food pantry for farm worker families
in Central Indiana through offices in Kokomo, Anderson and South
Bend. Most of the money will be aimed at vocational skill training
for migrant and seasonal workers wanting to switch to full-time
employment.
   Previous grants totaling $1.8 million from the emergency drought
job-training fund job training were awarded last month to JTPA
agencies in Arkansas, Idaho, Iowa, Minnesota, Ohio, South Dakota
and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
