<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland     10-11 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Demand Legalization of Banned Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of students at universities
nationwide today rallied to demand legalization of the outlawed
Independent Students' Association and Solidarity.
   Demonstrations were held at about 30 universities and colleges
in major cities throughout Poland, said Piotr Sosnowski, an
association spokesman in Gdansk.
   The government said it ``disapproved'' of the demonstrations and
accused students of trying to ``torpedo'' upcoming talks between
authorities and opposition leaders.
   The talks were promised by the government after a series of
pro-Solidarity strikes ended in August. They are expected this
month, but no date has been set.
   About 1,500 students gathered at noon at Warsaw University. They
raised banners for their organization and for the Solidarity trade
union federation and chanted the names of the two banned groups.
   Earlier, members of the officially recognized Polish Students
Association distributed leaflets saying one students' organization
could not represent all students.
   Supporters of the other student group burned the leaflets and
said the official organization was blocking their efforts to gain
legalization.
   Polish authorities legally registered the Independent Students'
Association in Feb. 1981, but it was banned shortly after the
martial law crackdown in Dec. 1981. Solidarity was also banned then.
   The Warsaw University students are demanding amendments to the
law on higher education to give them more autonomy; lifting of
obligatory courses in the Russian language; and reform of the
required military training course.
   Professor Grzegorz Bialkowski, the rector of Warsaw University,
which has the most politically active student body in Poland, said
in an interview last week that he favors legalization of the
Independent Students' Association because it would make it easier
to negotiate with the students. ``They are not criminals and they
should be allowed to be active,'' he said.
   The government and the state-run press have criticized the
student demonstrations, saying they could hinder agreement between
the authorities and the opposition.
   ``We treat students' demonstrations as excesses which are the
symtom of bad intentions of the organizers and political immaturity
of particpants,'' government spokesman Jerzy Urban said at his
weekly news conference today.
   ``Those demonstrations are being organized right before the
debates of the round table. So they are adventurous behavior aimed
against national accord, and in fact an attempt to torpedo the
round table and show arrogance to all the participants,'' Urban
said.
   A week ago, a small group of Warsaw University students began a
daily picket in front of the barracks where the military training
course is held, and more than than 300 have joined the protest,
said Mariusz Kaminski, one of the organizers.
   The banned student group also set up a human rights monitoring
group. Students who were detained or beaten at an alternative
demonstration on Friday were urged to contact the group.
   The demonstrators at Warsaw University dispersed peacefully
after about 45 minutes. Organizers had asked the students not to
continue the rally on the streets outside the university grounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
