<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trees-Greenhouse     10-11 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trees-Greenhouse,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Power Company To Finance Guatemalan Forests To Offset
Greenhouse Toll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0617 to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent electric power generator said
Tuesday it would help finance 385 square miles of forests in
Guatemala to offset the carbon dioxide emissions expected from a
Connecticut generating plant over the next 40 years.
   Carbon dioxide is the principal gas responsible for the expected
``greenhouse effect'' warming of the earth. It is an inevitable
byproduct of combustion of all fossil fuels.
   Applied Energy Services Inc. of Arlington, Va., said it would
give $2 million to a project aimed at planting almost 52 million
trees in plantations and small farmer woodlots.
   The Peace Corps, the U.S. Agency for International Development,
CARE and the government of Guatemala also will contribute cash or
services to the project.
   Applied Energy Services is building a coal-fired 180-megawatt
plant at Uncasville, Conn., which will sell electricity under
contract to Connecticut Light & Power Co. when it goes into service
in about a year.
   Though a mature forest neither absorbs nor releases carbon
dioxide on balance, the widespread destruction of tropical forests
and burning of their wood probably accounts for about a fifth of
all releases of carbon dioxide to the atmosphere, said Gus Speth,
president of the World Resources Institute, a Washington-based
environmental research organization which helped Applied Energy
Services organize the reforestation project.
   A growing forest, on the other hand, absorbs large amounts of
carbon dioxide in producing woody tissue.
   Applied Energy Services said it estimated that two square miles
of forest would be needed to offset each megawatt of capacity
during the life of the project. The project area in Guatemala is
slightly larger than the 360 square miles this rule of thumb would
require.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
