<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-PlainDealer     10-11 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Plain Dealer,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Sex Discrimination Case Against Cleveland
Plain Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
16-year-old sex discrimination case against the Cleveland Plain
Dealer.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out
the lawsuit because of delays by the Cleveland Newspaper Guild and
others in pursuing the case.
   Justices Byron R. White and Harry A. Blackmun voted to hear
arguments in the case. But the votes of at least four justices are
required to grant such review.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a 10-5 ruling last
February, said it would be unfair to permit the newspaper to be
sued after such a long delay.
   The appeals court also rejected arguments by the union and the
women who accused the Plain Dealer of bias that the newspaper had
``unclean hands'' because it contributed to the delays.
   The appeals court said that while throwing out such a civil
rights suit is an extreme measure it is necessary ``when the
prejudice to the defendant can be avoided in no other way.''
   The case began in April 1972 when the newspaper guild, on behalf
of its female members, filed a charge with the federal Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission.
   The complaint accused the newspaper of sex discrimination in its
handling of merit pay, promotions and assignments and in other
employment practices.
   Four years passed before the EEOC began its investigation.
Another six years elapsed before the union and its members sued the
Plain Dealer in federal court.
   In 1976, the Plain Dealer refused to surrender personnel records
sought by the federal agency. In 1980, the newspaper said the
documents no longer were available.
   The 6th Circuit court said the newspaper's lack of cooperation
with the commission's investigation does not explain the initial
four-year delay in launching the probe.
   The appeals court noted that the trial judge who dismissed the
suit initially had found that ``the EEOC's notice to defendant to
retain personnel records was too ambiguous to serve as a valid
command.''
   The case is Cleveland Newspaper Guild vs. Plain Dealer, 87-1864.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
