<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Klinghoffer     10-11 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Klinghoffer,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Hear Case Involving Achille Lauro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to hear a case
involving damage suits brought against the owners of the Italian
cruise ship Achille Lauro as a result of a 1985 PLO hijacking in
which American passenger Leon Klinghoffer was killed.
   The question brought before the court is whether American courts
must respect a provision printed on the line's passenger tickets
that require ``any controversy'' to be heard before courts in
Naples.
   Klinghoffer, 69, of New York, traveling with his wife Marilyn,
was killed by the four pirates who took over the ship, firing
Soviet-made submachine guns and brandishing hand grenades and other
explosives. The man, who was Jewish, had been paralyzed on the
right side by a stroke several years earlier and was in a
wheelchair.
   The U.S. District Court in New York denied a motion by the Lauro
Line in 1987 to dismiss all the damage suits for lack of authority
because of the provision on the ticket. The U.S. Court of Appeals
dismissed the ship line's appeal.
   Lauro Lines, saying that five courts of appeals have issued
conflicting opinions on a clause on which ``forum'' can hear a
case, asked the high court to decide.
</TEXT>
