<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Thatcher Bjt   10-11 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher, Bjt,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tories Open Convention in Resort Overshadowed by Tight Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Conservative Party opened its
convention Tuesday, shadowed by massive security and memories of an
Irish Republican Army attempt to kill Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher in the same town four years ago.
   The four-day annual convention began on a sour note as delegates
booed the socialist mayor of Brighton for implying in her welcoming
speech that the Tories' free-market doctrines were making Britons
greedy and uncaring.
   Defense Secretary George Younger pledged to retain Britain's
independent nuclear deterrent by deploying U.S.-made Trident
sea-launched missiles in the 1990s.
   He ridiculed the opposition Labor Party's commitment to
unilateral nuclear disarmament, reaffirmed at Labor's convention
last week, saying it would ``leave us totally vulnerable to nuclear
attack.''
   Younger said there was no sign that Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev had slowed the pace of military buildup, adding: ``By all
means let us welcome the new atmosphere and the smile of Mr.
Gorbachev, but let us recognize the military realities that lie
behind that smile.''
   The convention was back in Brighton for the first time since
1984, when an IRA bomb planted in Mrs. Thatcher's hotel killed five
people. The prime minister narrowly escaped harm.
   Before joining the convention, Mrs. Thatcher attended a private
memorial service at the nearby Church of St. Paul's for the bombing
victims and unveiled a plaque inscribed, ``They paid the price of
freedom.''
   Memories of the bombing surged back anew when former party
chairman Norman Tebbit arrived on the conference floor pushing a
wheelchair carrying his wife Margaret, who was paralyzed for life
in the explosion.
   Delegates stood and cheered the couple.
   More than 1,500 police officers were drafted into the normally
staid resort town on the southern coast in the biggest security
operation ever mounted for a British political conference.
   Civil overflights were banned, a Royal Navy destroyer patrolled
the shore and delegates were forced to line up early outside the
conference hall and endure rigorous security checks.
   The bomb damage to the Grand Hotel has been repaired, and as
Mrs. Thatcher checked in Monday night she declared that her
presence there was a gesture of non-surrender to terrorism.
   The IRA issued a statement expressing delight at ``the hysteria
and the expense surrounding the security of Mrs. Thatcher and the
Tories at their Brighton conference.''
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to rid
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland of British rule and unite it
with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who turns 63 Thursday, returned to Brighton with
her dominance of British politics looking even more secure than
four years ago.
   Elected in 1979 and 16 months into her third successive
five-year term, she is the longest continuously serving British
prime minister this century.
   Despite rising inflation and interest rates and a record trade
deficit, the Conservatives arrived in Brighton with a healthy
five-point lead in polls over the opposition Labor Party.
   The proceedings opened with greetings from Mayor Pat Hawkes, a
Laborite, who was booed when she urged the Tories not to forget the
needy in ``an orgy of getting and spending.''
   ``As you walk around in Brighton,'' she declared to mounting
heckling, ``look behind the facade of wealth and opulence and think
about the people over whom the government rules _ not just the
haves but the have-nots.''
   A theme of this year's conference is the Tories' need to restore
their image as a party that cares for the underdog, after years of
budget-slashing and union-curbing aimed at shaking Britain out of
its economic malaise.
   Many Tories feel that with unemployment finally falling, income
tax slashed and the economy booming, they should turn to social
issues.
   Michael Heseltine, a former Cabinet minister tipped as a
possible Thatcher heir, urged the government to spend the cash from
the ``richer Britain'' it had created on inner cities and the
environment.
   ``We want a fair distribution of ... wealth between the
privileged and the less privileged _ a generous society,''
Heseltine told a convention meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Thief'sConscience     10-11 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thief's Conscience,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Faces Hearing on Robbery Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENTWOOD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A philosophy student whose conscience
apparently bothered him was arrested after he balked at keeping the
booty from a shoe store robbery, police said.
   John P. Breuker, a 20-year-old part-time student at Calvin
College, was released Monday on $500 bond after being charged with
attempted armed robbery.
   Jane Kelm, manager of Payless Shoesource in the Grand Rapids
suburb, said a robber Saturday night handed her a note that said:
   ``Don't look at me. If you do, I'll kill you. I have a gun.
Calmly, quietly open the drawer and put all the bills in (the) bag.
The gun is ready and it's aimed at you. Just do everything the way
I want it and don't be stupid. Remember, don't look at me.''
   Kelm said she gave the thief an unspecified amount of money and
he fled.
   Police say Breuker called authorities about four hours later and
said he would drop off the money at a gas station.
   ``We're thinking he had second thoughts and decided to give the
money back with the idea that he'd get out of it,'' said Police
Chief Terry Tobias.
   Ryan Rohloff, assistant manager at the gas station, said he was
working the night shift when a man entered and telephoned police.
   ``It was a funny story, the old friend-of-a-friend story,''
Rohloff said. ``He said a friend robbed a business and that he
ended up with the money and that the friend asked him to turn it in
anonymously.''
   Rohloff said the man hung up the phone and asked him to hold the
money until police arrived.
   ``He said, `I just got to leave. You do what you have to do. I
can't stay any longer,''' Rohloff said. ``He seemed nervous. ...
His conscience was just eating him up.''
   The man drove off, and Rohloff said he copied down the car's
license number and gave it to police. A state trooper arrested the
suspect several minutes later, Tobias said.
   Breuker faces an Oct. 24 preliminary hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
