<DOCNO> AP881011-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Smokestacks     10-11 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Smokestacks,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Industry Challenges to Environmental Rules on
Smokestacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected industry
challenges to federal environmental rules governing the use of high
smokestacks to disperse air pollution.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that
strengthens clean air regulations by limiting the use of
smokestacks as a substitute for other pollution controls.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled in January that the
Environmental Protection Agency validly adopted the regulations in
1985.
   The rules were prompted in large measure by amendments to the
Clean Air Act, passed by Congress in 1977.
   The amendments were aimed at resolving disputes over the extent
to which industries may meet their required contribution to local
clean-air goals by dispersing pollution rather than by reducing
emissions.
   Building taller stacks, the leading technique of dispersal,
generally is cheaper than cutting emissions. But environmentalists
say that while dispersing the pollution may provide cleaner air in
the vicinity of plants and factories, it adds to the overall
pollution in the atmosphere.
   The rules upheld by the appeals court limit the extent to which
reduction in ground-level pollution near the plants counts toward a
company's compliance with national clean-air standards.
   There are several components to the regulations, including the
height of the stacks and when they were put in place. Generally,
the government permits higher stacks if they were built or approved
prior to the adoption of tighter regulations.
   Coal producers, utility companies and the United Mine Workers of
America challenged the rules.
   They said the Environmental Protection Agency failed to give
them adequate opportunity to be heard before approving regulations
that were far more stringent than those originally proposed by the
agency.
   The appeals court said, ``The EPA can obviously promulgate a
final regulation that differs in some respects from its proposed
regulation. We think the agency's ultimate choice (in 1985)
qualifies _ if barely _ as a logical outgrowth of the original
proposal.''
   The appeals court also rejected industry arguments that the
agency illegally was enforcing new rules retroactively.
   Environmental groups had asked the appeals court to compel the
EPA to adopt even tougher regulations.
   The appeals court ruled in favor of the environmentalists on
some points and against them on others, but the environmentalists
did not appeal to the Supreme Court.
   The cases are Alabama Power Co. vs. Thomas, 87-2068; Ohio Power
Co. vs. Thomas, 88-60; and National Coal Association vs. NRDC,
88-61.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pickles     10-11 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pickles,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Ruling Stand That Migrant Workers Protected by Law in
Wisconsin Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that migrant workers who harvest cucumbers for pickling are
protected by a federal law requiring fair treatment of employees.
   The court rejected an appeal by a Wisconsin farm-owning couple
who said the migrants are ``independent contractors'' not covered
by the Fair Labor Standards Act.
   Justice Byron R. White voted to hear arguments in the case. But
the votes of at least four justices are required to grant such
review.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last December ruled
against Michael and Marilyn Lauritzen, owners of a farm near
Waupaca, Wis.
   The appeals court said the pickers _ like other migrant workers
_ are employees under the federal law. It ruled that the Lauritzens
are not entitled to a full trial in the case.
   The migrants ``depend on the (Lauritzens') land, crops,
agricultural expertise, equipment and marketing skills,'' the
appeals court said. ``They are the defendants' employees.''
   But the 7th Circuit court said that does not mean the Lauritzens
must shoulder an unfair economic burden.
   The couple ``need only think of the proceeds paid to the pickle
pickers as wages, keep the necessary records and make sure they
abide by the protections that the act accords to working
children,'' the appeals court said.
   The U.S. Labor Department sued the Lauritzens to force them to
keep records of the names, ages and work hours of the migrants; to
require them to determine whether young children were working in
the fields; and to guarantee payment of the minimimum wage.
   Allegations that the farm owners were not paying the minimum
wage later were dropped.
   The migrants usually work in the fields from July through
September. While the crop is often referred to as pickles, it
actually is a type of cucumber suitable for pickling.
   The Lauritzens subdivide their property into family plots, and
the migrant family decides which members will pick the pickles. The
migrants' income is determined in part by their ability to judge
the pickles' size, color and freshness so as to harvest the more
valuable pickles.
   The workers also can increase their income by caring for the
plants and pickles on their plot.
   But the 7th Circuit court said those factors do not mean the
workers are anything other than employees.
   The Lauritzens ``did not effectively relinquish control of the
harvest to the migrants,'' the appeals court said.
   And, the appeals court added, the need for some skill in
harvesting pickles does not make the migrants independent
contractors.
   ``Skills are not the monoply of independent contractors. We do
not find that this level of skill sets the pickle harvester apart
from the harvester of other crops,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is Lauritzen vs. Brock, 87-1853.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0115 </DOCNO>
