<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Cambodia     10-11 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Cambodia,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Meets Sihanouk; Discusses Strife in Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Cambodian leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk voiced support today for any move to get Pol Pot and other
leaders of the Khmer Rouge exiled from the war-torn Southeast Asian
nation.
   Following a brief meeting at the White House with President
Reagan, Sihanouk was asked by reporters to comment on a report
saying many Asian officials see such an exile as a key element to a
political settlement in Cambodia, now known formally as Kampuchea.
   The prince, who will travel to the United Nations after meetings
with U.S. officials here, said, ``When I met with the Chinese
leadership in Peking, before coming to Europe and to America, I did
not get from China any indication that China would like to accept a
Pol Pot in exile.''
   But Sihanouk, who heads a small anti-communist faction known as
the National Party of Sihanouk, added that ``I think that it is
necessary to give the world some guarantee about the Khmer Rouge in
the future.''
   ``I think the ones who are responsible for the genocide of the
Cambodian people'' in the 1970s ``must not continue to lead the
Khmer Rouge movement and they must go into exile if possible,'' he
said.
   The New York Times, in a story published in today's editions,
said many diplomats view China as a likely haven for Pol Pot and
other figures of the Khmer Rouge, the communist regime that Pol Pot
headed before being ousted during the Vietnamese invasion of 1978.
   During his daily news briefing, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said that Reagan told Sihanouk that he ``supported
(Sihanouk's) efforts to establish a reconciliation government in
Cambodia.''
   ``He said our policy rests on two elements, a complete
Vietnamese withdrawal and no return to power of the Khmer Rouge,''
Fitzwater said.
   He said that Reagan ``told the prince that the United States is
prepared to join an international conference to ratify any solution
worked out by the parties and, further, that we believe an
international presence in Camobodia is needed.''
   The Vietnamese announced months ago that they planned to pull as
many as 50,000 troops out of Cambodia by the end of this year.
   But Sihanouk said today that the withdrawal is not progressing
satisfactorily.
   He said ``the puppet regime'' installed by Hanoi to run
Cambodia's affairs refuses ``to give a precise timetable'' for the
withdrawal of the approximately 120,000 Vietnamese forces from the
country.
</TEXT>
