<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ReadingProject     10-11 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reading Project,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Program Uses Newspapers to Teach Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national program designed to teach parents
ways to use newspapers to help their young children develop reading
and communications skills was kicked off Tuesday at a local
elementary school.
   The program, called ``Family Focus: Reading and Learning
Together,'' is aimed at parents with children in grades 1 through
3. Local programs are to be organized by schools and parent-teacher
associations.
   ``The newspaper is the reading material we use most frequently
in this country,'' said Patricia S. Koppman, president of the
International Reading Association, told a group of educators and
parents at the Gage-Eckington Elementary School.
   With newspapers as an inexpensive and readily available
resource, parents can help children ``have fun with words,'' said
Manya S. Ungar, president of the National Congress of Parents and
Teachers, another program sponsor.
   Suggestions for parents range from helping children read
headlines to having youngsters search the paper for pictures of
their favorite foods to cutting a comic strip into individual
pictures and asking the child to put them in order.
   The exercises are designed ``to establish an enthusiastic
reading habit,'' said Sandra C. Hardy, chairwoman of the American
Newspaper Publishers Association Foundation, a nonprofit
educational organization and one of the project sponsors.
   She dismissed any suggestion that the ANPA Foundation's motive
in the project was to sell more newspapers.
   ``None (of the ANPA's members) would complain if their
circulation increased ... but there are more immediate and direct
ways to increase circulation,'' she said.
</TEXT>
