<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Saudi-Iran     10-11 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Iran,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Fahd Offers Olive Branch To Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd held out an olive branch
to Iran on Tuesday, 5{ months after severing relations with Tehran,
saying he was sorry the Iranians weren't at a meeting of Islamic
information ministers.
   ``I would have wished the Iranian delegation to be with us,'' he
told 45 ministers when the session opened in this Red Sea city.
   ``Iran is an Islamic country, and deep in my heart I would have
loved to see my Iranian brothers here today,'' the monarch said in
his speech.
   Fahd's signal was the clearest in a series of recent Saudi
gestures toward Iran.
   The king's moves came amid efforts by Tehran to improve its
relations with its Arab neighbors and Western nations following the
Aug. 20 United Nations-sponsored cease-fire in the 8-year-old war
with Iraq.
   The Saudis broke off diplomatic relations with Tehran April 26
after accusing the Tehran regime of carrying oJuly at the end of the hajj,
or annual pilgrimage to Islamic
shrines in Saudi Arabia.
   Iranian pilgrims boycotted the pilgrimage this year because of
the rift between the two Moslem nations.
   The king's remarks came a week after the Saudi government
executed four saboteurs it said were working on Iran's behalf.
   The Iranians have condemned the executions and accused Saudi
Arabia and other gulf Arab states of producing more oil than the
quotas set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
drive down oil prices to weaken Tehran.
   Nonetheless, the war of words between the two gulf giants has
eased in recent months.
   Fahd's conciliatory gestures were in sharp contast to the
anti-Iranian sentiments in some of the literature handed out at the
conference.
   One tract, titled ``Khomeini and Israel,'' detailed alleged
dealings between Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime and the
Jewish state.
   Another was a slick publication in several languages and filled
with color photos of the bloody riots during the 1987 pilgrimage to
Mecca.
   More than 400 people, 275 of them Iranians, were killed in that
violence. Saudi officials said the bloodshed was instigated by
Iranian militants.
   The book also contained photos of Iranian dead and prisoners in
the war with Iraq as well as pictures of Iranian clerics and
black-cloaked women parading with automatic rifles and
rocket-propelled grenade launchers.
   The friction between Iran, whose 50 million population is
overwhelmingly Shiite Moslem, and Saudi Arabia, most of whose 12
million people are Sunni Moslems, mirrors a centuries-old schism in
the Islamic world and historical animosity between the Arabs and
Persians.
   Fahd's remarks opened a meeting that officials indicated was
aimed at improving the exchange of information between Moslem
countries and Islam's image in the non-Moslem world.
   This reflected concerns, acknowledged privately by some
officials, that Iranian-backed terrorism and other aggressive
fundamentalist activities have harmed Islam, with 800 million
adherents around the world.
   During the gulf war, Iran accused Kuwait and Saudi Arabia of
aiding Iraq.
   Kuwait has increased diplomatic links with Tehran in what was
seen as a general move by gulf states to normalize relations with
Iran.
</TEXT>
