<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Yellowstone     10-11 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montana, Wyoming Officials Set to Polishing Scorched Yellowstone
Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana and Wyoming officials are plotting
a $3 million program to get a message to the world's vacationers:
Yellowstone National Park is still there and worth visiting.
   John Wilson, chief of Montana's travel promotion office, said
the two states have asked for $3 million in federal money to
convince travelers, here and abroad, that the wildfires of 1988
left much of the park unscarred.
   Reports on the fires wrongly suggested most of the park was
blackened, said Wilson. ``There wasn't a blanket wall of flame that
just obliterated 1.2 million acres of the park,'' he said.
   While the boundaries of the fires may have encompassed about
half of Yellowstone, only 40 percent of that land actually burned
and a third of that was meadows and undergrowth that will quickly
grow back, he said.
   Also, the fires did not wipe out wildlife or fisheries, and the
major structures and natural features were undamaged, Wilson said.
   Before a Sept. 28 meeting with Wyoming tourism officials and
park representatives at Mammoth, Wilson and members of the Montana
Tourism Advisory Council toured Yellowstone and were buoyed by how
much of it remained uncharred.
   ``It lifted our spirits,'' he said. ``We thought the damage was
going to be much greater than we saw. The fires burned a mosaic.
The beauty of the park will come back.''
   There are areas that were severely burned, but much of the
underlying layer of plants and grass will grow back next year, he
said.
   ``Yellowstone is alive and well,'' he added. ``We can put an
honest effort together to tell the rest of the world.''
   The states are working together on a 15-minute film chronicling
the condition of Yellowstone, the oldest national park. The film
will be sent to travel agencies, tour planners and magazines,
Wilson said.
   If federal funding is provided, the states may conduct ``trade
missions'' to personally spread the message throughout the country,
he said.
</TEXT>
