<HEAD>Spokesmen Say Mrs. Reagan Does Support Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan called George Bush and his wife
to say she is ``very supportive'' of Bush's presidential campaign
and to deny reports she's loath to turn the White House over to
them, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   ``The stories are not true,'' Fitzwater said when asked to
respond to several recent published reports.
   Fitzwater called such stories ``outrageous'' and said it would
be wrong to assume President Reagan's wife did not support Bush
because she has not been present at some campaign appearances.
   ``She has not gone on day trips, as I recall, ever,'' the
spokesman said.
   He added, ``The first lady is very supportive'' of the Bushes.
   Fitzwater said Mrs. Reagan first spoke with the vice president
on Monday, and then later with Barbara Bush because the vice
president's wife was not present when she first called.
   ``The vice president sent her a note thanking her for her
graciousness and support over the last eight years,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen, said, ``I have to
laugh _ a year ago, stories were written about her house-hunting
and how eager she was to leave. Now, it's said she'll flatten the
tires on the moving truck.''
   The spokeswoman said Mrs. Reagan referred to the stories as
``such foolishness.'' And Mrs. Crispen recalled that at the
Republican Convention in New Orleans Mrs. Reagan spoke publicly of
``it being time to leave center stage'' and of her confidence in
and support of the Bushes.
   The spokeswoman said Mrs. Reagan did not attend one Los Angeles
rally for the Bushes because the event was scheduled after she had
made appointments to be with friends and to deal with the Reagans'
new home in Bel Air.
   ``She's never campaigned for anyone but Ronald Reagan _ but that
doesn't mean she doesn't support the Bushes,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
