<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     10-11 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says No Progress in Iran Peace Talks Since Start</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government-run newspaper said Tuesday
there has been no progress in the Iran-Iraq peace talks since they
started over six weeks ago.
   The front page editorial in Al-Joumhouriya was the first comment
by Iraq's official media on the statement Saturday by Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akhbar Velayati, who said the two sides agreed
in principle to United Nations proposals to end the war.
   The daily said that the peace talks to end the war remain
deadlocked because Iran has not committed itself to respecting free
navigation in the Persian Gulf and clearing the Shaat al-Arab
waterway.
   It said there was no breakthrough in negotiations and accused
Iran of continuing ``delaying tactics and procrastination.''
   The negotiations are ``still on square one where they started on
Aug. 25,'' Al-Joumhouriya said of the talks, which moved from
Geneva to New York and are expected to return to Geneva at the end
of the month.
   The paper said that Iraq will not give up its demand for free
navigation in the gulf and the clearance of the Shatt al-Arab, the
estuary of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and Iraq's main outlet
to the sea.
   Velayati said that Iran agreed to a U.N. proposal that it give
up its right to search ships in the Strait of Hormuz, the strategic
mouth of the gulf.
   He did not mention Iraq's demand to clear the Shatt al-Arab,
which forms the southern boundary between the foes, before letting
the talks progress.
   ``Neither of the two principles can be substituted for the
other,'' Al-Joumhouriya said. ``Both are closely linked.''
   The paper said that Iraq cannot benefit from free navigation in
the gulf without being able to use the Shatt Al-Arab.
   ``Iraq will not relinquish its rights in seeing these two
principles applied,'' the paper said.
   Al-Joumhouriya said ``Iraq is ready to show the same patience it
displayed during the war, but the Iranian rulers should realize
that they are impeding the process of peace,''it said.
   In a related development, a senior U.N. official visited the
Iraqi port of Basra, the country's second-largest city, and the
southern sector of the warfront.
   U.N. peacekeeping troops have been posted along the border to
monitor the cease-fire in the 8-year-old war.
</TEXT>
