<HEAD>Nearly 11,000 Kurdish Refugees Transferred to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 11,000 Kurdish refugees who
fled Iraq for Turkey amid allegations of chemical weapon attacks on
their homes reportedly have been transfered to Iran in the last
four days.
   Turkey's semi-official news agency, Anatolia, reported Tuesday
that 10,862 refugees, who were among the 60,000 Kurds who fled
Iraq, were taken in buses and trucks from two tent cities in
southeast Turkey and transferred to Iran.
   Anatolia reported the refugees were settled at a Kurdish camp
called Zive, which was operated by Massoud Barzani, president of
the Kurdish Democratic Party. Zive is near the Iraqi border.
   About 8,000 went to Iran last month before the transfers were
halted because of lack of shelter.
   Iran offered to accept any of the Kurdish refugees in Turkey.
During the Iran-Iraq war, Iran supported Kurdish guerrillas
fighting for autonomy in northern Iraq.
   Last week 1,467 Kurds returned to Iraq voluntarily.
   Iraq started its offensive against the Kurds soon after Iran
agreed to a ceasefire in the 8-year-old war.
