<HEAD>Dukakis Tops Bush In Wisconsin Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper poll showing Republican
presidential nominee George Bush trailing Democrat Michael Dukakis
in Wisconsin also indicates Bush's selection of running mate Dan
Quayle is unpopular with roughly half of those surveyed.
   The Milwaukee Journal poll, conducted after the vice
presidential debate Wednesday and released Monday, showed Dukakis
leading Bush 50 percent to 43 percent among residents of Wisconsin,
a state that offers 11 electoral votes in the Nov. 8 election.
   Dukakis led Bush by the same seven-point margin in a poll taken
last month, though a survey last June showed the Massachusetts
governor up by 14 points.
   As for the vice presidential hopefuls, nearly half the
respondents _ 46 percent _ viewed GOP nominee Dan Quayle as
unqualified to assume the presidency in an emergency. Sixteen
percent felt his Democratic counterpart Lloyd Bentsen lacked the
needed credentials to serve in that capacity.
   The poll, based on interviews with 604 Wisconsin residents of
voting age who said they were either absolutely or fairly certain
to vote, had a margin of potential sampling error of four
percentage points.
