<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRILTON, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stevie Wonder's unannounced visit to this
quiet town created a two-day traffic jam and spoiled his plans for
a restful low-profile weekend.
   Wonder accompanied Miss Arkansas 1980 Lencola Sullivan on a
visit to her hometown. Ms. Sullivan said the two have been seeing
each other for about six months and that Wonder ``wanted to meet my
parents and see Arkansas.''
   On Sunday morning, the couple attended services at a small
church near Ms. Sullivan's home. To the surprise of the
congregation, Wonder performed three songs. Word soon got out and
fans staked out the home, snarling traffic in the area for most of
Sunday and Monday.
   When the two went shopping Sunday afternoon in Conway, east of
Morrilton, Wonder was mobbed by autograph hounds. Wonder and Ms.
Sullivan left Arkansas late Monday. They both live in New York.
   Asked how serious their relationship was, Ms. Sullivan said:
``Right now we're just very close friends, but by him wanting to
meet my parents that should say something.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divorces don't come cheaply, especially
when you make $61 million, so a local rock band is throwing a
benefit concert for Bruce Springsteen.
   The announcement for the Oct. 29 ``Bucks for Boss'' benefit by
the Decibels was tinged with sarcasm.
   ``His upcoming, self-inflicted divorce and all the time he has
donated to causes have probably drained the guy,'' the release said.
   Springsteen is participating in the ``Human Rights Now!'' world
tour for Amnesty International. Forbes Magazine recently computed
the singer's earnings for 1987-1988 as $61 million.
   The rocker is in the midst of a divorce from actress Julianne
Phillips, his wife since 1985.
   The Decibels plan to give away a pink Cadillac at the concert, a
prize inspired by Springsteen's hit song about the car. If
Springsteen doesn't pick up proceeds from the benefit by Nov. 15,
the band says it will donate the money to environmental
organizations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author Alex Haley's
latest project is a biography about Indianapolis philanthropist
Madame C.J. Walker, the first black woman to earn $1 million in her
own right.
   Haley, the author of ``The Autobiography of Malcolm X'' and the
1976 best seller ``Roots,'' said when he was considering the
project he didn't necessarily have a black figure in mind, but he
did want to write about a woman.
   Walker, the daughter of ex-slaves, propelled herself from
washerwoman to businesswoman and activist. She built her fortune in
the early 1900s, developing and selling cosmetics and hair care
products.
   ``Given where she came from, it's extremely thrilling she did
all she did,'' said Haley. ``She's a fantastic story.''
   Haley said there has been talk of turning his unpublished book
into a film, possibly with talk-show host Oprah Winfrey, but ``We
haven't made a deal yet.''
   Haley will be in Indianapolis Friday for the opening of the
renovated Madame C.J. Walker Theatre, next to the factory Walker
opened in 1910.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STEVENAGE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana admitted a dislike for
needles Tuesday when she visited a clinic where young children were
being injected under a government inoculation drive.
   ``What on Earth have you set this up for? You know I can't stand
injections,'' she said to her aide while touring the clinic in
Stevenage, in western England.
   The 27-year-old Diana, wife of heir to the throne Prince
Charles, turned away when a 4-year-old girl and a 13-month-old girl
were given injections. The government program aims to immunize up
to 660,000 children a year in Britain against mumps and rubella.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don DeLillo and Anne Tyler are among 10 writers
who have been nominated for the 1988 National Book Awards.
   The five fiction nominations are DeLillo's ``Libra,'' based on
the events that led to John F. Kennedy's assassination; Tyler's
``Breathing Lessons,'' about a long-married couple traveling to a
funeral; J.F. Powers' ``Wheat That Springeth Green,'' about a
middle-aged priest and a new curate; Peter Dexter's ``Paris
Trout,'' about the murder of a black girl in Georgia; and Mary
McGarry Morris' ``Vanished,'' about a couple who kidnap a toddler.
   The five non-fiction nominations are Peter Gay's ``Freud: A Life
For Our Time''; Eric Foner's ``Reconstruction: America's Unfinished
Revolution, 1863-1877''; Brenda Maddox's ``Nora,'' a biography of
James Joyce's wife; Jack McLaughlin's ``Jefferson and Monticello'';
and Neil Sheehan's ``A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and
America in Vietnam.''
   Winners will be announced Nov. 29 in New York. Each receives
$10,000 and a commemorative sculpture by Louise Nevelson.
</TEXT>
