<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MandelaQuestion 1stLd-Writethru a0658 10-11 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela Question, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Predominantly Black Area Wants To Secede as City of Mandela</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf `The Rev...' to describe Mandela as
nationalist, sted civil rights leader. Picks up 6th graf pvs,
`Mayor Raymond...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents will decide next month whether a
proposal to permit predominantly black Boston neighborhoods to
become a separate new city named Mandela amounts to segregation or
good civic sense.
   The non-binding referendum on the ballot Nov. 8 is similar to
one soundly defeated in 1986 by a 3-1 margin. Those results were
far better than the 9-1 margin of defeat predicted and backers who
say the change would improve municipal services said they were
encouraged to try again.
   ``If the reaction had been a big yawn, then we probably wouldn't
be doing this right now,'' said state Rep. Byron Rushing, a Boston
Democrat.
   But this time there is little of the excitement created two
years ago. The movement that inspired its own rap song in 1986
hasn't even drawn formal opposition this time.
   The Rev. Charles R. Stith, a prominent black leader and a chief
opponent, said the proposed city of Mandela, named after jailed
black South African nationalist Nelson Mandela, could not survive
without the citywide tax base of Boston.
   Mayor Raymond Flynn opposes the referendum because it would
segregate the community, said his press secretary, Arthur Jones.
   And if the measure were approved, it would have to be signed by
Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, who also is against it.
   The proposed city of about 125,000 people would include a
12{-square-mile area made up of all of Roxbury and parts of the
Dorchester, Mattapan and Jamaica Plain sections of the city. Boston
covers 42.7 square miles and has 570,000 residents.
   Supporters argue the areas have long been neglected and would
fare better with control of their own tax dollars.
   The secession drive stemmed from a feeling that city leaders had
run out of options for improving municipal services such as police
and garbage collection, said Andrew P. Jones, a violinist and
independent television producer. He was a co-founder of the Greater
Roxbury Incorporation Project that got the secession movement
started.
   ``Right now, hardly any of the teachers send their kids to our
schools,'' he said. ``Most of the police live outside the
community. If the police live in the community, then they're
protecting their home. If they just work in the community, then
they're protecting their job.''
   Jones says his support of the proposal is to blame for an
attempt to evict him from his apartment. The owners of the building
insist the matter has nothing to do with politics.
   The secession proposal will be voted on in 10 state
representative districts covering all of proposed Mandela and some
fringe areas that include white residents.
   Rushing said he expects white residents who vote for the measure
would do so for improved municipal services, not to promote
segregation.
   If the non-binding referendum passes, Rushing said he would
introduce secession legislation, which would eventually lead to a
citywide vote.
   The campaign has sparked charges of reverse racism and
segregationism, but Rushing said eyebrows would not be raised if
white neighborhoods were trying to secede.
   Choosing the name of Mandela gave some a false impression that
the campaign had a militant character, Rushing said. In fact, he
said, the incorporation campaign is merely a way to control and
improve municipal services.
   ``It is a symptom of racism in this country that ... you always
expect black people to somehow want to be with white people,''
Rushing said. ``That's what I call paternalistic.
   ``This is not Utopian. If this happens, all the problems are not
going to be solved. The question here though is will things get
better if you have more direct control.''
</TEXT>
