<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cambodia     10-11 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cambodia,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pledges Support for Cambodian Peacemaking Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday reassured Prince
Norodom Sihanouk that the United States supports the former
Cambodian ruler's quest to win a negotiated political settlement in
the war-torn country, a White House spokesman said.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president reiterated
American policy favoring a complete withdrawal of Vietnamese troops
and opposing a return to power of the Khmer Rouge, the communist
group that ruled Cambodia during the mass killings and forced
relocations of the 1970s. The Khmer Rouge were overthrown by the
Vietnamese in 1978 and replaced with a regime installed by Hanoi.
   Describing a meeting that Reagan and Sihanouk had in the Oval
Office, the spokesman said the president ``told the prince that the
United States is prepared to join an international conference to
ratify any solution worked out by the parties and, further, that we
believe an international presence in Camobodia is needed.''
   Reagan met briefly with Sihanouk, who heads the National Party
Sihanouk, an anti-communist faction now loosely aligned with the
Khmer Rouge against Vietnamese occupation forces.
   Sihanouk will hold talks with State Department officials before
traveling to New York later in the week for discussions with
diplomats at the United Nations.
   Answering reporters' questions after meeting with Reagan,
Sihanouk said he seeks a moderate leadership of the Khmer Rouge and
would support any move to exile Pol Pot and other leading Khmer
Rouge figures to China.
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that many Asian officials
see exile in China for Khmer Rouge leaders as a key element in any
political settlement for Cambodia.
   But Sihanouk said that in his recent trip to Peking, ``I did not
get from China any indication that China would like to accept a Pol
Pot in exile.''
   Sihanouk, speaking in English, also said, ``I think the ones who
are responsible for the genocide of the Cambodian people'' in the
1970s ``must not continue to lead the Khmer Rouge movement and they
must go into exile if possible.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan and Sihanouk talked about ``a peacekeeping
force, a U.N. force of some kind. I think we would want to reserve
some flexibility in how that would be defined.''
   He also said that Reagan ``strongly supports increased aid to
the non-communist resistance and we are consulting with Congress to
bring that about.''
   The United States provided $3.5 million in aid to Cambodia last
year and plans to increase that to as much as $5 million this year,
although this figure ``may fluctuate,'' he said. Fitzwater said
Reagan and Sihanouk did not discuss new aid figures.
   Sihanouk said he is ``not optimistic'' about the prospects for
peace talks he is scheduled to have in Paris in early November with
Hun Sen, the Hanoi-installed prime minister of Cambodia.
   ``There are still obstacles and difficulties on the road towards
solution, because of Vietnam itself, because of the puppet regime
in Pnom Penh,'' he said. ``They continue to refuse ... to give a
precise timetable concerning the withdrawal from Cambodia of the
Vietnamese troops,''
   The Vietnamese announced months ago that they planned to pull as
many as 50,000 of their more than 120,000 troops out of Cambodia by
the end of this year. But there have been reports that the pace of
the pull-out has stalled as some Vietnamese have remained behind to
keep the Khmer Rouge from capturing abandoned territory.
   Sihanouk also said he has asked French President Francois
Mitterand to organize an international peace conference on Cambodia
in Paris. He said such a conference should include the Soviet
Union, Vietnam, China and the United States.
</TEXT>
