<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Oakland Bjt   10-11 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oakland, Bjt,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oakland Counts on World Series To Improve City's Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jose Canseco steps up to home plate
during the World Series, the hopes of more than baseball fans will
be riding on his performance.
   Civic leaders, investors and residents hope the World Series
will do what years of community effort and millions of dollars have
so far failed to do: Make this ``other'' City-by-the-Bay a major
league town.
   Plagued by drug problems, high crime and an economy that stalled
somewhere after World War II, Oakland has hovered in the shadow of
big neighbor San Francisco.
   The city's image is so bad ``it almost makes you feel bad to say
you live in Oakland,'' said Phyllis Bonner, a resident of the Acorn
Housing Project, a complex plagued by drug-related crime.
   The city's chance may finally have arrived now that the Oakland
A's have earned a spot in the World Series.
   ``It's exciting, everybody's talking about it,'' said Elva
Manuel, another resident of the Acorn project. She hopes the Series
will improve the city's image. ``It can't get any worse,'' she said.
   Now that the city is to be host to baseball fans and television
cameras, the Oakland Chamber of Commerce is hanging banners,
wrapping hospitality baskets in green and gold and painting
billboards touting the city.
   ``We've had our problems with drugs and crime, there's no
question,'' said acting Chamber president Connie Shapiro. ``But
there's been a real turnaround.''
   Among Oakland's blessings are a world-class port and a climate
that's the envy of fog-enshrouded San Franciscans, who routinely
endure consecutive summer days with barely a glimpse of the sun.
   More than 356,000 people live in Oakland, about 10 miles
southeast of San Francisco, although the Oakland A's draw fans from
all over the Bay area.
   ``There's an excitement created by the Oakland A's that's picked
up by many, many people _ of all ages ... and all economic levels
of the city,'' Mayor Lionel Wilson said. ``It really wasn't there
until the last couple of years. You can see it. You can feel it.''
   The best-of-seven World Series opens Saturday in either New York
City or Los Angeles, depending on the outcome of the National
League playoffs, and comes to Oakland on Tuesday.
   Officials expect the World Series to generate at least $5
million for the city each of up to three days the teams face off in
Oakland, in addition to an estimated $7 million for the Oakland
Coliseum.
   Ed Church, director of program development for a community-based
advocacy and planning organization called the Urban Strategies
Council, hopes the Series will provide a ``psychological boost.''
   ``If people talk about Oakland derisively, people pick up on
that,'' he said. ``When people come here from around the country,
they're amazed. They find it's a beautiful, beautiful place.''
   Indeed, Oakland has had serious problems.
   Infant mortality rates, down dramatically from a decade ago,
still remain well above the national average. Drug-linked killings
were up 83 percent in 1987 from the year before. In 1986, Oakland
had the nation's 10th-highest homicide rate.
   Wilson's efforts to revitalize downtown met with moderate
success. The Hyatt Regency built a hotel downtown five years ago,
but it didn't turn a profit until last year.
   The Oakland Symphony canceled its season not long ago. The zoo
was nearly closed for lack of funds. The Oakland Museum has
suffered budget cuts.
   Some say the city hasn't been the same since it lost the Oakland
Raiders to Los Angeles in a 1982 National Football League transfer.
   But an upscale shopping hub is on the drawing boards for
downtown. Big-name retailers such as Nordstrom, Neiman-Marcus and
possibly Saks Fifth Avenue have expressed interest, said Chamber
President Shapiro.
   Harry Edwards, a sociology professor at the University of
California at Berkeley who pioneered the field of sports sociology,
doubts that the Series alone will turn around Oakland's image.
   Business will benefit, he said, but for the rest of Oakland, the
Series will be ``at best a nice entertainment spectacle.''
   ``It's like Christmas,'' he said. ``It depends on how low down
in the slime you are. At some point, it could be a very depressing
thing.''
   And history may offer a lesson for those who pin their dreams of
Oakland's renaissance on the World Series: The Oakland A's were the
world champions for three years starting in 1972.
</TEXT>
