<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HorseSlaughter     10-11 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Slaughter,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bureau Of Land Managment Says Slaughter Total Up To 450</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bureau of Land Management ground search in
central Nevada has found 180 more slaughtered wild horses to bring
the total of mustangs believed shot to death up to 450, BLM
officials said Tuesday.
   ``Every time we go out there, we seem to find more,'' BLM
spokesman Bob Stewart said. ``The carnage that occurred out there
was terrible, almost unbelievable.''
   The carcasses have been found in wild horse management areas on
unfenced federal land. Killing them is a violation of the Wild and
Free Roaming Horse and Burro Act of 1971, a misdemeanor with a
penalty of up to a $2,000 fine and one year in jail for each dead
animal.
   Stewart said he would not be surprised if more carcasses were
found before the investigation is complete.
   He refused to say if the BLM had any suspects or strong leads.
One possible motive is that in some areas the horses consume scarce
water and grass in areas that also are leased for cattle grazing.
   Maxine Shane, another BLM public affairs officer, said federal
authorities in Washington have ``promised us the full resources of
the BLM to solve this case.''
   ``We're not at liberty to say how many people are working on the
case,'' she added.
   Discovery of the mass horse killings began last month with the
sighting from a helicopter of 41 carcasses in the Austin area.
   Since then, the discoveries have spread over 102,000 acres,
mostly in Lander County. Stewart said the investigation has been
difficult because the shootings were spread over such a vast area.
   Last week, BLM officials spotted 140 carcasses near Bald
Mountain during a aerial search, bringing the total found to 268.
The ground search in the same area during this weekend turned up
the additional carcasses for a total of 450.
   ``You just can't see as many from the air; it takes a trained
eye,'' Stewart said. ``So every time we spot them in a plane we
know there'll be more on the ground than we can count.''
   Ms. Shane said the killings apparently began about two years
ago, although some of the horses were shot late this spring or
early this summer.
   Investigators believe the slaughters in the Bald Mountain and
Mount Callaghan areas are related, Ms. Shane said. But killings in
the Mount Moses area near the Pershing-Lander county border are
being handled as a separate case, she said.
   There are an estimated 28,000 wild horses in Nevada.
   Rewards as high as $12,000 have been pledged by animal rights
groups for information leading to the arrest and conviction of
those responsible.
</TEXT>
