<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Milosevic 1stLd-Writethru a06COLORADOSPRINGS
10-11 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Milosevic, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0674,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milosevic: New Tito For Some, Threat For Others</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and 6th graf to CORRECT it to ethnic groups
sted races.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To his supporters, Serbian Communist
Party chief Slobodan Milosevic is ``the second Tito,'' the new
leader Yugoslavia needs to extricate the country from its worst
crisis since World War II.
   To his detractors, Milosevic is a Serbian nationalist who
threatens the delicate unity of his ethnically diverse nation and
wants to expand the power of Serbs at the expense of other ethnic
groups.
   Milosevic has ridden to national prominence in recent months on
a wave of mass rallies by Slavs enraged by the alleged harassment
of the Serb and Montenegrin minority in Kosovo, a backward southern
Serbian province now dominated by ethnic Albanians.
   The 47-year-old Serbian leader has won the hearts of the crowds
who adoringly wave his portrait with a combination of tough
politicking and rousing oratory.
   By pushing for greater control over Serbia's two autonomous
provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo, Milosevic has struck a chord
with many of Yugoslavia's 8 million Serbs, who have a strong
attachment to Kosovo because it was the heart of their medieval
empire.
   But he has automatically antagonized other ethnic groups fearful
of Serbian nationalism and may be toppled by communist leaders from
other republics if they feel he is pushing too hard.
   Milosevic's chief opponents _ the communists in Yugoslavia's
most prosperous republics of Slovenia and Croatia _ may force a
showdown as early as next week, when the party holds a key meeting
of its Central Committee.
   There, Milosevic is expected to come under fire for failing to
stop the nationalist rallies and allowing them to turn into
anti-government protests, as they did in the southern republic of
Montenegro last weekend.
   If Milosevic is ousted, however, the other republics could face
even worse unrest from the Serbs who see him as a hero.
   Some of Yugoslavia's top leaders got a taste of Milosevic's hold
over Serbs last week when angry workers from the Belgrade
industrial suburb of Rakovica marched on the federal parliament
demanding wage hikes to feed their families.
   Belgrade journalists at the scene said leaders such as vice
premier Milos Milosavljevic and Dusan Popovski, president of
parliament, hesitated before addressing the crowd, and were
instantly booed by workers shouting Milosevic's name.
   Displaying a populist touch that has helped him rise throughout
his political career, Milosevic drove up in his own Yugo and calmly
told the workers to leave.
   ``They were hypnotized by him,'' recalled a journalist who saw
the scene.
   Born Aug. 20, 1941 in the southern Serbian town of Pozarevac,
Milosevic studied social sciences in Belgrade before going into
industry.
   His political career began in earnest only in 1982, when he quit
his job as president of the boar at a Belgrade bank to sit on the
presidium, or top party body, in Belgrade, the federal and Serbian
capital.
   In 1984, he gained a seat on the party presidium in Serbia,
vaulting into the top party seat last year after making his mark at
a demonstration in Kosovo, where he prevented police from beating a
crowd of Slav protesters.
   To get the top spot in Serbia, Milosevic forced out a man who
had been his political patron, Petar Stambolic.
   Milosevic succeeded by skillful use of the Serbian media to
portray himself as a firm leader attacking fellow communists
dithering about how to handle the economic and political crisis.
   Since last fall, Belgrade journalists say, Milosevic has moved
to bring key Serbian newspapers, and the television and radio under
his sway. The Communist Party daily, Politika, is full of emotional
writing on Kosovo in almost every issue.
   Detractors, particularly in liberal Slovenia, often portray
Milosevic as a hardliner who wants to impose firmer one-party rule
in a country where the communists have lost much of their authority
in an economic crisis that has sent inflation spiraling over 200
percent.
   However, the Serbian party chief has taken on board many
liberalizing economic reforms outlined in the ``Memorandum,'' a
document prepared by Serbian intellectuals in 1986 and officially
denounced by the communists at that time.
   An English speaker, Milosevic is married with a son and a
daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
