<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1521EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0485 10-11 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parties Say Angolan Talks Produced No Agreement On Cuban
Withdrawal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 11th graf pvs, ``South Africa...'' to CORRECT
that Pretoria removed its troops from Angola, sted Namibia. Pickup
12 graf pvs, ``Diplomats involved...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats left weekend talks still
laboring to agree on a timetable for withdrawing Cuban troops from
Angola, according to Cuban and Angolan envoys involved in the
negotiations.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada of Cuba and
Angolan U.N. Ambassador Manuel Pedro Pacavira told reporters Monday
that negotiators reached no breakthrough in New York on a timetable
for pulling out 50,000 Cuban troops.
   ``At this meeting, there was no agreement whatsoever,'' Alarcon
said.
   Earlier news reports quoted U.S. officials as saying Cuba,
Angola, South Africa and the United States had agreed to a
withdrawal of Cuban forces within 24 to 30 months.
   However, a U.S. official in Washington told The Associated Press
on Monday the sides had only ``substantially narrowed''
disagreements on a timetable.
   While no final deal was struck in New York, Cuban officials
suggested they were willing to step up the pace of withdrawal from
the 2,000 soldiers a month they had proposed, said U.S. officials
in Washington, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In New York, Pacavira said negotiators were still split over
proposals for a 24-month or a 30-month timetable.
   ``Up to now, at the negotiating table, there is a proposal from
the mediator (the United States) that was accepted by the South
African delegation for 24 months,'' said Pacavira.
   However, he said the Angolan-Cuban delegation considers the
proposal only ``a basis for discussion because our proposal is 30
months, and we consider that the last limit of our concessions.''
   He said the conflicting proposals were advanced a month ago in a
meeting in Brazzaville, Congo. All three previous rounds of talks
have been mediated by Chester Crocker, U.S. secretary of state for
African affairs.
   South Africa has linked its scheduled Nov. 1 implementation of a
one-year independence plan for neighboring South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia, to the Cuban troop withdrawal. Pretoria, which
withdrew its troops from Angola earlier this year, says the Cubans
threaten the independence of the territory, which borders Angola.
   Diplomats involved in the talks had said they were working
toward reaching agreement on a Cuban withdrawal timetable at a
formal meeting to be held sometime later this month in the Congo.
   However, U.S. officials said Monday it may not be possible to
reach the Nov. 1 deadline set by the United Nations for transition
to independence for South-West Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
