<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     10-11 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Reported Stable, Looking Forward to Autumn Moon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was resting in stable condition
Tuesday and asked about the date for his autumn moon-viewing,
officials at the Imperial Palace said.
   The ``Juusan-ya,'' the traditional night for viewing a nearly
full autumn moon, falls on Oct. 23.
   Physicians stepped up blood transfusions to the 87-year-old
monarch after signs that his intestinal bleeding was continuing.
The palace said the transfusions were to combat Hirohito's
continuing anemia.
   ``Even the court physicians say they aren't sure why His
Majesty's anemia hasn't improved despite all the transfusions,''
palace spokesman Shoichi Fujimori told a news conference.
   Also Tuesday, the palace announced that Prince Hiro, Hirohito's
28-year-old grandson, would attend Saturday's opening of the annual
Autumn National Sports Festival in Kyoto in place of Crown Prince
Akihito.
   The emperor, the world's longest-reigning monarch, customarily
attends the opening ceremonies. Akihito represented his father at
last year's sports meet in Okinawa while Hirohito recuperated from
intestinal bypass surgery.
</TEXT>
