<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Oil Rig,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Living Quarters Of Destroyed North Sea Rig Recovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A floating crane on Tuesday raised the
living quarters of a North Sea oil rig destroyed in the world's
worst oilfield disaster.
   The 180-ton structure provided accommodations for 33 workers on
the Piper Alpha, which was torn apart by gas explosions July 6 and
sank in 150-feet-deep waters, killing 167 men.
   The bodies of the 112 men still missing are believed to be
trapped inside a second 1,100-ton module still lying on the sea
floor, said the rig's American owner, Occidental Petroleum Corp.
   The larger living module is expected to be raised later this
week, said spokesman Alex Blake-Milton.
   Salvage workers are still trying to recover the wreckage of the
rig 120 miles off Scotland's east coast.
</TEXT>
