<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Salvador-Rebel     10-11 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Rebel,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Says Insurgents Would Support Moderate Outcome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Salvadoran leftist leader said Tuesday his
country's guerrilla insurgency would support a political settlement
that guaranteed the continued existence of private industry and a
representative democratic system.
   Ruben Zamora, a member of the Revolutionary Democratic Front,
told reporters the experience of the Sandinista government in
Nicaragua illustrates the dangers of a program of radical reform
and has has a moderating effect on the Salvadoran left.
   ``We have learned a lot from the Nicaraguan experience,'' Zamora
said, alluding to the support the United States has provided to the
Contra rebels.
   ``The U.S. government has the capacity not to defeat a
government like the Sandinistas, but has the capacity to ruin
whatever social and economic programs (a revolutionary government)
has in mind,'' he said.
   Zamora's group has been allied with the FMLN insurgency since
the early 1980s. Under President Jose Napoleon Duarte, El Salvador
has been a major recipient of U.S. assistance because of concern
that a rebel victory would lead to the establishment of another
Soviet foothold in the hemisphere.
   The Reagan administration maintains that the rebels receive
material and other support from Cuba and Nicaragua.
   More than 60,000 Salvadorans have died since the civil war there
erupted in 1980. Zamora said a new ``political dynamic'' now exists
in El Salvador in support of a negotiated settlement.
   Agreements in three basic areas are essential for the fighting
to stop, he said. The first involves agreement on a cease-fire and
the disposition of the ``two armies'' now at war _ the regular army
and the guerrilla army.
   The second, Zamora said, would lay down the rules that guarantee
a pluralistc system and respect for civil liberties and human
rights. Finally, he said, there would be guarantees for private
enterprise, so long as the business community pays taxes, and free
for trade unions to organize.
   Zamora's group, whose initials in Spanish are FDR, boycotted the
1984 national elections but is participating in balloting set for
next March, when a successor to Duarte will be chosen. The ticket
is headed by Guillermo Ungo, a one-time ally of Duarte.
   Zamora said the FMLN rebels have adopted a neutral position
toward FDR participation in the elections. A prime purpose of the
FDR candidates is to rally public support for negotiations to
achieve a political settlement to the civil war, he said.
   He added that the FDR will take part in the elections so long as
its candidates are assured freedom of movement, including security
for its nominees, access to the mass media and fair treatment from
Salvadoran civilian and military authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
