<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolStrikes     10-11 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Strikes,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike After School Board Says It Can't Afford Raises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in Arkansas' second-largest
school district went on strike Tuesday after the Board of Education
said it could not afford a 3 percent pay hike.
   Classes were canceled for 20,000 students in the Pulaski County
School District, which includes all schools in the county except
those in Little Rock and North Little Rock.
   Elsewhere, teachers strikes in Pennsylvania, Illinois and
Michigan disrupted classes for 14,000 students.
   Pulaski County teachers walked off the job after the school
board Monday night refused to act on the union's demand for a 3
percent raise, as recommended by a mediation committee. Their
average salary is currently $23,349.
   ``We are very disappointed with the decisions that have brought
us to this point,'' Dan McElderry, spokesman for the Pulaski
Association of Classroom Teachers, said as teachers gathered before
sunrise for a rally.
   ``We'd much rather be in the classroom, doing what we've been
trained to do,'' said McElderry, chairman of PACT's Crisis
Committee.
   Following the rally, teachers began picketing peacefully at
district schools. There were no incidents, the sheriff's department
said.
   Board President Sheryl Dunn said she was extremely disappointed
at the strike. ``We tried so hard to come to a point that we could
agree on something to find the money for the teachers,'' she said.
``They just won't wait, and all I can say is how desperately sorry
I am.''
   The Pulaski School Board voted 4-3 to reopen negotiations if
money becomes available for raises. The board, in effect, rejected
the teachers' demand by failing to act on it. The union, which
represents 1,000 of the district's 1,300 teachers, voted last week
to strike if the recommended pay increase was rejected.
   Gary Miller, the administration's chief negotiator, told the
board that without raises, the district would have a $1.9 million
deficit unless it receives $2.5 million it contends it had been
underpaid by the state as part of a desegregation case. The money
is tied up in federal litigation. The raise sought by the teachers
would cost about $1 million.
   Elsewhere, 600 teachers and 10,000 students were affected by
strikes in five Pennsylvania districts. In the Spring-Ford
district, a walkout resumed Tuesday after a 30-day cooling-off
period. That strike affected 200 teachers and 3,300 students.
   Illinois had one strike affecting 65 teachers and 1,000
students, while Michigan had one strike affecting 150 teachers and
3,000 students.
</TEXT>
