<DOCNO> AP881011-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nielsens     10-11 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Adds New Shows To Top 10; ABC Rained Out Of No. 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rainout of a National League playoff game
lowered ABC's score in the Nielsen television ratings last week and
gave NBC an unexpected win for the week.
   For the week ending Oct. 9, NBC had a 15.0 rating, ABC had 13.4
and CBS 12.4, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co. NBC had expected to
lose the week because of the baseball playoffs on ABC. But Game 3
in the National League faceoff between the New York Mets and Los
Angeles Dodgers was rained out Friday.
   NBC's premiere of ``Empty Nest,'' nestled behind the hit
``Golden Girls'' on Saturday, and a preview of ``Dear John''
enveloped by the NBC Thursday hit lineup, both landed in the top 10.
   The season premiere of ``The Cosby Show'' was No. 1, though it
had a considerably lower rating and share than its premiere last
season _ 24.2 and a 40 share, compared to a 31.5 and 51 share last
year.
   Gerald Jaffe, NBC's vice president for research projects,
attributed the ``Cosby'' number to competition from ABC's American
League game between the Boston Red Sox and the Oakland A's. He said
NBC was not surprised by the lower number anyway, having predicted
that the hit sitcom would slide in the ratings in this, its fifth
season.
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``A Different World,'' ``Golden
Girls,'' ``Empty Nest'' and ``Dear John,'' all NBC; ``Jesse,'' a
CBS Tuesday movie; and _ all tied at eighth _ ``ALF,'' ``Tonight
Show 26th Anniversary'' and ``The Hogan Family'' on NBC, plus CBS'
``60 Minutes'' and ABC's ``Monday Night Football.''
   CBS won the battle of the Sunday movies with its version of the
Liberace story, ``Liberace: Behind the Music,'' which was 14th in
the Nielsens, ahead of NBC's ``Going to the Chapel'' at 21st.
   ABC ran its Liberace movie, ``Liberace,'' a week earlier.
Apparently, there was enough interest in the life of the flamboyant
entertainer to support the two made-for-TV movies. They got almost
identical ratings: ABC's version scored a 16.8, CBS' 16.6.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 homes with televisions. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   In news, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' managed a close second
despite pre-emptions on the West Coast by baseball. But the ``CBS
Evening News'' won the week with a 10.2 rating and 20 share. ABC
had a 9.9 and 21 share (indicating a larger percentage of a smaller
audience). ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 9.6 and 20 share.
   NBC's Olympics coverage sputtered to a close with the ``Summer
Olympics Review'' ranked 47th with an 8.7 rating and 14 share.
   It was just above the lowest-rated shows of the week:
``Incredible Sunday,'' ``American League Championship Pre-game 3,''
``National League Championship Pre-game 3,'' ``Full House,'' ``Bugs
Bunny Specials,'' ``Cavanaughs,'' ``Perfect Strangers,'' ``Simon &
Simon'' and ``Live! Dick Clark Presents.''
</TEXT>
