<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Manhunt     10-11 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Manhunt,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Mount Nationwide Hunt For Seven Escaped Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50,000 police combed residential
and entertainment districts Tuesday for seven escaped prisoners who
held a family hostage for 26 hours.
   Police said the search extended nationwide for the seven, last
seen early Monday when they left the home of a Seoul pharmacist
where they had burst in a day earlier brandishing knives and a
pistol.
   The Home Ministry ordered neighborhood associations in Seoul and
the adjacent province of Kyonggi to hold their monthly meetings
Tuesday night, two weeks earlier than usual, to seek their
cooperation in tracking down the fugitives.
   They were among 12 prisoners who opened their handcuffs with a
makeshift key while en route to provincial prisons Saturday,
overpowered their guards, and forced the prison bus back to Seoul.
They tied up the 11 guards and fled, taking the pistol and five
cartridges.
   Five of the prisoners are back in custody, including three
captured Sunday after a saloon owner tipped police that suspicious
men were at his bar.
   Police officials said at least 50,000 of the nation's 120,000
troopers had been pressed into the search for the others, who
reportedly had talked of revenge against the saloon owner.
   Sohn Byung-nok, the pharmacist who was held hostage, also said
he heard the fugitives discussing a robbery raid in a high-class
residential area.
   Sohn said the seven had wanted to stay longer in his home, but
left in two groups when his 23-year-old daughter told them she had
to attend college courses Monday.
   ``We were terrified during the 26 hours,'' said Sohn, 51, whose
home was invaded at 2:30 a.m. Sunday when he, his wife, two
children, a cousin and an employee of his shop were sleeping.
   Newspapers reported that one of the seven telephoned the
Yongdungpo Prison, where the three recaptured prisoners were held,
and was allowed to talk to one of them. He told the prisoner that
he had seized a car and would use it for one raid before deciding
whether to surrender, the reports said.
   The seven each had been sentenced to prison terms of seven years
or more for murder, armed robbery or rape. They had been awaiting
the results of appeals to the Supreme Court.
   The 11 prison bus guards were under investigation for negligence.
</TEXT>
