<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Tartikoff,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC's Tartikoff Signs Long-Term Deal to Stay at Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff,
who had been rumored to be fielding offers from movie studios, will
remain at NBC with expanded duties as chairman of a new program
development division, Tartikoff and NBC President Robert C. Wright
announced Tuesday.
   ``Several different jobs were offered to me, major studio
executive situations, independent production deals, but a few weeks
ago both Jack (GE Chairman Jack Welch) and Bob (Wright) met with me
and made a very generous offer for me to continue on at NBC,''
Tartikoff said in a statement close-circuited to network affiliates
from NBC headquarters in New York.
   Wright called Tartikoff ``simply the best.''
   ``His decision to remain with NBC is exceptionally good news for
NBC's advertisers, for our affiliates, for our employees and for
America's viewers,'' said Wright.
   Tartikoff has been head of the entertainment division since 1980
and has held the job longer than anyone in television. NBC had
never won a season before taking the top spot four seasons ago and
it has been No. 1 ever since, a feat credited to Tartikoff's
programming ability and eye for new talent.
   Tartikoff will be chairman of a new NBC Program Development
Group, which includes NBC News President Michael Gartner and Sports
President Arthur Watson, plus the heads of NBC productions,
business affairs, the station group and the network. Tartikoff will
also oversee advertising and promotion.
   Tartikoff said details about program development would probably
be revealed later this month, but said the new ``Later with Bob
Costas'' show was an example of the type of cooperative programming
the group might develop. ``Later'' is an entertainment talk show,
but Costas came from NBC Sports.
   Tartikoff said he felt the deal he was offered _ there were no
details released except that the contract extends ``into the
1990s'' _ represented a commitment by NBC's corporate owner, GE, to
``the future of free, over-the-air television.''
