   Although the practice of crossing flight paths _ with planes
separated by altiSHIP, N.J. (AP) _ A regulatory board Tuesday gave
unanimous approval to entertainer Merv Griffin's offer to buy
Resorts International Inc., its casinos and property, despite
lingering questions about whether Griffin will complete the deal.
   ``Thank you for the unanimous vote,'' Griffin told the Casino
Control Commission after its ruling. ``It was a vote of
confidence.''
   The commission's decision came a day after Griffin's company
announced it had allowed a deadline for its $36-per-share tender
offer to Resorts' stockholders to expire. The move gave rise to
speculation that Griffin was trying to back out of the deal.
   It also drove down the price of Resorts stock by $4.875 Monday
to $29.125.
   Griffin told reporters after the ruling that the speculation was
``ridiculous,'' but that allowing the deadline to expire was
designed to allow him to get out of the deal if conditions were not
favorable.
   ``It gives me the right to continue on and close (the deal) as
quickly as I can,'' he said. ``It gives me a chance to leave it if
all things aren't in place.
   ``I want to be able to stay very fluid and to be able to make a
businessman's decision, and to walk if everything is not done,''
Griffin added.
   Under the deal, Griffin would purchase Resorts' stock, including
that owned by billionaire developer Donald Trump. Griffin would
take control of the Resorts International Casino Hotel, Resorts'
vast land holdings in Atlantic City, and a casino and property
Resorts owns in the Bahamas.
   Trump would purchase from Resorts its unfinished, 1,250-room Taj
Majal casino next door to Resorts' gaming hall on the Boardwalk in
Atlantic City.
   Griffin is still awaiting approval from the Bahamian government
on his request to purchase Resorts' property there. The commission
has not yet acted on his request for a permanent casino license,
although it granted him a 90-day license Tuesday.
   His attorney, Howard Goldberg, assured the commission that
Griffin wasn't pulling out of the sale.
   ``I hate to paraphrase Mark Twain,'' he said, ``but the rumors
about the death of this deal are greatly exaggerated.''
   Goldberg said the refusal to extend the tender offer gives
Griffin ``flexibility'' to reconsider the deal if market conditions
take a downward slide or if Griffin fails to get approvals he is
waiting for.
   Robert Trump, executive vice president of The Trump Organization
and the brother of Donald, said he was confused by Griffin's
announcement.
   ``We didn't quite understand it,'' he said.
   ``I read and re-read the (Griffin news) releases and I don't
know what they mean,'' said Joel Sterns, an attorney for Resorts.
   Reading from a prepared text, Griffin said if an acquisition is
completed, it would be done through a merger, not a tender offer.
   A merger offer was approved Aug. 30 by the required number of
shareholders, said Griffin.
   Griffin, who recently has turned his attention to real estate,
would take the company private by buying out Trump's controlling
stock and all remaining shares.
   Griffin and Trump had engaged in bitter negotiations for control
of Resorts, but appeared to have come to terms about their
differences and worked out the deal now in question.
   Griffin has offered to pay Trump $135 a share, or $96 million,
for Trump's Class B stock. Trump also would receive another $63
million from Griffin to break Trump's management contract with
Resorts.
   Griffin's tender offer for Class A stockholders would cost him
$205.2 million. Griffin would also invest $50 million in Resorts to
help it generate enough cash flow to cover interest payments on
Resorts' debt.
   In turn, Trump would pay Resorts $273 million for the Taj Mahal.
