<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Refugees     10-11 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Refugees,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. High Commission Increases Budget For Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. High Commission for Refugees Tuesday
increased its 1988 budget by $43 million to help the world's 12
million refugees, the head of the agency said.
   Jean-Pierre Hocke said the 1988 target budget of $420 million,
up from the original $377 million, was approved by the agency's
Executive Committee at a meeting on Monday. Hocke said the High
Commission was about $100 million short of funding the new budget.
   The 43-nation committee also targeted $428.7 million for the
1989 budget.
   In 1988, the High Commission allocated the most money _ $46.3
million _ for refugees in Pakistan, followed by $42.9 million for
those in Sudan and $37.6 million in Somalia.
   Hocke told reporters that in Africa alone, the number of
refugees increased by 1 million in the past 12 months because of
the flow of refugees into Malawi and Ethiopia.
   He noted the Geneva peace accord aimed at ending the war in
Afghanistan, the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war, and the positive
prospects for peace in Namibia and Angola, favored the world's
refugees.
   ``If everything goes well, about half of the world's refugees
will have benefited from solutions within several years,'' either
by repatriation or resettlement, Hocke said.
   He said 75 percent of the world's 12 million refugees are women
and children under the age of 16.
</TEXT>
