<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficialEnglish     10-11 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Official English,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida English Foes Seek Federal Injunction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of a proposed state constitutional
amendment to make English the state's official language went to
federal court Tuesday to try to knock the measure off the November
ballot.
   ``We are opposed to it,'' said Monsignor Bryan Walsh, a
spokesman for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami, on the steps
of U.S. District Court. ``We do not think that we have problems in
Florida which merit such a constitutional amendment.''
   He said the diocese was supporting the effort to block Amendment
11.
   A group called Florida English circulated petitions to get the
amendment on the November ballot. If approved, the measure would
require all state business be conducted in English.
   Opponents and supporters of the measure, however, disagree over
what changes would be required under the amendment.
   In their suit, the opponents argue that the petitions circulated
throughout the state were only written in English.
   ``Florida is a state that is extensively populated by persons
whose primary language is not English,'' says the suit, filed on
behalf of four U.S. citizens of Mexican, Cuban and Puerto Rican
descent.
   Citing a U.S. District Court decision in Colorado, the suit
argues that the Voting Right Act of 1965 mandates that the
petitions be circulated in minority languages in counties where
more than 5 percent of the residents speak that language.
   Seven southern Florida counties fall in that category because of
their Spanish-speaking population, according to the U.S. Census
Bureau.
   For example, in Dade County, which includes Miami, 40 percent to
50 percent of the population speaks Spanish as their first language.
   Supporters of the Official English initiative were angered by
the suit.
   ``It's an outrage that people will be deprived of the
opportunity to vote `yes' or `no' on this if the lawsuit
succeeds,'' said Pat Fulton, spokeswoman for Florida English.
   State officials never told them they must circulate petitions in
Spanish, she said, and her group contends the Voting Rights Act
applies to governments, not private organizations.
   ``We will be responding to it on a legal basis,'' she said. ``We
are also asking people to phone their legislator to complain that
they are being disenfranchised if such an injuction is granted.''
   In Tallahassee, Gov. Bob Martinez said he agreed with the
objectives of the suit.
   ``I think it's a known fact to this country we didn't use
English only to assimilate Italian-Americans, German-Americans or
anyone else, and this nation's been doing that for way over a
century,'' Martinez said.
   The suit, filed against Secretary of State Jim Smith and local
elections officials, was assigned to U.S. District Judge James
Kehoe. It seeks an injunction preventing the issue from appearing
on the ballot and preventing the state from counting the votes.
Kehoe is out of town until Monday and no hearing has been set.
   In Colorado, a federal judge recently took that state's
official-English initiative off the ballot because the petitions
were not circulated in Spanish as well as English in Colorado's 12
heavily Hispanic counties.
   That ruling could affect not only other initiatives on this
year's ballot in Colorado, but laws passed by previous initiatives
and 36 initiatives pending in 11 states, according to Steve
Workings of the Washington-based U.S. English.
   Fourteen states have adopted official English proposals to date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
