<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--KingAppeal     10-11 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--King Appeal,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Files For New Trial In Globe Libel Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for former Gov. Edward J. King filed
a motion for a new trial Tuesday in a libel suit against The Boston
Globe.
   A Suffolk Superior Court jury on Sept. 29 ruled that, while a
1981 Globe column was false, it didn't libel King. In filing his
motion, Robert H. Goldman asks the court to set aside the judgment
and schedule a new trial.
   The column alleged that King had telephoned the judge in a
controversial rape case seeking a tougher sentence. King and the
judge both denied the call ever took place.
   The jury was asked to answer two questions. It agreed that
former Globe columnist David Farrell was wrong when he wrote in a
Nov. 8, 1981, column that King called a judge to demand harsher
sentences in a gang-rape case.
   But the jurors said no when asked if they believed the statement
discredited King. King needed to prevail on each question.
   In his motion, Goldman said, ``The court erred in instructing
the jury that as a matter of law no crime was alleged in the
statement in issue.''
