<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PoliceTrial     10-11 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Trial,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Detectives Sentenced For Shaking Down Bars, Restaurants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven current and former city police detectives
were sentenced Tuesday to federal prison terms ranging from two to
five years for soliciting bribes from restaurant and bar owners.
   They were convicted Sept. 13 of federal charges of conspiring to
extort more than $18,000 in return for protecting the
establishments from inspections, overlooking violations or seeking
to influence liquor cases in court or before the city's Licensing
Board.
   Prosecutors Diane Kottmyer and James Farmer accused the
detectives of selling their badges for influence while defense
attorneys maintained that the detectives were only accepting gifts
from people they worked with closely over several years.
   ``They sold the public trust in return for personal gain,''
Kottmyer said.
   The prosecutors had sought longer sentences, but they said they
were satisfied. ``The message is that police officers, just like
all other citizens, are bound by the constraints of the law.''
   In handing out sentences well below those recommended by
prosecutors, U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone said: ``It's
difficult not to be impressed by their records.''
   All seven defendants remain free on their own recognizance
pending appeals to the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The officers were indicted last year following an investigation
of more than six years by the New England Organized Strike Force,
whose last major case was the prosecution of Boston mobster Gennaro
Angiulo.
   The trial lasted more than eight weeks.
   Two defendants also were convicted of 19 and 18 counts of mail
fraud in connection with a scheme to extort $15,000 for a police
detail that they never performed.
   A group of detectives handed out a press release after the
sentencing, saying they had attended the hearing ``to demonstrate
our support for our seven brothers who are the victims of a
terrible injustice by overzealous prosecutors.''
</TEXT>
