<HEAD>American Feared For Family During Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American man broke down in
tears Tuesday as he told a court about his fears for his wife and
daughter during a 1985 TWA hijacking in which a Navy diver was
beaten and killed.
   Leo Byron, testifying at the murder and air piracy trial of
Mohammed Ali Hamadi, said Hamadi's alleged accomplice kicked
Byron's 13-year-old daughter and that Hamadi struck other
passengers.
   Byron, 52, also said he saw Navy diver Robert Stethem after the
hijackers had beaten the sailor severely.
   ``His face was puffy. He was very raw or bloody in the neck
area. He appeared to be dazed,'' said Byron. Stethem was later shot
and killed.
   Witnesses' hometowns were not given for security reasons.
   Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage for 17 days after the
jetliner was commandeered on June 14, 1985 during a Rome-to-Athens
flight and forced to land three times in Beirut and twice in
Algiers.
   Byron sobbed as he told of his terror in not knowing what the
hijackers would do to his daughter, Pam, and his wife.
   ``When my wife and Pam were taken to the back of the plane, I
tried to watch them ... but I didn't see them,'' he said.
   He said he was relieved when his daughter came back to say she
and her mother would be among a group of passengers who were
released in Algiers.
   Byron said that shortly after the hijacking began, the hijackers
ordered passengers to sit in a crouched position. Hamadi then began
striking passengers, Byron said, adding that he was hit on the head
and hands.
   ``The taller hijacker kicked Pam in the shoulder,'' said Byron.
   He also said he heard screams and rhythmic beatings later at the
front of the plane.
   Byron sobbed again as he recalled the shot that mortally wounded
Stethem at Beirut airport.
   ``It was a pop,'' said Byron. ``I'm familiar with guns, so I
knew it was a gunshot.''
   But Byron said he did not see who fired the shot. Hamadi admits
that he was one of the hijackers, but denies killing Stethem.
   Hamadi listened intently to the testimony in the heavily guarded
courtroom inside Frankfurt's Preungesheim prison. Outside the
courthouse, police were on patrol, some with machine guns.
   Earlier Tuesday, another American held captive on the jetliner
testified that Stetham, of Waldorf, Md., was so severely beaten he
could barely walk.
   ``He was mobile, but he was staggering in his walk and was being
supported by (chief flight attendant) Uli Derickson,'' said the
American, Sarah Ashmore, 50.
   ``He was moaning and groaning and Uli was trying to keep him
quiet,'' said Ms. Ashmore, who frequently pressed her hands against
her head during the testimony.
   Ms. Ashmore testified that Hamadi robbed her.
   Looking directly at Hamadi, she said: ``This is the man who
searched me. This is the man who took my jewelry.''
   Court documents indicate the hijackers stole jewelry, cash,
cameras and other valuables from passengers.
   Ms. Ashmore said she had no doubt about the identities of the
two hijackers. ``I spent a long time staring at them.''
   The other alleged hijacker, Hassan Ezzeddine, is still at large.
   Ms. Ashmore also told the court she heard the shot that killed
Stethem.
   ``I heard the shot and the body drop, but I couldn't see
anything,'' she said.
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem, have attended
each session of the trial, which began July 5.
   Hamadi was arrested Jan. 13, 1987 at Frankfurt airport after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
