<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WellsFargo     10-11 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wells Fargo,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Trial Opens With Heated Court Exchanges, Call for
Mistrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key defendant in the $7.1 million Wells
Fargo robbery admitted Tuesday that he agreed before the heist to
accept the money for the Puerto Rican independence movement.
   The revelation by Juan Segarra Palmer came as he and four
co-defendants went on trial in U.S. District Court in Hartford
after more than three years of pretrial proceedings.
   The first day of the trial before a packed court room was
highlighted by surprising disclosures, heated exchanges, a motion
for a mistrial and stern lectures by Judge T. Emmet Clarie.
   The government also called its first witness, a former Wells
Fargo security guard who was tied up during the Sept. 12, 1983,
robbery at the company's West Hartford depot.
   The $7.1 million theft was the second-largest cash robbery in
U.S. history. The only money ever recovered was the torn halves of
a $10 bill.
   In addition to the Segarra, 38, the others standing trial are:
Carolos Ayes Suarez, 29; Norman Ramirez Talavera, 32; Roberto
Maldonado Rivera, 52; and Antonio Comacho Negron, 43, all residents
of Puerto Rico.
   The government contends that all five were members of a group
known as Los Macheteros, which advocates independence for Puerto
Rico and which the government contends is a terrorist organization.
   The defendants are accused of participating in a conspiracy to
plot the heist, to transport the stolen money out of the country
and to distribute the money.
   Both the prosecution and the defense agree that the robbery was
committed singlehandedly by Victor M. Gerena, a former Wells Fargo
security guard. He is accused of overpowering two co-workers and
fleeing with the millions.
   The trial of nine other defendants has been postponed while the
government appeals a ruling tossing out some evidence collected
through wiretaps. Two other defendants pleaded guilty last month.
   ``It took years to perpetrate the offense and it will take
months to prove it,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Albert Dabrowski told
the jury in his opening remarks.
   Segarra's attorney, Leonard Weinglass, said although his client
knew in advance that the heist would occur and received stolen
money, he was innocent of the crimes with which he has been
charged. Segarra faces 17 counts, including robbery, but no charge
of receiving stolen funds.
   Weinglass said Gerena decided on his own to rob Wells Fargo to
support Los Macheteros. Segarra said he was not a member of the
group.
   Gerena has not been seen since the robbery. The government
believes he is probably in Cuba.
   The opening remarks became heated when Maldonado, an attorney
defending himself, said: ``If I'm guilty of all the charges, I
could go to jail for 55 years.''
   The judge told him the remarks were improper. When Maldanado
persisted, the judge said he was ready to cite him for contempt.
   Clarie then got into another exchange with Juan Ramon Acevedo,
who is representing Ramirez. Acevedo said the defense intended to
put the FBI on trial as part of its claim that the defendants are
being prosecuted for political reasons.
   Clarie was visibly angry as he raised his gavel and issued a
warning, saying the remarks were inappropriate.
   The defense later asked for mistrial because of Clarie's remarks
to Acevedo and Maldonado. The judge denied the motion.
   The first witness was Timothy R. Girard, a former Wells Fargo
guard and Gerena's partner. He told the court how Gerena held a gun
to his supervisor's head and ordered Girard to lie on the floor of
the depot.
   Girard said he was bound, gagged and left behind as Gerena took
about an hour to load cash into a car and flee.
</TEXT>
