<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Senate     10-11 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Senate,360</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says GOP Can Regain Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Tuesday that Republicans
have ``a real shot at getting back control of the Senate'' in this
year's elections, which he painted as ``a referendum on
liberalism.''
   In a speech prepared for delivery at a reception for two western
GOP senatorial candidates, Reagan predicted voters will reject
``senators who talk conservative back home but vote liberal in
Washington.''
   His remarks were aimed at Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont., who is
opposed by Yellowstone County Commissioner Conrad Burns; and Sen.
Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., facing a challenge from Minority Leader
Earl Strinden of the North Dakota House of Representatives.
   Republicans won control of the Senate with Reagan's election as
president in 1980, but lost it in 1986. Democrats now hold control
by a margin of 54-46.
   Reagan, who has been stepping up the pace of his campaign
activity as the Nov. 8 voting approaches, told the Republican
gathering, ``This is a great time of year because it gives me an
opportunity to get out and around and spread some gospel.''
   ``I've been out on the campaign trail lately and I'm just
starting to wonder if this year there isn't something in the air,''
he said.
   He said Sen. Rudy Boschwitz of Minnesota, chairman of the
National Republican Senatorial Committee, and Senate GOP leader Bob
Dole of Kansas deserve ``enormous credit because far from being
discouraged they've realized that with voter interest much higher
in this presidential year there's a real shot at getting back
control of the Senate.''
   ``You see, all the issues we had so much trouble getting out
there in 1986 are automatically there in 1988 _ the public is
beginning to realize that this election is a referendum on
liberalism,'' he said.
   ``And when the good conservative voters of Montana and North
Dakota begin to realize that the opponents of Conrad Burns and Earl
Strinden are nothing less than hard-core liberals _ senators who
talk conservative back home but vote liberal in Washington _ they
are not going to be happy.''
   Reagan flies to Pennsylvania and New Jersey on Wednesday to
campaign for Republican candidates.
</TEXT>
