<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadets Stricken, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadet Is Rehospitalized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd with inquest into 1985 death
ordered. Deletes now-outdated grafs 12-13.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of several cadets stricken by a
kidney ailment during police training last month re-entered the
hospital Tuesday with intestinal bleeding, officials said.
   Cadet Joseph Metcalfe of Ludlow was in guarded condition at the
intensive care unit following surgery at Baystate Medical Center,
said hospital officials.
   A nursing supervisor said shortly after Metcalfe was admitted,
``He's bleeding heavily and is pretty bad.''
   Also Tuesday, Secretary of Public Safety Charles V. Barry
recommended an inquest into the 1985 death of a state police cadet
after meeting Tuesday with Medical Examiner Brian Blackbourne and
Public Safety Commissioner William McCabe.
   James Whitehouse of Braintree was 22 when he died on the second
day of training at the state police academy in Framingham. A
medical examiner ruled that he died from a genetic disorder, but
the doctor has since called for the state to reopen the case,
saying he made his diagnosis on the basis of faulty information,
including police claims that Whitehouse had been exercising only
moderately.
   Metcalfe was in the class of 50 cadets who apparently underwent
strenuous exercise with little water the first day of class, Sept.
19, at a police academy in Agawam, which provides uniform training
for police departments in the 74 towns and cities of western
Massachusetts.
   Metcalfe was hospitalized for at least two days that week with
kidney problems that required dialysis treatment, authorities said.
Fifteen other cadets were also hospitalized for ailments from heat
stroke to exhaustion and dehydration.
   Timothy Shepard, 25, of Pittsfield, the only other cadet still
hospitalized Tuesday, remained in critical condition at the
Pittsburgh hospital where he underwent a liver transplant two weeks
ago.
   Metcalfe's boss, Ludlow Police Chief John Jorge, said he
believed the cadet suffered a relapse after his doctor allowed him
back to the academy last week.
   The nursing supervisor said he didn't know if Metcalfe's
rehospitalization was related to his police training, but said the
cadet had been healthy before beginning training.
   The state Department of Public Safety has suspended such
discipline techniques as pushups and laps at the state's six police
academies, but it was unclear if physical training had resumed.
Department spokesmen were at meetings Tuesday and did not
immediately return telephone calls.
   At least four state investigations are under way into the cause
of the hospitalizations and the regimen at the state-run academy.
   At least a dozen state representatives headed for a meeting
Tuesday on their investigation of academy practices. The committee
has said it will submit recommendations to the full state House by
Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
