<DOCNO> AP881011-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Politics     10-11 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Politics,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Vote Postponed After Lack of Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Tuesday postponed a vote on whose
outcome Premier Ciriaco De Mita has staked the future of his
6-month-old government.
   The vote is on a measure to eliminate most secret voting in the
Chamber of Deputies, the lower house. Voting was set for late
Tuesday, but was put off to Wednesday at the earliest after the
rules committee failed to agree on the exact text.
   De Mita indicated last Saturday that he will resign if the
reform fails to pass. The premier was scheduled to leave on
Thursday for Moscow.
   The five parties in his coalition _ De Mita's Christian
Democrats, the Socialists, Republicans, Liberals and Social
Democrats _ pledged to abolish most secret voting when they formed
the government in April.
   The reform is aimed at reining in ``snipers,'' lawmakers from
government parties who vote in secret against party line. The
practice has weakened many of Italy's governments. De Mita's is the
48th government since World War II.
   The vote on the measure will itself be secret and thus snipers
could be critical.
   The Senate will consider its own version of the reform
separately.
</TEXT>
