<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CIA-Settlement     10-11 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CIA-Settlement,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US to Pay Former Patients Drugged in CIA Experiment $750,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Tuesday announced a
final settlement providing $750,000 to nine people who were
subjected to mind-control experiments by their psychiatrist, whose
research was aided by a CIA front organization.
   The CIA in the late 1950s granted $60,000 to Dr. Ewen Cameron, a
Canadian and former president of the World Psychiatric Association
as well as the Canadian and American psychiatric associations, who
used the money to conduct a series of experiments with his patients.
   He subjected the patients to drug-induced sleep therapy for
weeks at a time, gave them LSD and administered electroshock
therapy at up to 75 times the usual intensity.
   Cameron's goal, to reprogram behavior, caught the attention of
CIA officials at a time when the agency was concerned with
countering purported Soviet and Chinese breakthroughs in
brainwashing and interrogation techniques.
   The CIA initiated a chemical-biological warfare research project
known as MKULTRA, to aid in eforts.
   The nine former patients of Cameron brought a suit in 1980 in
U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., and a tentative settlement
with the CIA, now given final approval, was disclosed last week in
court.
</TEXT>
