<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Evangelists-Sex     10-11 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Evangelists-Sex,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Evangelists Convicted Of Running Boy Sex Ring</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three evangelists who traveled the Southern
revival circuit pleaded guilty Tuesday to running an interstate sex
ring of boys they recruited with gifts and money and then molested.
   Mario ``Tony'' Leyva, Rias Edward Morris and Freddie M. Herring
entered guilty pleas to federal charges they used the Tony Leyva
Evangelistic Association Inc., based in Columbus, Ga., to recruit
boys for homosexual prostitution.
   Dozens of boys told investigators they were given money, lodging
and gifts in return for letting the preachers molest them. The
evangelists were not accused of selling the boys' services to
others.
   Leyva took the witness stand and said he had molested at least
100 boys, beginning in the 1960s in North Carolina, where he began
having sex with the young brothers of his wife, from whom he has
since been divorced.
   FBI Special Agent John Terry said an investigation had uncovered
dozens of the preachers' victims in the South and Midwest.
   ``Four of the boys stated they were victims of all three,''
Terry said. ``Six of the boys were victims of at least two. The
victims ranged from an 8-year-old on up to the mid-teens.''
   Leyva pleaded guilty to conspiracy and four counts of shipping
minors across state lines for prostitution. The charges carry a
penalty of 45 years in prison, but Assistant U.S. Attorney Jennie
Montgomery agreed to seek a maximum of 20 years in a child
molesters' prison unit in Butner, N.C.
   The preachers will undergo psychiatric evaluations at the
pedophile unit beginning Oct. 25.
   Morris, Leyva's ministry organist, pleaded guilty to conspiracy
and three counts of aiding and abetting the interstate transport of
a minor for prostition. The charges carry a penalty of 35 years in
prison, but the prosecutor agreed to ask for no more than 15 years.
   Herring, founder of the Lighthouse Assembly in Douglasville,
Ga., pleaded guilty to one count of interstate transportation of a
minor for homosexual prostitution and one count of aiding and
abetting interstate transportation of a minor for prostitution. The
counts carry 20 years in prison, but the plea bargain calls for a
maximum sentence of 15 years.
   ``I'm sorry that this happened, and I hope that their hurt will
not linger,'' Herring testified. ``I'm asking for their
forgiveness.''
   Ms. Montgomery said the plea agreements were a good deal for the
government as well as for the victims who did not have to relive
their molestation by testifying.
   The indictment alleged that the Pentecostal preachers abused
boys in Virginia, North Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi,
Louisiana, Arkansas, Ohio and Indiana. Police received complaints
about Leyva over the years, but usually by the time they got them,
he had crossed state lines en route to the next revival, making it
hard for a case to be built, Ms. Montgomery said.
   Up to seven more preachers were identified as child molesters
when the FBI questioned Leyva, Morris and Herring, she said. The
offenses sounded like local crimes and she said she would turn over
information to authorities in Indiana, Mississippi and Alabama.
   Last month, Leyva was convicted by a Roanoke County Circuit
Court jury of two counts of oral sodomy on teen-age boys and
recommended that he receive counseling during a two-and-a-half-year
prison term.
</TEXT>
