<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government, Politburo Members Chosen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 6 grafs SUB for grafs 5-6 pvs, The changes ... the Politburo.
BACKGROUND on leadership's caution, 1968 invasion. Picks up 7th
graf pvs, Fojtik said ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party leadership
made changes at the top of the party and government Tuesday in a
meeting that also expressed clear opposition to sweeping economic
or political reform.
   Ladislav Adamec, 62-year-old premier of the Czech lands, was
chosen as new federal premier to replace Lubomir Strougal, who
resigned Monday after more than 18 years in the job and gave up his
seat on the Communist Party's ruling Politburo.
   Jaromir Johanes becomes foreign minister, replacing Bohuslav
Chnoupek. He has been first deputy foreign minister since July 1987
and is a former ambasssador to Canada and the United States.
   Interior Minister Vratislav Vajnar, 58, will be replaced by
Frantisek Kincl.
   The changes were made at a two-day meeting of the party Central
Committee session, which ended Tuesday, and were announced at a
news conference by Jan Fojtik, the new party ideologist. He also
said five men were made full members of the Politburo, increasing
the membership from 12 to 15.
   Peter Colotka, who resigned as premier of Slovakia on Monday,
also stepped down from the Politburo.
   Czechoslovakia's leaders appear to have been discouraged by
developments in neighboring Hungary and Poland. Efforts toward
reform there, or public demand for it, have created serious
problems for the communist governments.
   This country has no shortage of basic consumer goods and the
foreign debt and inflation are comparatively low.
   Vasil Bilak, a hardline member, remained on the Politburo but
now is in charge of foreign policy because Fojtik has been given
Bilak's old job as party ideologist.
   Bilak and party chief Milos Jakes are among only a few senior
officials left from the leadership installed after a Soviet-led
invasion crushed Alexander Dubcek's brief ``Prague Spring''
liberalization in 1968.
   Fojtik said Rudolf Rohlicek, first deputy premier, will be in
charge of the government until the changes can be approved by the
parliament next month.
   Ladislav Gerle, in charge of the recently created ``super
ministry'' including metallurgy, engineering and electrotechnical
industry, is being replaced by Karel Julis, 59, a former Czech
minister of education, youth and physical training.
   Savotpluk Potac, head of the State Planning Commission, gave way
to Bohumil Urban.
   New Politburo members are Miroslav Zavadil, 56; Miroslav Stepan,
43; Karel Urbanek, 47; Frantisek Pitra, 56, and Ivan Knotek, 52.
   Fojtik said Colotka would become ambassador to France and Knotek
would replace him as premier of Slovakia.
   Strougal, 63, was considered the chief advocate of economic
reforms, but observers said party conservatives diluted his plans.
   In a long speech to the Central Committee on Monday, Fojtik made
clear that the leadership opposes radical political and economic
changes similar to those Mikhail S. Gorbachev is promoting in the
Soviet Union.
   According to the text distributed Tuesday by the official news
agency CTK, he expressed support for cautious reform and emphasized
the party's leading role.
   ``One of the most fundamental lessons of the past is that in
looking for and pursuing new ways of development, we must under no
circumstances permit the weakening of the leading role of the
Communist Party,'' Fojtik said.
   He warned of ``private-ownership petit-bourgeois ideology'' and
rejected foreign criticism of Czechosovakia's tough approach to
dissident movements.
   ``We must not close our eyes to any of the risks of reform,''
the party ideologist said. ``Superficial journalism, and here we
are not speaking only about our own authors, makes light of some
(of these problems) or passes them over in silence altogether while
dramatizing others.''
</TEXT>
