<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-11 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls in Michigan, Sleet in Northern Indiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell in Michigan and sleet was reported in Indiana Tuesday,
while other parts of the nation got scattered showers.
   Upper Michigan and the eastern part of the state received some
snowfall in the afternoon, but it was too light to measure. Frost
and freeze warnings were posted for Tuesday night across Indiana
except for the northeast corner. Fort Wayne and South Bend, Ind.,
got some sleet during the day.
   Rain was widely scattered over the rest of lower Michigan and
northern Indiana, as well as western New York state, northwest
Pennsylvania and northern Ohio. Thunderstorms also were scattered
over the southern coast of Maine and over northeast California into
northwest Nevada.
   An inch of snow fell at Mount Washington, N.H., during the six
hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   The nation's low for the morning was 12 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 92 at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Wednesday's forecast called for rainshowers reaching west from
the lower Great Lakes across the northern half of the Appalachians,
changing to snow in the higher elevations. Skies should be cloudy
along the northern Pacific Coast, with gusty winds over the
northern Rockies.
   High temperatures should be in the 30s and 40s from the Great
Lakes across the northern half of the Appalachians and northern New
England. Highs in 50s and 60s should be the rule from central New
England across the Carolinas, from the Ohio Valley across the
Tennessee Valley and inland portions of the central Gulf of Mexico
states, the upper Mississippi Valley, eastern Kansas and Nebraska,
the Dakotas, the Pacific Northwest and the northern California
coast. Highs should rise into the 80s over much of the Florida
peninsula, southern Texas and inland California, reaching into the
90s to near 100 through the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
