<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     10-11 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Voids Elections of Candidates Backed by Strike Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men won seats in Armenia's legislature with
support from leaders of strikes that paralyzed the southern
republic for weeks, but Armenian authorities voided their
elections, an activist said Tuesday.
   Their victories were among the first in which unofficial
candidates defeated Communist Party nominees.
   A high-ranking Communist who had certified the two men's
elections was kicked out of the party and faces dismissal from his
government job, the official news agency Tass reported.
   It said the bureaucrat falsified the election returns by
certifying H. Stamboltsyan as a winner.
   Stamboltsyan and candidate Ashot Manucharian were backed by the
Karabakh Committee, activist Galstyan Ambartsum said. The committee
wants the Nagorno-Karabakh region of neighboring Azerbaijan, whose
population is predominantly Armenian, to be made part of Armenia.
   The Karabakh Committee organized strikes. The ethnic dispute led
to arson and gunfights, and the central government sent soldiers
with tanks to Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh last month.
   Soviet officials say the situation in both areas has stabilized
and workers have been returning to their jobs.
   Ambartsum, a member of the Karabakh Committee, said by telephone
from Yerevan, capital of Armenia, that the group put up two
candidates in an interim election for three seats in the Supreme
Soviet of Armenia.
   He said Stamboltsyan beat the interior minister, the republic's
top police official, by a 4-1 margin and Manucharian got 70 percent
of the vote against the foreign minister. Neither he nor Tass said
when the election was held.
   On Monday, the Central Committee of the Armenian Communist Party
threw out Stamboltsyan's victory on grounds he was not a registered
candidate, Ambartsum said. Tass said Stamboltsyan ``had not been
registered and did not receive a majority of the votes of all the
voters of the district.''
   Tass did not mention Manucharian. Ambartsum said the leadership
canceled Manucharian's victory by saying that he had to win with 75
percent of the vote, which the activist declared to be a lie.
   Several non-party members backed by unofficial citizen groups
have won local offices this year in the Baltic republics of
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
   According to Tass, the Armenian Central Committee expelled K.L.
Mandalyan, from the party and recommended he lose his job in the
bureaucracy for certifying Stamboltsyan's victory.
   It said Mandalyan presided over a meeting of the local election
commission and pushed through acceptance of the victory while only
six of the 14 members were present. The agency said he delivered
the documentation to the Karabakh Committee, which announced the
victory in Yerevan's central square.
   Mandalyan's action was a ``deliberate political provocation''
that fired ethnic and nationalist passions, the local party
committee said. Tass reported that V. Galumyan, the republic's vice
president, was reprimanded for failing to prevent Mandalyan's
action.
</TEXT>
