<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-11 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Capture Fourth Provincial Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem insurgents captured a fourth
provincial capital in Afghanistan, a guerrilla spokesman said
Tuesday, and Western diplomats said several others were under siege.
   The diplomats reported rocket attacks on several provincial
capitals and airports, and said the rebels closed a strategic road,
reducing the supply of food to Kabul, the capital.
   The rebel spokesman, Asim Nasser-Zia of the National Islamic
Front of Afghanistan, said Asadabad, capital of northeastern Kunar
province, fell to guerrillas Monday after a month-long campaign. He
said the victory gave insurgents control of the entire province,
which borders Pakistan.
   The reported victory also opens a northern route to Kabul and
gives guerrillas access to Jalalabad. Asadabad is about 12 miles
from Pakistan, where border towns and refugee camps serve as
guerrilla bases, and 100 miles northeast of Kabul.
   Moslem insurgents began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and the Soviet Union sent military forces to Afghanistan in
December 1979. Under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed last April,
the Soviets have been withdrawing their estimated 115,000 soldiers.
   The guerrillas were not a party to the agreement between
Pakistan and Afghanistan, which the Soviet Union and United States
signed as guarantors, and vowed to conmtinue fighting.
   They claim to have overrun several Afghan army garrisons and two
provincial capitals in two weeks, bringing the number of capitals
in their hands to four.
   Sharan, capital of Paktika province in the east, was reported
captured early last week, and diplomats confirmed it.
   Guerrillas also claim to control the capitals of Takhar province
in northern Afghanistan and Bamyan in the center of the mountainous
nation.
   Mohammad Ishaq, spokesman for the Khalis faction of the
Hezb-E-Islami guerrilla group, said several strategic garrisons in
Kunar province were captured along with Asadabad.
   Diplomats said 20-25 rockets are fired every day at the airport
in Kandahar, a southern city. They said the airport in Lashkargah,
capital of western Helmand province, has been closed to civilian
trafic. Airports are regular guerrilla targets.
   Busloads of wounded arrived in Kabul after the bombing of
villages near Maidan Shahr, capital of central Wardak province,
diplomats reported. Guerrillas captured Maidan Shahr earlier but
were pushed out by heavy bombing, rebels and diplomats reported.
   Guerrillas said they had closed the Kabul-Jalalabad highway and
diplomats said no traffic moved east from the capital between Oct.
2-6.
   A report by the official Afghan media said 199 rockets hit the
eastern city of Gardez last week, killing five people. Twenty
people were reported killed by rockets Monday in Jalalabad and
Kabul also is a regular target of guerrilla rockets.
</TEXT>
