<DOCNO> AP881011-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0691 10-11 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0691,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Trying to Scare People About Foreign Ownership</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with protests, INSERT six grafs after 4th pvs, ``We
will..., picking up 5th graf pvs, Bush's harshest...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush promised on Tuesday to
crack down on white-collar crime, including insider trading in
stocks, saying people guilty of such activities ``may wear fancy
suits'' but are dangerous all the same.
   Bush also took Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis to
task for his recent criticism of foreign ownership of U.S.
businesses. Bush said, ``My opponent needs an issue, and he's
willing to scare people to find it.''
   His remarks, prepared for delivery to the Seattle University
Business School, were released just before he left Washington, D.C.
for the West Coast. Bush is to spend the next few days in light
campaigning and in preparing for Thursday night's debate with
Democrat Dukakis in Los Angeles.
   ``We will throw the book at insider traders and other
white-collar criminals,'' said the Republican presidential nominee.
``They may not carry guns and they may wear fancy suits, but they
are a real danger to society, and they should be hit with the
maximum penalties of the law.''
   Bush's speech to the Catholic college was disrupted by shouting
from a Jesuit priest, who was forcibly removed from the room by
police and taken away in a squad car. He identified himself as
William Bichsel, who operates a program for the homeless in nearby
Tacoma.
   ``Isn't this a great country. You csn run into all kinds of
characters in my line of work,'' Bush said, continuing with his
speech. ``This one ... amazing.''
   Bichsel shouted questions at Bush about the homeless and, as he
was led away, said: ``They stand for the complete destruction of
the people of this country and abroad. The rich grow richer and
poor grow poorer.''
   Another protester, John Whitney, 30, a philosophy teacher at the
college, also shouted questions at Bush, but left the room when
officials asked him to and was not arrested.
   Whitney, who said he was an associate of Bichsel's, complained
that only business students and faculty were invited to the speech,
and that questions were not permitted.
   ``I stood up because he would not answer questions of
students,'' said Whitney, who was wearing a Dukakis button. ``I
thought the school was being used.''
   Bush's harshest words came in his criticism of the Democratic
candidate's recent assault on foreign ownership.
   ``Frankly, I've been surprised at my opponent's recent turn to
protectionist demagoguery,'' Bush said. ``I don't think he really
believes it. He ran against this so-called `economic nationalism'
in the primaries. But now, for political reasons, he sees advantage
in stoking fears about foreign influence.''
   Bush said that ``like the Know Nothing Party a century before
him,'' Dukakis had ``turned to fear of foreigners. ... Or maybe
with this latest flip-flop, he's become a believe-nothing
candidate.''
   Last week, Dukakis in a speech in Missouri voiced concern about
a rise in foreign ownership of businesses and plants in the United
States.
   And he returned to the subject on Tuesday, asking college
students in Medford, Mass., ``Will we sell out more and more of our
land and our factories and our banks, or will we take charge of our
future?''
   Bush, on the other hand, said. ``Foreign investment in the
United States, whether it's in Wellston, Mo., or Marysville, Ohio,
or right here in Seattle, helps create jobs.''
   The vice president, for the second day in a row, appeared to go
out of his way to mention his running mate by name.
   ``Under the leadership of my running mate, Dan Quayle, we've
revamped our job training program so that it actually helps the
economically disadvantaged find jobs in the private sector,'' he
said.
   On Monday, at an airport rally in Trenton, N.J., Bush said, ``I
urge you to work for me and Dan Quayle.''
   Before this week, Bush hardly ever mentioned the Indiana
senator, who recent polls suggest has become a political liablity
to the vice president's campaign.
   In his remarks on white-collar crime, Bush said, ``For every
share of stock that is bought from someone with inside information,
there is an innocent investor who has paid too much for his or her
goods, just as surely as if a product was misrepresented in a
simple fraud.''
   Bush added, without elaboration, ``I am against business
journalists who buy stock in a company just before writing a
favorable story on that same company.''
   He took another swipe at the news media in the remarks prepared
for the audience of business students. ``I don't have to tell you
the image that many Americans, and many in the press, have of
business students,'' Bush said.
   ``Instead of recognizing that you're learning to help make our
economy run better, they've painted a picture of a generation only
concerned about quick and easy money,'' Bush said.
   From Seattle, Bush was going to Los Angeles to prepare for the
debate with Dukakis.
</TEXT>
