<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeamstersTrial     10-11 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters Trial,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerful Friedman Now Focus Of Teamsters' Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal embezzlement and racketeering trial
opening Wednesday that once centered on the late Jackie Presser
will now focus on a longtime Presser associate who has emerged as
Ohio's most powerful Teamsters official.
   Harold Friedman, 66, was indicted May 16, 1986, on two counts of
labor racketeering, two of embezzlement and two of making false
statements to the U.S. Department of Labor.
   The president of the 5,000-member Teamsters Local 507, founded
in Cleveland in 1967, is also an international vice president of
the union, the new president of the Ohio Conference of Teamsters
and the leader of Teamsters Joint Council 41 in northeast Ohio. He
also is president of Bakery Workers Local 19 in Cleveland.
   His co-defendant is Anthony Hughes, 52, Local 507 recording
secretary, who is charged with two counts of labor racketeering and
one count of embezzlement.
   Until recently, both Friedman and Hughes were overshadowed by
the defense of Presser, Teamsters president from 1983 until this
year and Local 507's secretary-treasurer. Presser, who was accused
in the indictment of masterminding the $700,000 scheme, died July 9.
   After numerous delays, the trial is set to begin Wednesday with
jury selection in U.S. District Court. On Oct. 3, questionnaires
were handed out to some 125 prospective jurors in an effort to save
lawyers time in the interrogation process needed to come up with a
12-person panel.
   The trial is expected to last four to six weeks.
   Federal prosecutors will try to prove that Friedman and Hughes
had a role in placing three ``ghosts,'' or people who were paid and
did no union work, on the Local 507 payroll.
   The jury trial will culminate a federal probe that first came to
light six years ago, on Oct. 8, 1982, when U.S. marshals and agents
of the Department of Labor inspector general's office seized
records at the Local 507 building.
   Federal prosecutors had considered the indictment in 1985, but
held back after FBI agents revealed Presser's FBI informant
relationship.
   Presser's defense, according to statements of defense attorney
John R. Climaco, would have been that Presser was told to place
certain men on the local's payroll and to keep them there, in order
to protect and enhance his informant role.
   The Justice Department's Strike Force Against Organized Crime
maintains that Presser never had such authorization.
   Unlike Presser, who made numerous public appearances as the
Teamsters leader and vowed to beat the government's case, Friedman
has never publicly commented, in line with his preference to shun
the press.
   Presser and Hughes have been identified in pre-trial documents
filed with U.S. District Judge George W. White as FBI informants,
who would provide their FBI ``handlers'' with information about
organized crime and Teamsters inner-politics. Friedman apparently
had no such FBI link, and court documents leave unclear whether he
knew anything about the others' FBI connection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
