<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iraq-Sanctions     10-11 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Sanctions,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Adopts Bill to Impose Sanctions Against Iraq for Alleged
Posion Gas Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday revived attempts to
impose punitive sanctions against Iraq for its alleged use of
poison gas against Kurdish civilians but eliminated sanctions
senators said would harm U.S. farm exporters.
   The 87-0 roll call vote by which the sanctions measure was
adopted was the third time the Senate has voted on the issue since
poison gas attacks by the Iraqi army were reported in late August.
   The Senate's third attempt to deal with the poison gas issue
came on a bill far less sweeping than sanctions legislation
originally adopted early in September. The new Senate bill closely
follows the line of legislation adopted by the House and represents
a compromise with three House committees.
   It would impose two sanctions immediately. They are:
   _ A ban on the export of munitions and certain high technology
items.
   _ A requirement that the United States oppose loans to Iraq by
international financial institutions such as the World Bank.
   The bill requires President Reagan to impose additional
sanctions by the end of the year if Iraq does not stop the use of
chemical weapons and provide verifiable assurances it will not
again use them.
   The president is required to choose from a list of potential
sanctions that include denying export-import credits, restricting
imports from Iraq, expanding restrictions on exports to Iraq and
downgrading of diplomatic relations.
   Contracts entered into prior to the imposition of sanctions
would be protected.
   Responding to the demands of senators representing farmers
producing such crops as rice or wheat, the legislation imposes no
limitation on agricultural exports to Iraq or the provision of
credit or credit guarantees for agricultural purchases.
   ``The concern is that this not lead to an embargo on
agricultural exports to Iraq,'' said Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., saying sanctions are fully justified
by ``the horrifying acts of the Iraqi government to systematically
eliminate its own citizens.''
   ``The world cannot stand by in the face of repeated use of
poison gas by Iraq,'' said Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn.
   But Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., complained that the measure unfairly
penalized U.S. manufacturers.
   ``Unilateral controls on U.S. agriculture do not work and they
don't work on medical equipment, personal computers or machine
tools,'' Heinz said, adding that Iraq would turn to other suppliers
if U.S. exports of those products were cut off.
   ``They're probably laughing at us in Iraq right now,'' Heinz
said, declaring that the bill would not cut off the export to Iraq
of the equipment and chemicals needed to produce such chemical
weapons as mustard gas and nerve gas.
   ``It shoots American exporters in the foot and does not get to
the root of the problem,'' he said.
</TEXT>
