<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Shows Rifle Expertise, Defends Democrats on Crime</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 8th pvs, ``If George..., to show
Philadelphia appearance, picking up 9th pvs, Bush has...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen took target practice at a police academy Tuesday,
then turned his rhetorical fire on George Bush, accusing the
Republican of ``playing politics with the tragedies of crime.''
   Bentsen watched a police-dog demonstration and then picked up an
AR-15 rifle _ the civilian version of the military M-16. The avid
sportsman fired three times and left a tight cluster of holes in
the silhouette target's chest.
   Asked if he were a quail hunter, Bentsen cracked jokes about
``Quayle season'' starting around the first week of November,
ending Nov. 8. ``I plan on bagging a Quayle that day at least,'' he
said, referring to his GOP vice presidential rival.
   Speaking afterward to the recruits at the Allentown police
academy, Bentsen said that while Bush talked about fighting crime,
``this administration has voted to either cut or do away with every
federal assistance program for local law enforcement.''
   The Democrats would add drug enforcement officers and U.S.
attorneys to prosecute cases against drug traffickers and ``put
those fellows in the slammer where they belong,'' he said.
   Later, at a rally in a Philadelphia union hall, Bentsen
ridiculed Bush's choice of Dan Quayle to head the drug interdiction
effort in his administration.
   ``George Bush wants us to follow Dan Quayle into battle,'' he
said. ``I'll tell you, I've been in combat, and I'll pass on that
one.
   ``If George Bush is serious about being president, why would he
chose Dan Quayle for being vice president.''
   Bush has repeatedly criticized Dukakis in connection with a case
in which a Massachusetts inmate attacked a Maryland couple after
failing to return from a furlough. That criticism is off target,
Bentsen said.
   ``When we get into the furlough program,'' he said, Bush was
``playing politics with the tragedies of crime.''
   Bentsen was highlighting the issues of drugs and crime _ areas
where the Democrats have suffered from Republican attack _ on a
one-day swing through eastern Pennsylvania and nearby New Jersey.
The Democrats are trying to get off the defensive on those issues.
   While Dukakis has tightened up Massachusetts' furlough program,
which he inherited from the previous governor, the federal
government has had an extensive furlough system of its own and
tragedies have occurred there also, Bentsen told the police
recruits.
   He said of the vice president, ``He has to assume
responsibility. He's been the second man in command of the
government.''
   Earlier, Bentsen told high school students in Blackwood, N.J.,
that a Democratic administration would separate the United States
from Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   ``You know that song, `Breaking Up Is Hard to Do''' he said in
response to a student question, drawing giggles from the crowd.
``Well, it's not going to be hard to do for Mike Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen.''
   ``What you've seen in George Bush and Noriega is kind of a
shotgun wedding,'' he said. The Democrats, he said, would initiate
``a very well publicized divorce from Mr. Noriega.''
   ``While this administration has been talking, illegal drugs have
been flooding our country at a record rate,'' he said in his speech
at Highland Regional High School, which he praised for declaring
itself a ``drug-free zone.''
   Asked about applying the death penalty to drug kingpins, Bentsen
said, ``Well, I'm one that favors it, but I must say reasonable
people can differ on that one.'' Dukakis opposes the death penalty.
   One student, noting talk about legalizing some drugs, asked
Bentsen if he saw ``any positive angle'' in that approach.
   ``No. That's my answer,'' he said. ``I just think you shouldn't
be able to go down to the grocery store and pick between the corn
flakes and the oatmeal and find a package of drugs.''
</TEXT>
