<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-O-Rings     10-11 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-O-Rings,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O-Rings From Both Shuttle Boosters Looking Good</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shuttle Astronauts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the O-rings on both booster
rockets from the space shuttle Discovery have been examined and
appear to be in excellent condition, a Morton Thiokol Inc. official
said Tuesday.
   A faulty O-ring was blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of
the shuttle Challenger and the deaths of all seven astronauts
aboard.
   Engineers worked around the clock at Cape Canaveral to take
apart the solid rocket motors that helped launch the Discovery
Sept. 29, said Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab.
   ``They disassembled the joints and then they did a visual
inspection of the O-rings,'' Raab said. ``They looked for soot,
charring, and there was none.''
   The seals might have been marred if gas from solid propellant
burning inside the motors reached them, but there was no evidence
that hot gases reached any of the 24 O-rings that had been
inspected as of Tuesday, Raab said.
   After separating from the shuttle two minutes into flight, the
boosters fell by parachute into the Atlantic Ocean and were towed
to shore the next day.
</TEXT>
