<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Aristide     10-11 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Aristide,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activist Priest Said Ready To Leave Haiti For Canada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ An activist Roman Catholic priest,
whose church was burned and parishioners killed in a massacre that
sparked the latest coup, will obey orders from his superiors and
leave Haiti, his friends said Tuesday.
   Thugs with guns, machetes, clubs and spikes invaded the Rev.
Jean-Bertrand Aristide's church, St. Jean Bosco, during Mass on
Sept. 11, killed 13 people and wounded more than 70. They burned
the church down.
   Aristide, an outspoken critic of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, who was
deposed as Haiti's leader on Sept. 17, said in a statement read
Monday over church-run Radio Soleil that he was told to leave Haiti
by Oct. 17.
   He did not say who issued the order for him to leave or whether
he would obey, and could not be reached for comment on Tuesday.
   Two of his friends, however, said Aristide received a letter
last Saturday from his Salecian Order superiors in Rome ordering
his transfer to St. Clair parish in Montreal.
   ``He is packing his bags,'' said Paul Dejean, director of the
Karo Leveque Center, a social works group.
   Stephan Francisque, a former Salecian priest who now is a social
worker, said Aristide received the letter ``from the correct
channels in Rome.''
   Radio Soleil reported Tuesday that 30 Catholic priests sent a
telegram to the order asking that Aristide be allowed to stay.
   A leftist organization, the National Popular Assembly, called
for a demonstration Friday in solidarity with Aristide. Previous
rumors of his departure from Haiti inspired demonstrations.
   Those who attacked Aristide's church were identified later as
Tonton Macoutes, members of the Duvalier dictatorship's brutal
private army. President Jean-Claude Duvalier fled the country in
February 1986, ending 29 years of rule by himself and his father
Francois, known as ``Papa Doc.''
   Soldiers who ousted Namphy and installed Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril
as president cited the massacre as one major reason for the coup.
   Aristide repeatedly denounced state-sponsored terrorism and
repression and advocates liberation theology, which holds that the
church should speak out against social injustice. Aristide calls
that ``active non-violence.''
   The Vatican does not support liberation theology and Aristide
has been warned before.
   A message sent to him by Haiti's bishops last Sunday said:
``There are not two churches; there is one.''
   The Salecians told Aristide to leave Haiti at least once
previously, but their letter arrived a day after the church
massacre and the priest was told he could stay.
   The Rev. Jean Marie, spokesman for the papal nuncio, Monsignor
Paolo Romeo, said the Vatican had ``nothing to do'' with Aristide's
transfer.
   On Sept. 30, supporters of the priest marched from the rubble of
St. Jean Bosco to the nuncio's suburban residence and accused Rome
of plotting Aristide's transfer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
