<HEAD>Prominent Gandhi Party Politician Among 13 Killed in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants killed 13 people in
Punjab Tuesday, including a leader of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's
Congress Party, two days before Gandhi's planned visit there, Press
Trust of India news agency reported.
   The extremists in northern Punjab state are fighting for an
independent Sikh nation.
   PTI said Bhagwan Dass, vice president of the Punjab state unit
of the Congress Party, his bodyguard and an unidentified man were
killed at Jaito Mandi in Faridkot district by five Sikh gunmen.
Faridkot is about 185 miles northwest of New Delhi.
   Gandhi is scheduled to visit Punjab on Thursday for a personal
assessment of flood damage there. Recent floods killed 462 people
in Punjab and three other northern states.
   Dass was a government minister in the party-led government in
Punjab in 1980.
   Other deaths at the hands of Sikh attackers were reported from
Ropar district, where two policemen were killed. Three people were
killed in Amritsar, one in Jalandhar, two in Ferozpur and two in
Bhatinda district.
   At least 13 people also were killed Tuesday in sectarian
violence in the north Indian town of Muzaffarnagar, 78 miles north
of New Delhi, the United News of India reported.
   It said the adminstration called in the army with orders to
shoot rioters on sight. UNI said Indian army units moved in after
new violence led to fears of violence escalating and spreading to
other areas.
   Indian news media did not specify the parties involved, as media
norms here prohibit mention of warring religious groups. But
informed sources in New Delhi, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Hindus and Moslems were involved in the riots.
   State-owned Indian television, Doordarshan, said 200 people were
arrested in the town on Tuesday. UNI said a curfew, which bars
people from streets, was imposed there Tuesday.
   The agency quoted an Uttar Pradesh state government police
official as saying the situation in Muzaffarnagar was
''explosive.'' It did not elaborate.
