<HEAD>Prosecutor Says He'll Sue Tawana Brawley and Her Advisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS CAROLA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FISHKILL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said Tuesday he will file
suit against a black teen-ager and her three advisers who falsely
accused him of involvement in an alleged sexual assault against her.
   Steven Pagones, a Dutchess County assistant district attorney,
was cleared by a grand jury of accusations he sexually attacked
Tawana Brawley, 16, formerly of nearby Wappingers Falls.
   The grand jury concluded Miss Brawley made up her story she was
attacked by six white men last year. The girl's advisers, without
offering evidence, had accused Pagones of being one of the
attackers.
   Pagones said lawyers are preparing a lawsuit that will be filed
within a month against Miss Brawley, the Rev. Al Sharpton and
attorneys C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr.
   Pagones had harsh words for the Brawley advisers, labeling their
verbal attacks as ``blatant, disgusting and deplorable lies.''
   Miss Brawley, who never cooperated with the grand jury during
its seven-month investigation, was found in Wappingers Falls last
Nov. 28 smeared with dog feces and with racial slurs scrawled on
her body. Wappingers Falls is about 70 miles north of New York City.
   Pagones announced the lawsuit at a news conference, which
Sharpton tried to interrupt by shouting through a hotel doorway,
``I'm here, Pagones. Your accuser's here. Why don't you give me the
papers?''
   A hotel employee closed the door on Sharpton and held it closed
for the rest of the news conference.
   Hayes would not say how much the lawsuit would be for, only that
it would be ``millions of dollars.''
   Pagones said he will also file a grievance against Mason and
Maddox and will seek discipline against the two lawyers for
``knowingly making false statements of law and fact.''
   ``I feel they should be disbarred,'' he said.
   Last week, state Attorney General Robert Abrams announced that
he asked for investigations of the lawyers for possible
disciplinary action.
   Miss Brawley denounced the grand jury's report, as did Sharpton,
Mason and Maddox.
   During the grand jury investigation, Pagones was questioned
about a friend of his, Harry Crist Jr., a part-time Fishkill
policeman who committed suicide three days after Miss Brawley was
found.
   Glenda Brawley, Tawana's mother, raised questions about Crist's
possible involvement in her daughter's alleged attack, but Crist
was also cleared by the grand jury.
   During the grand jury investigation, Pagones testified that he
and Crist were at a Connecticut shopping mall the day Miss Brawley
was found.
   ``They have made the past six months a living hell for the
parents and family of Harry Crist,'' Pagones said.
   He also criticized the media, calling it the ``life support
system'' for Sharpton, Maddox and Mason.
   ``This charade will not end until the media ends it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
