<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     10-11 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslems Respond to Christian Moves to Defuse Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem legislators on Tuesday called for
a prompt presidential election, echoing a group of Christian
lawmakers and raising hopes of ending a major constitutional crisis.
   The 16 pro-Syrian members of Parliament also rejected any kind
of partition and ruled out the rehabilitation of an estimated
500,000 Palestinians in south Lebanon.
   In a statement the group urged ``speedy and strong efforts to
break the presidential election deadlock and overcome the obstacles
and hardships that still prevail.''
   A similar call was made Monday by 29 Christian deputies who said
they had authorized Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, head of the dominant
Maronite Catholic community, to negotiate with rival Moslems to
elect a new head of state.
   The political crisis was triggered after Parliament failed three
times to elect a successor to President Amin Gemayel before his
6-year term expired Sept. 23. The Christians boycotted all three
sessions of Parliament, prompted by Syrian efforts to promote an
ally for president.
   The power vaccuum resulted in two interim governments, one
Christian, one Moslem, each claiming legitimacy.
   The Christian deputies said the new president's mandate should
``reject all forms of partition and rehabilitation.''
   Both groups of lawmakers stressed that the presidential vote
should take place before Oct. 18, when Parliament Speaker Hussein
Husseini's term runs out.
   Between them, the Moslem and Christian legislators total 45,
only six short of the quorum needed to hold an electoral session of
Parliament.
   Parliament has 99 seats. But there are only 76 members still
alive after 13 years of civil war.
   There have been no parliamentary elections since 1972 and the
House has repeatedly renewed its mandate since then.
   The statements by the two groups suggested that they may be
ready to seek a compromise candidate for president, provided that
Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, responds favorably.
   If a president and speaker are not elected soon, Parliament is
likely to disintegrate and the de facto partition of this
Mediterranean country would be likely be formalized.
   Parliament has not convened since Aug. 18.
   Syria, which supports the Moslems and their leftist allies, has
been pressing for the election of either ex-president Suleiman
Franjieh, a 78-year-old Christian warlord closely allied with
Damascus, or pro-Syrian deputy Mikhail Daher, 58, also a Christian.
   Right-wing Christians have vetoed both candidates, claiming they
are too heavily committed to the Syrians, who maintain 40,000
troops in north and east Lebanon and Beirut's Moslem sector.
   Under an unwritten covenant dating from 1943 when Lebanon gained
independence from France, Maronites have held the posts of
president, army commander and central bank governor.
   The prime minister hs traditionally been a Sunni and the
Parliament speaker a Shiite.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
