<HEAD>Off-Duty Policeman Killed, Two Hurt In Ulster Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen burst into a Belfast ice
cream parlor Tuesday and opened fire, killing an off-duty policeman
and injuring a man and a woman, police reported.
   The attack occurred an hour after two shots were fired at a
British army foot patrol in the predominantly Catholic Lenadoon
area of west Belfast. The soldiers returned one shot. Nobody was
reported injured in that incident.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the policeman's
death, but suspicion inevitably fell on the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   None of the victims was immediately identified. There was no
indication whether the gunmen targeted the man and woman or whether
they were shot accidentally.
   A press officer at Belfast police headquarters, who in
accordance with British practice spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the lives of the two injured people were not in danger.
   The ice cream parlor is off Lisburn Road, a main traffic artery
in south Belfast where sectarian divides are not as strictly
observed as in other parts of the city.
   The death of the policeman brings to at least 2,700 the death
toll since sectarian and political violence flared in Northern
Ireland 20 years ago.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of
Ireland under socialist rule.
