<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Refuseniks     10-11 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Refuseniks,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Jewish Couple Allowed To Emigrate After Politician's Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet Jewish couple long denied permission to
emigrate has been told they can leave, following their appeal for
help last week to a British Cabinet minister visiting the Soviet
Union, officials said Tuesday.
   Eduard Nadgorny, 57, and his wife, Nina, both scientists,
telephoned the British Embassy in Moscow on Monday to say Soviet
authorities promised the necessary emigration papers would be
prepared in the next few weeks, Britain's Department of Education
said.
   Education Secretary Kenneth Baker met the couple and seven other
refuseniks at a breakfast at the British Embassy Oct. 4 during his
seven-day tour of education facilities in the Soviet Union.
   ``She said that her meeting with Mr. Baker could have given the
Soviet authorities the final push,'' a Department of Education
spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said of Mrs. Nadgorny.
   Baker subsequently asked Yuri Marchuk, president of the Soviet
Academy of Sciences, to press emigration authorities for all nine
refuseniks to receive travel documents.
   ``I am delighted they (the Nadgornys) are to be allowed to
emigrate. It is marvelous news,'' Baker said Tuesday on the first
day of the ruling Conservative Party conference in Brighton, 50
miles south of London.
   ``I hope now that two have come that others might also get
permission to leave,'' he said.
   Refusenik is the name given to people who have applied for
permission to emigrate from the Soviet Union and been denied.
   Nadgorny lost his job as a physicist shortly after he and his
wife applied for emigration visas in 1981. The applications were
denied on grounds that they held information vital to the Soviet
Union.
   The couple staged hunger strikes to protest the refusal, but
were again denied permission to leave earlier this year to join
their 26-year-old son, Boris, a scientist at Princeton University
in New Jersey.
   In a telephone interview with the British domestic news agency
Press Association, Nadgorny thanked Baker for speaking to the
Soviet authorities.
   ``My wife and I kissed each other'' when the visa department
told them their official exit papers would be ready within two or
three weeks, Nadgorny was quoted as saying.
   ``We want to leave here as soon as possible,'' he was quoted as
saying. ``We hope it will be before the new year.''
   They expect to join their son before deciding where to settle,
Nadgorny said.
   Some of Nadgorny's writings have been smuggled out of the Soviet
Union and published in Britain. Mrs. Nadgorny is a leader of the
refusenik pressure group ``Women in Refusal'' and serves as a
correspondent for the London-based weekly Jewish Chronicle
newspaper.
</TEXT>
