<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--LibraryFire     10-11 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Library Fire,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Hits Central Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out Tuesday at Central Library,
which has been closed since two arson fires in 1986 damaged
thousands of books at the nation's second largest library, an
official said.
   The fire began about 5:10 p.m. and was extinguished about a half
hour later, said assistant Fire Chief Gerald Johnson.
   The 62-year-old Central Library in the downtown financial
district was hit by two arson fires that damaged its extensive
collection in 1986. The first fire destroyed 375,000 books and
caused $22 million in damage. The second destroyed 25,000 books for
an additional $2 million in damage.
   Some 900,000 books have been repaired.
   The library operations moved while the main library undergoes
expansion and renovation.
   Tuesday's fire apparently started somewhere in the basement
where construction materials were stored.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
