<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-11 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0549</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
failed to investigate most reports of suspicious foreign trading of
U.S. securities, despite a growing number of illegal trades
originating from abroad, a House panel says.
   A report released Monday by the Government Operations Committee
stated the SEC actively had investigated only 61 of 229 reports
from stock exchanges of suspicious foreign trades _ mostly those
appearing to involve insider trading _ in 1986 and 1987.
   The report was based on a year-long investigation by the panel's
subcommittee on commerce, consumer and monetary affairs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc., taking a giant step toward getting
out of the risky oil business, has announced agreements to sell
most of its oil and natural gas operations for an amount expected
to exceed $7.3 billion.
   Although negotiations continued for some minor portions, the
nation's 10th largest oil company said Monday it had entered into
definitive contracts with several buyers.
   Tenneco plans to sell Tenneco Oil Co. _ which makes up about 22
percent of total revenue _ and use the proceeds to help pay its
$8.5 billion debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getty Petroleum Corp. formally has submitted a
$553.5 million bid to acquire ailing Clark Oil & Refining Corp., a
leading discount gasoline marketer in the Midwest.
   Stephen Salzman, Getty's senior vice president, said Monday the
proposal had been filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in St. Louis.
   Getty said last week it would submit a bid that would top an
outstanding offer from Horsham Corp. of Canada.Salzman said his
company's bid is $50 million higher than Horsham's.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York investment company will purchase
Best Products Co. Inc. for $684.8 million in what both parties have
termed a friendly buyout.
   Adler & Shaykin will purchase the discount retailer through two
newly created corporations, the parties announced Monday.
   The investment firm will pay $27.50 a share cash for Best
Products' 24.9 million outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JAY, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the paperworkers union have
abruptly ended a bitter 16-month-old strike against International
Paper Co. mills by 2,300 workers in three states.
   The union said Monday the move would give strikers first crack
at any jobs vacated by non-union employees who now run the mills in
Jay; De Pere, Wis.; and Lock Haven, Pa.
   ``We have lost this battle but the war for justice in the work
place is not over,'' said Felix Jacques, executive vice president
of United Paperworkers International Union Local 14 in Jay.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin, whose
efforts to buy Resorts International Inc. had been going smoothly,
is now giving himself an option to back off the deal, attorneys and
casino officials say.
   Griffin said Monday he allowed a deadline to complete the
acquisition to expire last Friday, and that any party to the
proposed deal was now free to terminate its obligations.
   Griffin had offered to pay $36 a share for Resorts, which owns a
casino and huge land holdings in Atlantic City, as well as land and
a casino in the Bahamas.
</TEXT>
