<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-11 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0556</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia has reaffirmed that it
will adhere to an OPEC oil production quota if other members of the
cartel do, a move aimed at reining in overproduction that is
driving prices down.
   The affirmation was made Monday at the weekly cabinet session
chaired by King Fahd and reported by Information Minister Ali
al-Shaer.
   Oil industry sources have reported Saudi Arabia recently has
been producing about 6 million barrels of oil a day, far above its
quota of 4.343 million barrels set by the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand for new farm equipment will
increase in 1989, say leaders from an industry group who cite
expectations of substantially increased planting, higher crop
prices and government drought relief payments to farmers.
   ``The need for new equipment is there. If the weather
cooperates, 1989 could be a very good year,'' Bernard L. Nielsen,
president of Gehl Co., said Monday.
   John Tye, newly elected chairman of the Farm and Industrial
Equipment Institute, said industry inventories are at the lowest
levels in years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have frozen two foreign bank accounts
belonging to a fugitive financial planner who was captured in
Japan, spurring hopes that clients may be able to recover some of
the $20 million reported missing.
   Court-appointed receiver James Feltman said Monday he filed
lawsuits freezing Henry Gherman's bank accounts in two countries.
   The Miami accountant said investigators were preparing to freeze
a third foreign account.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. has named Ira C. Herbert president
of its flagship division, Coca-Cola USA, in an attempt to increase
its advertising firepower in the cola wars.
   Herbert, executive vice president of the parent company, will
replace Edwin R. Mellett as president of both Coca-Cola USA and the
North America Business Sector, the company announced Monday.
   Mellett, a senior vice president of Coca-Cola Co., will take
over the new job of president of international post-mix sales,
where he will be in charge of fountain sales outside the United
States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market crash has realigned the
fortunes of the nation's wealthiest, but they are still really rich.
   Forbes magazine says its annual survey found the 400 wealthiest
Americans had total worth of about $220 billion at midyear, enough
to wipe out the government's budget deficit or nearly enough to
support the entire U.S. military, which spent $287 billion in 1987.
   The average fortune on the list comes to $551 million, up $1
million from last year.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered buying of blue chips Monday lifted the Dow Jones
average to a new high since the October 1987 crash. The closely
watched market barometer climbed 8.71 points to 2,158.96,
surpassing the previous post-crash closing peak of 2,158.61 on July
5.
   The dollar tumbled in light trading. Gold prices rose, boosted
by a jump in oil prices.
   The government bond market was for the Columbus Day holiday, but
prices of corporate bonds rose.
   Oil futures rallied; copper futures continued to climb; grains
and soybeans were mixed; and livestock and meat futures mostly were
lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
