<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Griffin-Resorts     10-11 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Griffin-Resorts,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin Says He Won't Offer Assurances About Closing Deal On
Resorts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Donald Trump and
Resorts International Inc., as well as state casino regulators, say
they are puzzled by an apparent shift in entertainer Merv Griffin's
plans to purchase the hotel-casino business for $364 million.
   A lawyer for Griffin said Monday he could offer no assurances
that the deal, which only recently seemed on the verge of
completion, would go forward.
   Griffin was to appear today before the state Casino Control
Commission to discuss the matter.
   ``There are a lot of questions,'' said Joel Sterns, an attorney
for Resorts. ``...I frankly don't know what this means.''
   Griffin issued a prepared statement Monday saying he allowed a
deadline to complete the acquisition to expire on Friday, and that
any party to the proposed deal was free to terminate its
obligations.
   The former talk-show host had offered to pay $36 a share for the
Class A stock of Resorts, which owns a casino and real estate in
Atlantic City, plus land and a casino in the Bahamas.
   Resorts Class A stock closed down $4.87{ a share at $29.12{
Monday on the American Stock Exchange, and traded as low as $26 a
share during the session.
   Griffin, who recently has turned his attention to real estate,
would take Resorts private by also buying out real estate magnate
Trump's controlling Class B stock for $135 a share, and pay Trump
$63 million to break his management contract with Resorts. Griffin
also planned to
   Griffin's latest move could be an indication that he believes he
can buy Resorts at a lower price by threatening to withdraw from
the deal.
   A spokesman for Griffin Co., Thomas Gallagher, said: ``We have
not made any decision that we're going to terminate. On the other
hand, we're not giving any assurance that the deal is going to go
forward.''
   A lawyer for Trump was more optimistic.
   ``The deal is going to go forward,'' said Jack Nusbaum from his
New York office. He said Griffin ``has given us no indication he's
going to back out of the deal.''
   Griffin said in the news release that if an acquisition was
completed it would be done through a merger, not a tender offer. A
merger offer was approved Aug. 30 by the required number of
shareholders, said Griffin.
   Griffin and Trump had engaged in bitter negotiations for control
of Resorts, but appeared to have come to terms about their
differences and worked out the deal now in question.
   In addition to the money Griffin would pay for Resorts stock, he
would invest $50 million in Resorts to help it generate enough cash
flow to cover interest payments on Resorts' debt.
   In turn, Trump would pay Resorts $273 million for its
unfinished, 1,250-room Taj Mahal Casino.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
