<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar traded lower in Europe today, pulled
down by an earlier drop against the Japanese yen in Asia, foreign
currency traders said.
   Gold prices firmed.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 131.15 yen, down 2.35 yen, largely due to
technical selling, traders said. The dollar was trading at the same
level later in London.
   In Rome, traders said the dollar was also under pressure in
anticipation of Thursday's U.S. trade report for August which is
expected to show a worsening trade deficit.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.8507 West German marks, down from 1.8550;
1.5700 Swiss francs, down from 1.5755; 6.3060 French francs, down
from 6.3213; 2.0859 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0907; 1.379.00
Italian lire, down from 1,383.295; and 1.2070 Canadian dollars,
unchanged.
   The British pound continued to strengthen. One pound cost
$1.7195 this morning, compared with $1.7130 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $409.85 an ounce, up
from $407.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $408.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $407.10, up from $407 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.79 to close at a bid $412.13.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.35 an ounce,
slightly lower than Monday's $6.37.
</TEXT>
