<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-11 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today
while prices rose on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar fell sharply and closed at 131.15 yen, down 2.35 yen
from Friday's close of 133.50 yen. After opening at 132.20 yen, the
currency gradually fell while ranging between 130.95 yen and 132.23
yen.
   It was the first time the dollar closed at the 131-yen level
since July 25, when it closed at 131.80 yen.
   A dealer with Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the the pound sterling rose sharply against the
dollar overnight in London and the Tokyo market followed suit.
   The dollar's decline in London was widely linked to a statement
Monday by Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, Nigel Lawson, who
said the government would keep interest rates high ``as long as it
is necessary to fight inflation.''
   The Mitsubishi dealer said dollar-selling dominated today's
trading in Tokyo, led by speculative investors.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 211.33 points, or 0.78
percent, to finish trading at 27,469.60. The market's main index
quickly gained 278.98 points after the trading began and kept
rising, although at a slower pace.
   ``Trading started off pretty good following the (Dow Jones')
higher close in New York overnight,'' said a broker with Daiwa
Securities in Tokyo, also speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Although share prices were higher across the board in the
early trading, the index was unable to keep rising due to lack of
the market's energy,'' he said.
   ``But a good thing was that participants traded a variety of
issues,'' although trading was light with the volume on the first
section estimated at 650 million shares, the broker said.
   Among issues that attracted participants were steels, cars and
chemicals.
</TEXT>
