<HEAD>London Stocks Lower in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Tuesday, with trading light
ahead of the release later this week of key economic reports and
Britain's Conservative Party convention.
   Stocks of companies whose earnings are dollar-dominated were
among the major losers, dropping back in line with the U.S.
currency's weakness on foreign exchange markets.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down 5.1
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,839 at midday.
   Volume was light, as 244.8 million shares changed hands,
compared with 236.9 million shares at the same time Monday.
   Key among the economic statistics due out this week will be
Thursday's release of U.S. trade figures for August. British retail
price figures will be announced Friday.
   In addition, the market will be keenly watching the Conservative
Party convention for indications about the near-term course of
British interest rates. Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson
will address his fellow Tories at the conference in Brighton on
Thursday.
