<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AmocoDonuts     10-11 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amoco Donuts,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Food and Fuel Moving Under One Roof</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Fill 'er up'' may take on a whole new meaning
if a partnership between Amoco Corp. and Dunkin Donuts Inc. catches
on around the country.
   The two companies have merged a self-service gas station in
Downers Grove, Ill., a Chicago suburb, with a doughnut shop under
the same roof and say the results have been promising.
   ``We don't have an awful lot of experience,'' said Richard Hart,
vice president and treasurer of the Randolph, Mass.-based Dunkin'
Donuts. ``But the results are satisfactory enough that we're
looking at other locations with Amoco.''
   The partnership is a departure from having convenience stores
adjacent to gas pumps and having service stations and fast food
restaurants share sites on highways or near toll booths.
   At the moment, Chicago-based Amoco stands alone in putting gas
stations and fast-food stores under one roof.
   ``This may be a trend we're looking at,'' said Joseph Koach,
executive director of the Service Station Dealers of America.
   For Amoco, the deal with Dunkin' Donuts is one of a number of
agreements with various fast food firms, including Burger King
Corp. and International Dairy Queen, Inc.
   ``The thinking is that their (Amoco) customers and our customers
are looking for the same thing: convenience, good products and good
prices,'' said Colt Hothorn, national director of development for
Burger King.
   ``There are compatible needs on the part of the customer. It's
not difficult to see a person filling up and buying a doughnut, or
a hamburger or an ice cream cone,'' said Robert Rauscher, Amoco's
vice president for marketing.
   Amoco and Dunkin' Donuts started the Downers Grove project in
1986 and since then, the oil company has started similar joint
ventures with Burger King in Pillsbury, Colo. and Dairy Queen in
Westminster, Colo.
   Two more partnerships, with Joyce's Subs and Pizza, a
Denver-based chain, are scheduled to start this fall in Colorado.
   In all cases, the food stores will sell only take-out items and
the gas stations are all self-service.
   The concept has attracted customers' notice.
   ``I come in all the time,'' said Keri Moon, a college student
who uses the Downers Grove station. ``It's a quick way to get
breakfast.'' If she could not buy doughnuts there, she said, ``I'd
probably buy gas someplace else.''
   ``There are a lot of stations down the street selling gas for
the same price, so it's not the price,'' said Alan Buresz, of
Lemont, another Chicago suburb, who is a frequent customer. ``I
come in for the convenience.''
   Other firms, such as Texaco Inc. and Phillips Petroleum Co. have
built gas stations in tandem with McDonald's restaurants along
highways and each is looking to add more.
   But unlike Amoco's project, McDonald's likes to place sit-down
restaurants next to gas stations and have the two businesses
operate separately.
   ``McDonald's is in the business of selling hamburgers. We want
to leave selling gasoline to the oil companies,'' said Melissa
Oakley, a spokeswoman for the fast food giant.
   But Rauscher said other oil companies will follow Amoco's lead.
``It's too soon to say that this is the next thing,'' he said.
``But if successful, these things tend to be duplicated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
