<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back today, a day after one
key index reached its highest level since last October's crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 8.71 points
to a post-crash high on Monday, was down 7.64 at 2,151.32 after 90
minutes of trading.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 7 to 4 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 390 up, 731 down
and 535 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 45.43 million shares at 11 a.m.
on Wall Street, compared with 43.87 million shares at the same
point Monday.
   Investors have taken some reassurance from recent government
reports that the economy is growing at a more moderate pace than
earlier this year.
   Slower growth has been taken to indicate that inflation is not
an immediate problem and that the Federal Reserve will find no
compelling need to tighten credit conditions.
   Tighter credit means higher interest rates, and makes
fixed-income securities such as Treasury notes and bonds more
competitive with stocks.
   The bond market was lower today after taking Monday off for the
observance of Columbus Day. Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds were
up to 8.86 percent.
   But investors are worried that the earnings reports due to be
released over the next three weeks may show smaller gains than
earlier this year.
   And some analysts contend that some traders remain wary of
stocks as the market pushes toward levels from which it crashed
only a year ago next week.
   Tenneco was among the most actively traded stocks on the NYSE,
rising 1 to 50}. The company said Monday it had agreed to sell oil
and gas assets for more than $7.3 billion in a series of
transactions.
   Among other active issues, AMD was up ] at 9, Best Products was
off [ at 26}, Baxter was up ] at 18{ and Philips Petroleum was up [
at 200\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.54 at 156.42. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index was down .34 at 303.75.
