<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices were narrowly mixed while
grain futures were mostly lower in cautious early trading today on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said traders were taking few chances ahead of the
Agriculture Department's revised crop production report, due
Wednesday afternoon.
   The market has developed ``a little bit of a bearish bias'' on
expectations that the USDA will increase its corn and soybean
production estimates due to better-than-expected yields in the
ongoing harvest, said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   But analysts' published pre-report guesses vary widely _ from
1.44 billion to 1.54 billion bushels of soybeans, and from 4.25
billion to 4.6 billion bushels of corn.
   Those numbers compare with the USDA's September estimates of
1.47 billion bushels of soybeans and 4.46 billion bushels of corn.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.26 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $2.92{ a bushel; oats
for December delivery, the only active contract in early trading,
were \ cent lower at $2.46} a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents lower
to 5 cents higher with November at $7.90{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .40 cent lower with October at
72.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .37 cent lower
with October at 81.55 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .32 cent
lower with October at 40.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.28 cent lower to .40 cent higher with February at 47.37 cents a
pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower on Monday while pork bellies
settled higher.
