<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated broadly today, as
profit-taking depressed prices a day after one key market index
reached its highest level since last October's crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 8.71 points
to a post-crash high on Monday, was down 12.27 at 2,146.69 at
noontime.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 2 to 1 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 410 up, 821 down
and 535 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 68.18 million shares at noon on
Wall Street, compared with 61.16 million shares at the same point
Monday.
   Investors have taken some reassurance from recent government
reports that the economy is growing at a more moderate pace than
earlier this year.
   They feel that slower growth means inflation is not an immediate
problem and that the Federal Reserve will feel no compulsion to
tighten credit.
   Tighter credit means higher interest rates, and makes
fixed-income securities such as Treasury notes and bonds more
competitive with stocks.
   The bond market was lower today after taking Monday off for the
observance of Columbus Day. Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds were
up to 8.86 percent.
   Analysts said today's decline reflected some profit-taking after
four consecutive advances by the Dow Jones industrial average,
including a 42.50-point rise last Friday.
   ``When the rally didn't continue through today, some traders
thought they would take a few profits,'' said Eldon A. Grimm,
senior vice president at Birr, Wilson Securities.
   He said an overnight decline in the dollar in foreign exchange
trading may also have discouraged stock investors, particularly
foreigners.
   Some traders also remain wary of stocks as the market pushes
toward levels from which it crashed only a year ago next week.
   ``It's sort of a mental block,'' Grimm said.
   Kroger tumbled 2{ to 55[ after the investment form Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. withdrew its buyout proposal of $64 a share.
Kroger has proposed a restructuring and has a buyout proposal from
the Haft family.
   Tenneco was up } at 50{. The company said Monday it had agreed
to sell oil and gas assets for more than $7.3 billion in a series
of transactions.
   Digital Equipment rose 1 to 89[ after effectively increasing
prices on most of its products.
   Elsewhere in the computer group, International Business Machines
was up 1 at 117[, Hewlett Packard was up \ at 50\ and Prime
Computer was up [ at 13~.
   Among other active issues, AMD was up ] at 9, Best Products was
off [ at 26}, Philips Petroleum was up \ at 20] and Pillsbury was
off { at 56~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.69 at 156.27. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index was down 0.67 at 303.42.
