<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Caterpillar-UAW     10-11 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caterpillar-UAW,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Workers Issue Notice of Contract Expiration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers told negotiators
for Caterpillar Inc. today the company has five more days to reach
agreement on a new contract or face the possibility of a strike.
   Caterpillar spokesman Mark Polzin said the contract would expire
at 9:30 a.m. Sunday.
   No new talks between the company and Caterpillar have been
scheduled, Polzin said.
   Talks between the UAW and Caterpillar recessed Sept. 30, the day
the current contract was to have expired, with both sides agreeing
to an indefinite extension that could be lifted any time, as long
as notice of five days was given.
   When the two sides met briefly this morning, the union gave such
notice to the company.
   Polzin declined to discuss the situation further. Union
officials were not immediately available for comment today, but
chief UAW negotiator Bill Casstevens said the union wanted to get
down to serious talks immediately.
   Negotiators could keep talking right through the deadline in an
effort to reach an agreement, they could extend the deadline or the
union could call a strike.
   The union's membership has voted to authorize a strike.
   Union officials had said Monday they believed a new deadline
would prompt the two sides to negotiate at a quick pace, picking up
where they left off before the extension. Without such a deadline,
they said, there would be less incentive for either side to make
rapid progress.
   The union sought the extension so it could concentrate on
reaching a new agreement with Deere & Co. UAW members ratified an
agreement with Deere over the weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
