<DOCNO> AP881011-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Interco     10-11 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Interco,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Target Interco Reports Lower Quarterly Net</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc., fighting a $2.5 billion hostile
tender offer, on Tuesday said its profits slipped 9 percent in the
second fiscal quarter.
   The company said net income totaled $34.9 million, or 93 cents a
share in the quarter ended Aug. 31, compared with $38.4 million, or
90 cents a share in the year-ago period.
   Sales during the quarter totaled $630 million, up 3 percent from
$610 million in the comparable period in 1987.
   Results were restated to reflect Interco's announcement in
August to put its apparel manufacturing group up for sale.
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp., headed by the Rales brothers of
Washington, D.C., has launched a $70-a-share tender offer for
Interco that is being contested in the courts.
   For the first half of the fiscal year, Interco said earnings
totaled $65.6 million, or $1.73 per share, up 1 percent from $64.9
million, or $1.52 per share a year earlier.
   The number of shares outstanding totaled 37.83 million at the
end of the first fiscal half, down from 42.80 million a year ago.
   Sales were up 3 percent at $1.27 billion, from $1.23 billion in
the first half of the pervious fiscal year.
   Interco Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Harvey Saligman
noted in a statement that ``despite the distraction during recent
months caused by the unsolicited hostile tender offer, sales and
earnings per share were ahead of last year's strong performance.''
   In response to Cardinal's tender offer, Interco announced a
major restructuring and recapitalization program last month that is
designed to increase shareholder value to at least $76 a share.
   Interco, a manufacturer of furniture and apparel, is
headquartered in St. Louis.
</TEXT>
