<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 2ndLd-Writethru   10-11 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Surge on Speculation About OPEC Production Restraint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, But prices ... to include midday price.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, Crude oil ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures are bounding up from two-year lows
reached last week, but analysts say it is unclear whether the
recent downward trend in prices has been reversed or merely
interrupted.
   Trading was active Monday, analysts said, as Saudi Arabia, the
world's largest oil exporter, reaffirmed it would stick to its
production quota if other members of OPEC did.
   The statement triggered speculation that other members of the
13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would
reduce production in order to help boost prices.
   But Nauman Barakat, vice president for energy investment at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said he remained skeptical
because other OPEC members have ``shown no indication they are
willing to cut back output.''
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate climbed 66 cents to settle at $13.60 a
barrel. At one point during the day's trading, the contract traded
as high as $13.80 a barrel.
   After opening lower today, prices retraced lost ground. By
midday, the November crude contract was up 6 cents at $13.66 a
barrel.
   Crude oil prices had tumbled to around $12.30 a barrel last week
as Saudi Arabia threatened to produce more than its quota if the
other OPEC members continued pumping more than their quotas.
   Among refined oil products traded on the exchange, the November
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 1.28 cent to settle
at 41.41 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 1.50 cents to
38.96 cents a gallon.
   Steven Chronowitz, director of futures research at Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. Inc., said Monday's rise could mean prices
bottomed out last week.
   But he said, ``if over the next few weeks we don't see any real
action to back up the words, then the market may sag again.''
   Saudi Arabia delivered its affirmation about its willingness to
abide by its quota if others did at the weekly Cabinet session
presided over by King Fahd and reported by Information Minister Ali
al-Shaer.
   Prudential-Bache's Barakat said the Saudis have made similar
statements before, but that ``this statement is being taken more
seriously than before.''
   He said one explanation is that a published report from the
Mideast said Saudi Arabia produced an average of 4.3 million
barrels a day in the first week of October, matching its quota. He
said previously, the Saudis reportedly had been producing 5.7
million barrels a day.
   Barakat said the market was asking ``whether they have cut back
output intentionally as an overture to others to cut back output or
is it result of scheduling problems. That is the $64,000 question.''
   He said trading was heavy and was driven by professionals buying
contracts to cover borrowed contracts they sold earlier on the
expectation that prices would fall further.
   ``The rally was a combination of technicals and fundamentals.
People are still not giving too much credence to the Saudi
statement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Phone     10-11 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Phone,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Telecom Reports Profit As US Sprint Improves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp reduction in the losses of US Sprint
Communications Co. contributed to higher third-quarter profits at
United Telecommunications Inc., which is half-owner of the
long-distance company along with GTE Corp., United Telecom said
Tuesday.
   United Telecommunications said US Sprint's pre-tax loss fell to
$19 million in the third quarter, from $165 million in the third
quarter of 1987 and $112 million in the second quarter of 1988.
   US Sprint's revenue rose 34 percent to $916 million in the third
quarter from $685 million a year earlier. Revenue for the first
nine months rose to $2.48 billion from $1.85 billion a year earlier.
   After taxes, United Telecom's share of the loss of US Sprint was
reduced to $44,000 in the third quarter and $77.9 million in the
first nine months, compared with $44.7 million and $296.5 million
in the respective periods a year earlier.
   United Telecom, which is based in Kansas City, Mo., said it
earned $54 million, or 52 cents a share, in the third quarter, up
from $25.8 million, or 25 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
for units other than US Sprint rose to $805.8 million from $750.6
million.
   For the first nine months, United Telecom said it registered a
profit of $127.1 million, or $1.18 a share, compared with a loss of
$80.7 million a year earlier. Revenue excluding US Sprint rose to
$2.33 billion from $2.18 billion.
   GTE said it would release its quarterly results at a later date.
GTE is scheduled to sell 30.1 percent of US Sprint for $600 million
at the beginning of 1989, leaving itself with 19.9 percent of the
long-distance carrier.
</TEXT>
