<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Next-Ratners     10-11 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Next-Ratners,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Next To Sell Two Retail Jewelry Divisions to Ratners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next PLC, a British fashion retailer, said Tuesday
it has agreed to sell 433 Salisburys and Zales and other jewelry
stores in Britain to Ratners Group PLC for the equivalent of $232
million.
   The sale follows last year's bidding war between Next and
Ratners over Combined English Stores Group PLC, a diversified
retail chain which included the Salisburys and Zales jewelry store
chains.
   Next ultimately won the takeover battle, paying about 338
million pounds, or $581 million, in new Next shares.
   At the time of the takeover, Next discussed the sale to Ratners
of some of the Combined English Store jewelry stores, but these
talks broke down.
   Also included in the sale announced Tuesday are 73 jewelry
stores which previously formed part of the Collingwoods and J. Weir
chains, also acquired by Next as part of the Combined English
Stores takeover.
   ``Next will retain those CES stores which most naturally fit
into the Next retail format and will sell to Ratners those stores
currently selling jewelry and accessories which don't, thereby
raising cash for the further development of the group's core
businesses,'' Next said in a statement.
   The acquisition of Zales marks a significant move by Ratners
into the medium-level jewelry market, while Salisburys broadens its
business to include fashion accessories.
   The two subsidiaries had combined operating profit of 9.5
million pounds on sales of 83.5 million pounds in the year ended
Jan. 31.
   Ratners, which specializes in low-cost jewelry, currently has
about 1,140 stores in Britain and the United States, according to
analysts.
</TEXT>
