<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     10-11 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower on Yen and Pound Strength, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in European trading Tuesday,
pressured by investor interest in the Japanese yen and the British
pound and cautious market sentiment ahead of Thursday's release of
U.S. trade figures.
   Gold prices were slightly lower.
   Dealers said the dollar's weakness against the yen was triggered
in Tokyo trading by a large order to sell dollars for yen, which
prompted other stop loss orders.
   Two market sources in London said Salomon Brothers in Tokyo sold
one billion dollars for yen during the Tokyo day on behalf of a
client. An official at Salomon Brothers in London refused to
comment, saying the investment bank never discusses its trading
activities.
   Dealers said the American currency's weak tone also has
encouraged investors to sell dollars and buy other high-yielding
currencies such as the pound.
   The momentum of the pound's rise Monday continued on Tuesday and
the Bank of England reportedly intervened to keep the market from
getting carried away.
   ``There was no suggestion that the bank was putting a top on the
pound or forcing it lower,'' said one London dealer. ``It was just
a normal smoothing operation.''
   The Bank of England refused to comment on the reports of
intervention.
   Dealers in Frankfurt said the market was waiting for Thursday's
U.S. trade report.
   Economists were forecasting an August deficit of $11.3 billion,
wider than July's deficit of $9.53 billion.
   ``The trade figures will be the trigger of any movement'' on the
foreign exchange market, said one Frankfurt trader.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 2.35 yen to a closing 131.15 yen from
Friday's 133.50 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at a lower
rate of 130.80 yen. The Tokyo market was closed on Monday for a
holiday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7175 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7130 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8512 West German marks, down from 1.8550; 1.5690
Swiss francs, down from 1.5755; 6.3070 French francs, down from
6.3213; 2.0850 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0907; 1,379.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,383.295; and 1.2075 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2070.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $406.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $407.25.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $406 compared with
$407 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.79 to close at a bid $412.13.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.31 a troy ounce, compared
with Monday's $6.37.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
