<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Higher On Export News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures prices closed mostly higher Tuesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to signs of stronger
foreign demand for U.S. grains and soybeans, analysts said.
   Reports that China was bidding for 400,000 metric tons of
subsidized U.S. wheat sparked speculative and commercial buying of
wheat futures, which had been slipping after making new
life-of-contract high prices last week.
   Egypt and Yugoslavia were said to be in the market for U.S.
corn, and exporters said Taiwan had purchased 54,000 metric tons of
soybeans.
   But gains were limited by expectations that the Agriculture
Department will increase its corn and soybean harvest estimates in
a crop production report scheduled for release Wednesday afternoon,
analysts said.
   ``That type of attitude may also prevail a bit tomorrow'' in
trading ahead of the report, said Ted Mao, a grain specialist in
New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``But, barring any major surprises, I would not view this crop
report as the major one,'' he said. ``We already know the general
size of the crop. This report is just fine tuning.''
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 6{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.34 a bushel; corn was 2\
cents lower to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.95\ cents a
bushel; oats were 5 cents to 7} cents higher with December at
$2.54} cents a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 5\ cents higher with
November at $7.93 a bushel.
</TEXT>
