<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-ExchangeRules     10-11 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Exchange Rules,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Relaxes Foreign Firms' Listing Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   London's Stock Exchange on Tuesday announced a
relaxation of its listing requirements for foreign firms, in an
effort to attract more overseas companies to the market.
   Overseas firms that satisfy certain basic requirements will be
permitted to disclose financial information for the three most
recent years, rather than for the five years required previously.
   The basic requirements include a five-year trading record and
compliance with internationally accepted accounting rules. The
company must also have been listed for at least two years on an
overseas exchange, and the value of its shares in public hands must
exceed 150 million pounds, or the equivalent of $258 million.
   The Stock Exchange said the relaxation brings its rules in line
with European Community listing requirements.
</TEXT>
