<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Industry Challenge to Smokestack Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business challenges to federal environmental
rules governing the use of high smokestacks to disperse air
pollution were rejected Tuesday by the Supreme Court.
   In another case, the justices refused to revive a challenge to
the way Laurence A. Tisch became president of CBS Inc., letting
stand rulings that his assumption of power two years ago did not
amount to a transfer of control requiring prior approval by the
Federal Communications Commission.
   The court also refused to kill a lawsuit charging Boeing Co.
with illegal age bias because it bars pilots from active flight
status when they reach 60.
   In the environmental case, the justices, without comment, left
intact a lower court ruling that strengthened clean air regulations
by limiting the use of smokestacks as a substitute for other
pollution controls.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled in January that the
Environmental Protection Agency validly adopted the regulations
involving use of high smokestacks in 1985.
   Building taller stacks, the leading technique of dispersal,
generally is cheaper than cutting emissions. But environmentalists
say that while dispersing the pollution may provide cleaner air in
the vicinity of plants and factories, it adds to the overall
pollution in the atmosphere.
   The rules upheld by the appealse futures trading on the New York Coffee,
Sugar and Cocoa Exchange Tuesday:
