<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewToyotas     10-11 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Toyotas,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota Looking for 1.5 Million in Annual Sales for Mid '90s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Sales, U.S.A., will increase U.S.
sales to about 1.5 million cars and trucks annually by the
mid-1990s _ a twofold sales boost fueled by a new truck plant, a
company executive said Tuesday.
   At the introduction of the Japanese automaker's 1989 models, Bob
McCurry, executive vice president for sales and operations for the
U.S. arm of the company, said he didn't know where that plant would
be located.
   ``We've got to get a truck plant'' in the United States, he said
flatly, adding it would take about 2{ years from site selection to
production at a new truck plant.
   The light truck market in the United States has been booming,
and industry analysts aren't sure where it will level off. Included
in the category are pickup trucks, sport utility vehicles and the
popular minivans.
   Toyota now imports a wide variety of pickup trucks with assorted
cab and bed sizes. The company also builds a van in Japan and
brings it to the United States, but sales of the vehicle have been
slipping against stiff competition from domestic and overseas
minivan makers.
   McCurry said the Toyota van is designed for Japanese consumers,
and that a new small van would be built in Japan specifically for
the U.S. market.
   For the first nine months of this year, Toyota has sold 684,961
cars and trucks in the United States, up 1.4 percent over the same
period last year. The reason that percentage isn't higher, McCurry
said, was a limited availability of the vehicles from Japan.
   But he added, that will change.
   ``By 1995, if we implement all our plans, nearly half of our
products will be built right here in North America and many of them
will have more American content than some Big Three products,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
