<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Slip From Post-Crash Highs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A midafternoon recovery fell short and the stock
market finished lower Tuesday, a day after one key index reached
its highest level since last October's crash.
   Analysts blamed profit-taking, lingering worries about the
economy and interest rates and general investor wariness for the
pullback.
   Bill Raftery, a market analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co., said investors were acting like reluctant grooms being dragged
to the altar.
   ``He's going in kicking and screaming. There doesn't seem to be
any overwhelming desire to own stocks,'' he said.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 8.71 points
to a post-crash high on Monday, fell back 2.49 to close at 2,156.47.
   But that was an improvement from midday when the market's
best-known index was down more than 16 points as the lunch hour
ended.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 3-to-2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
593 issues up, 823 down and 535 unchanged. The NYSE composite index
slipped 0.19 to 156.77.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 140.90 million shares,
up from 124.66 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
167.35 million shares.
   Analysts said investors continue to exhibit little confidence
about the longterm direction for the economy and interest rates.
   While some recent government reports have indicated the economy
is growing at a more moderate pace, investors seem reluctant to buy
stocks in advance of knowing what the next set of economic
statistics may show.
   ``The market has been living in fits and starts,'' said Alfred
E. Goldman, director of technical market analysis for A.G. Edwards
& Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ``Trends last a day-and-a-half and are
usually tied to today's news.''
   He said investors focus on the latest economic report, and noted
they have plenty to look to this week. The government plans to
report this week on the August trade balance and on September
wholesale prices.
   Jack Baker, head of block trading for Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., said the market's pullback also reflected a decline of the
dollar in foreign exchange trading, which serves to discourage
foreign investment in U.S. stocks.
   He said profit-taking also occurred as the market had sent the
Dow Jones industrial average up nearly 57 points over the past four
sessions.
   The bond market provided little encouragement for stocks.
   Prices were lower and interest rates edged higher with yields on
30-year Treasury bonds rising to 8.85 percent from 8.79 percent
last Friday.
   Kroger tumbled 2| to 55 after the investment form Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. withdrew its buyout proposal of $64 a share.
Kroger had rejected its overtures and had proposed a restructuring.
   Tenneco fell | to 49[. The company said Monday it had agreed to
sell oil and gas assets for more than $7.3 billion in a series of
transactions.
   Digital Equipment rose 1 to 89[ after effectively increasing
prices on most of its products. Elsewhere in the high-technology
group, International Business Machines climbed 2| to 118}, National
Semiconductor was up ~ at 10[, Hewlett Packard rose { to 50{ and
Honeywell rose { to 64.
   Among other active issues, Phillips Petroleum rose { to 20|,
Baxter rose } to 18~, Pillsbury fell | to 56} and Best Products
slipped [ to 26}.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $2.64 billion, or 0.10
percent, in value.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index slipped 0.10 to 319.62, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was off 0.31 at 277.93.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.32
to 303.77. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market fell 0.21 to 385.28.
</TEXT>
