<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Illinois,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bank Execs Surrender to Begin Serving Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former bank executives surrendered to federal
authorities Tuesday to begin serving prison terms imposed after
they pleaded guilty to crimes that helped bring Continental
Illinois Bank to the brink of bankruptcy.
   John R. Lytle, 53, a former Continental Illinois vice president,
appeared before noon at the Federal Prison Camp in Oxford, Wis.,
said camp administrator Charles Stewart. He will serve a 3{-year
term after being sentenced Aug. 30 by U.S. District Judge Milton
Shadur.
   William G. Patterson, the head of energy lending at the
now-defunct Penn Square bank of Oklahoma City, surrendered to
authorities at the Federal Prison Camp at Big Springs, Texas. He
was sentenced to serve 2 years.
   The maximum sentence Shadur could have imposed on either
defendant under terms of the plea bargain was five years.
   Lytle and Patterson admitted taking part in a scheme in which
Lytle took kickbacks in exchange for arranging to have Continental
Illinois buy millions of dollars in risky energy loans from Penn
Square Bank of Oklahoma City.
   Lytle pleaded guilty to one charge of misapplication of bank
funds; Patterson to a single count of aiding and abetting Lytle.
   Continental Illinois Bank, saddled with a host of troublesome
energy loans and loans to third world countries, was saved from
collapse in 1984 by a $4.5 billion federal bailout package.
</TEXT>
