<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Bankers-Greenspan     10-11 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bankers-Greenspan,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenspan Praises New Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Tuesday that broad new guidelines for increasing banks' capital are
the key to maintaining stability in the financial world.
   ``Capital acts as a buffer against unexpected shocks to a firm,
and thereby helps to insulate both individual firms and the system
from risk,'' Greenspan said at the 114th annual convention of the
American Bankers Association.
   Greenspan also assured bankers that the repeal of the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, which separates commercial and
investment banking, remains one of the Fed's highest priorities.
   Bankers have been trying to gain a foothold in the securities
industry for the past several years, arguing that it is necessary
to compete more efficiently with banks abroad.
   Banking reform legislation has been tossed around in Congress,
although it appears unlikely any major changes will come this year.
   To help maintain a more level playing field between banks here
and abroad, the United States and 11 other industrialized nations
agreed in July to standardize capital requirements for banks by
1992.
   Capital represents a financial cushion of profits and
stockholder money reserved for times of stress. The purpose of the
international accord was to link capital requirements to the
riskiness of bank assets.
   Under the new guidelines, all of the nation's 14,000 commercial
banks will be required to have capital reserves equivalent to 8
percent of assets, weighted by risk, in the next four years. The
total capital requirement now is 6 percent.
   Greenspan praised the new guidelines, which the Fed voted to
enact in August, as a way of ``providing shock absorbers'' for the
financial system by discouraging excessive risk-taking.
   ``There is no better way to ensure that owners exert discipline
on the behavior of their firm than to require that the owners have
a large stake in that enterprise,'' Greenspan said. ``The safety
and soundness of the financial system requires that banks have
adequate capital.''
   The new guidelines will force several money center banks to
raise as much as $15 billion. Experts predict that many banks will
have to issue new stock and sell some assets to raise their capital
base.
   ``I recognize that some of these banks, not feeling market
pressure to raise capital ratios, may consider increased capital
requirements unnecessarily burdensome,'' Greenspan said. ``However,
given the existence of the federal safety net, market signals
regarding the level of capital may not be appropriate from a
broader perspective.''
</TEXT>
