<2ND_LINE>AM-Port Director,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Chooses Rotterdam Executive To Head Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Port of Seattle announced Tuesday it has
named the No. 2 executive for the port of Rotterdam in the
Netherlands as its new executive director.
   Zeger van Asch van Wijck, adjunct director for the port of
Rotterdam, will replace Jim Dwyer, who has resigned.
   Van Wijck, 41, was approved unanimously by the Seattle port
commission, the panel's President Henry Aronson said. He will
assume his new duties in January. John Belford will continue as
interim director until then.
   The director, who answers to the Port of Seattle Commission,
oversees nearly $1 billion in assets, including Seattle's giant
marine terminals and Seattle-Tacoma International Airport. The port
employs 1,100.
   Aronson said van Wijck, who has held his Rotterdam post for 3{
years, was chosen because of his international experience with one
of the world's top ports.
   The port of Rotterdam handled 255 million metric tons of cargo
last year, including 2.84 million containers. The Port of Seattle
handled 10.4 million metric tons, including 1.03 million containers.
   The executive's annual salary is estimated to be $125,000.
   Some in Seattle's marine industry questioned why the port
commission went to Europe to find a new director.
   ``I'm shocked they went outside the country, but from what I
gather the people at the port are happy they're getting him, so
we'll just wait and see,'' said Bill Laurence, vice president of
the Pacific Coast chapter of American Waterways Operators.
</TEXT>
