<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-11 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Retreat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures prices fell sharply Tuesday, giving back
most of the previous day's gains after gold ran into resistance at
$410 an ounce.
   On other markets, cocoa futures plummeted; grains and soybeans
advanced; livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures
were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Gold may be headed below $400 a troy ounce, the key
psychological barrier it struggled past last week, analysts said.
   After climbing $5.40 to $408.60 a troy ounce Monday on New
York's Commodity Exchange, spot gold prices peaked at $410 Monday
night on overseas markets, then began to retreat.
   Gold for October delivery on the Comex settled at $404.40 a troy
ounce, down $4.20 from Monday's final price.
   ``The markets basically got up to their first main resistance
area, then started picking up selling, which seemed to accelerate
throughout the day,'' said David Syphen, manager of metals futures
trading for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   ``This is an indication that the gold market is still
fundamentally on the defensive and may retest the previous lows
below $395,'' he said.
   Spot gold fell to $392 an ounce on the Comex late last month,
reflecting slack investment demand and low inflation.
   Analyst Bette Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York said rising crude oil prices and a softer dollar early in
the session held some promise of supporting gold prices. But those
markets reversed direction later in the day.
   On the Comex, gold settled $4.20 to $4.30 lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $408.40 a troy ounce; silver
was 14.2 cents to 14.7 cents lower with December at $6.275 a troy
ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum settled $7.30 to
$8.10 lower with October at $513.10 a troy ounce.
   Cocoa futures prices plummeted on New York's Coffee, Sugar &
Cocoa Exchange, ending a seven-day rally that had pushed the
December contract up $174 a metric ton.
   The market gave up more than a third of its recent gains on
Tuesday in what traders termed a mostly technical correction.
   Cocoa futures are at 13-year lows due to a glut of cocoa and the
inability of producer and consumer nations to agree on a
price-support program.
   Cocoa settled $51 to $74 lower with December at $1,216 a metric
ton.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade in response to a surge in foreign demand, analysts
said.
   Reports that China was bidding for 400,000 metric tons of
subsidized U.S. wheat sparked speculative and commercial buying of
wheat futures. Egypt and Yugoslavia were said to be in the market
for U.S. corn, and exporters said Taiwan had purchased 54,000
metric tons of soybeans.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced the Soviet
Union had purchased 250,000 metric tons of corn. The USDA also said
it had targeted Mexico for 300,000 metric tons of subsidized wheat.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 6} cents higher with December at
$4.34\ a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 2\ cents higher with
December at $2.95 a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 7} cents higher
with December at $2.54} a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 5 cents
higher with November at $7.93{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures posted modest losses on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on technical factors while pork futures were narrowly
mixed on a combination of steady cash hog prices and light retail
demand, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled unchanged to .45 cent lower with October at
72.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .48 cent lower
with October at 81.55 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent lower to
.05 cent higher with October at 40.20 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .18 cent to .43 cent higher with February at 48 cents
a pound.
   Crude oil futures prices seesawed in nervous trading before
finishing slightly lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
Gasoline and heating oil futures were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 9 cents
lower with November at $13.55 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent
lower to .12 cent higher with November at 39.08 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .62 cent lower to .15 cent higher with
November at 40.79 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of stocks on the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled .70 point lower at 279.60.
</TEXT>
