<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Macmillan     10-11 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Macmillan,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Posts $1.1 Million Loss for 3rd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. said Tuesday it lost nearly $1.1
million in the third quarter as it took a charge for disposing of
some inventory and recorded expenses related to tender offers being
made for the company.
   The latest loss contrasts with Macmillan's earnings of $43.3
million in the July-through-September period a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 5.9 percent to $340.7 million from
$322.2 million in 1987.
   The company said it took a charge of $29.4 million for a
disposal of inventory resulting from its decision to close its
Scribner Laidlaw elementary school book line and to reorganize its
educational publishing group to achieve economies within its
elementary and high school textbook publishing business.
   It said the results also reflected expenses of $39.7 million
resulting from the tender offers and the company's own proposed
restructuring, later dropped.
   Since mid-May, Macmillan has been the target of competing offers
from the groups led by Texan Robert M. Bass, British publisher
Robert Maxwell and the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   It proposed a restructuring plan that would have divided the
company into separate publishing and information services companies
but later abandoned it.
   It has accepted a $2.5 billion offer from the Kohlberg group
that includes members of its senior management, although Maxwell
has offered $2.51 billion under certain conditions and is
challenging the company's agreement with the Kohlberg group in
court.
   For the first nine months of the year, Macmillan said it earned
$9.5 million, or 40 cents a share, down 83 percent from $55.3
million, or $2.10 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 8.4 percent to $764.3 million from
$704.9 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
