<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     10-11 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Takes Case for Buyout to Polaroid Employees in Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. and would-be buyer Roy E.
Disney battled for support of the company's workers Tuesday, with
Disney publishing a letter of reassurance about his plans for an
employee stock plan.
   Disney, who through his Shamrock Holdings Inc. is pressing an
unsolicited $2.6 billion offer for the instant film maker, also
suggested a buyout would increase job security by making Polaroid
``a vigorous, productive and more progressive company.''
   Disney, the millionaire nephew of the late animator Walt Disney,
addressed the workers in an open letter to be published Wednesday
in newspaper advertisements near Polaroid's Cambridge, Mass.,
headquarters and released earlier to the press.
   The letter said Burbank-based Shamrock's attempts to overturn a
new employee stock ownership plan as part of its buyout would be
replaced with unspecified opportunities for workers to profit from
anticipated growth at Polaroid.
   Polaroid officials refused to comment on the open letter, but
did reveal that it had rejected an Oct. 7 request by Shamrock
President Stanley Gold to meet with the employees.
   That refusal was in keeping with company policy against putting
outside speakers in touch with employees, said I. MacAllister
Booth, Polaroid's president and chief executive officer.
   Shamrock, the vehicle for Disney's diverse investments, has made
a $42-a-share tender offer to Polaroid stockholders for a majority
of the company's 61.9 million shares. That offer is valid only if a
recently announced employee stock ownership plan is overturned.
Under the plan, the company would issue new stock totaling 14
percent of the shares outstanding.
   A parallel Disney offer would pay $44 a share if management
drops its opposition and negotiates a sale.
   Polaroid management, which has sued to stop Shamrock from
increasing its 8 percent stake in the company, has characterized
the suitor's objections to the ESOP as a threat to employees.
   In the letter, Shamrock asks ``Why is polaroid's president
afraid to allow Shamrock to meet with Polaroid employees?''
   It accuses management of cutting pay 5 percent and laying off 15
percent of its U.S. workforce while establishing ``golden
parachute'' payments for top executives in event of a buyout.
   ``We intend to replace the ESOP with meaningful opportunities
for employees to participate in the future growth of Polaroid,''
the letter says, without specifying what those opportunities would
be.
   In his letter, Polaroid's Booth invited Shamrock to reveal its
plans for Shamrock's revitalization in a formal proposal.
</TEXT>
