<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drexel     10-11 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Courtroom Exchange; Judge Accuses Defense of Ethics Breach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior federal judge accused defense lawyers
Tuesday of ethical misconduct in the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
securities-fraud case, escalating what has become a hot-tempered
courtroom battle pitting the octogenarian jurist against some of
the nation's best-paid legal talent.
   Judge Milton Pollack made the accusations in response to defense
efforts to have him disqualified on grounds his wife, Moselle,
stands to gain about $30 million from the sale of her stock in
Palais Royal, a Houston company going private in a deal financed by
Drexel.
   The judge said he would forward a complaint to the chief judge
of Manhattan federal court, Charles Brieant, for a possible
disciplinary hearing into how two defense lawyers, Martin
Flumenbaum and Arthur Liman, obtained the Palais Royal information.
Both attorneys denied wrongdoing.
   The judge also chastised other defense attorneys for what he
called their ethical misconduct and irresponsible behavior for
notifying him at home on Saturday, Oct. 10, of their belief he had
a conflict of interest in the case.
   ``I'd have preferred it if you'd not called me privately,''
Pollack said angrily. ``It isn't appropriate to call up a judge on
a Saturday afternoon.''
   The developments marked the angriest exchanges yet between
Pollack and the Drexel legal team fighting the Securities and
Exchange Commission's wide-ranging civil-fraud charges.
   The SEC charges, filed last month after an intense
investigation, allege Drexel, its high-yield bond chief Michael
Milken and others colluded with now-imprisoned insider trader Ivan
Boesky to violate a variety of securities laws.
   So far the Drexel case has been stalled in pretrial maneuvering
that centers on fact-gathering and whether the case should be
handled by Pollack, a highly regarded 82-year-old jurist known for
tough rulings in securities fraud cases. From the start, Drexel and
the others have sought his removal.
   In arguments Tuesday, defense attorneys claimed they only
learned about Moselle Pollack's Drexel-related business deal on
Oct. 9 and felt obligated to notify the judge promptly, as
specified under federal litigation rules on conflicts of interest.
   They said that even if the judge can rule objectively, his
wife's business deal creates the appearance of conflict.
   Barry Goldsmith, a deputy SEC litigation counsel, argued that
Moselle Pollack's financial interests in the Drexel deal are
extremely remote and indirect, because she will get $30 million for
the sale of her ownership interest whether Drexel is involved or
not.
   He also implied Drexel created the conflict by agreeing to
become involved in the Palais Royal transaction. Drexel attorneys
denied it.
   The judge did not rule Tuesday on whether he should disqualify
himself but is expected to issue a written decision in a few days.
People familiar with the case said they doubted he would surrender
the case to another judge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
