<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WorldsFairSuit     10-11 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worlds Fair Suit,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Sends World's Fair Suit Back To District Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Petr is CQ in 6th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEGHERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district court shouldn't have dismissed a
$120 million lawsuit against officers and directors of the bankrupt
1984 Louisiana World Exposition, a federal appeals court said
Tuesday in remanding the case for further proceedings.
   ``It is clear that Louisiana law does, in fact, recognize that a
corporation may hold its officers and directors liable for gross
negligence, mismanagement and breach of fiduciary duty, '' the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said.
   The suit sought damages for contractors and other creditors who
lost money when the world's fair declared bankruptcy four days
before it closed in November 1984.
   The lawsuit was filed by a committee of creditors of the
exposition against the event's directors and officers.
   The district court threw out the case without a hearing because
state laws protected officers and directors of the bankrupt fair
from lawsuits by creditors of the event, the appeals court said in
reviewing the suit.
   The directors included fair president Petr Spurney, and other
officials of the corporation that sponsored the exhibition, such as
Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, who was a city councilman at the time,
City Councilman James Singleton and other former city officials.
   ``This appeal involves the interaction of Louisiana corporate
law and federal bankruptcy law. The fundamental question before us
is whether the committee can maintain an action against the
appellees ... for gross negligence, mismanagement and breach of
fiduciary duty,'' the appeals court said.
   ``In short, we have corrected the district court's mistaken
impressions as to the nature and viability of this lawsuit,'' the
appeals court said.
</TEXT>
