<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Interco     10-11 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Stalls Takeover Bid For Interco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>by PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Halts Hostile Takeover Of Interco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Tuesday blocked a
hostile $2.66 billion takeover bid for Interco Inc. just hours
before the tender offer was scheduled to close.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in ruling against
Cardinal Acquisition Corp. of Washington, did not specify that
judges would hear the suit filed by Interco, which argues
Cardinal's bid was illegal. The ruling freezes the bid until a
further decision is made.
   Cardinal's $70 a share tender was scheduled to close at midnight
Tuesday. Cardinal, led by brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales, began
its takeover attempt with a bid of $64 per share in July.
   In the suit, Interco alleged Cardinal violated federal
regulations by failing to disclose a co-bidder, Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Interco, a diversified furniture and apparel maker based in St.
Louis, also argued the takeover planned by Cardinal violated
federal regulations by being too highly leveraged.
   Interco spokesman David Garino said the judges had not informed
Interco of any next step in the case.
   The Rales brothers did not return a call to their Washington
office for comment.
   Interco issued a statement Tuesday afternoon urging shareholders
not to tender their shares to Cardinal and to withdraw shares
previously tendered.
   Last week, a three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Missouri upheld a federal judge's decision barring
litigation in the case.
   Before the 8th Circuit ruling, Cardinal Acquisition attorneys
argued the case should be heard in Delaware, where the Rales group
is chartered and other motions had been heard. The 3rd Circuit's
jurisdiction includes Delaware.
   On Sept. 20, Interco announced that its board of directors had
rejected a revised, conditional $72-a-share offer from the Rales
group. The board said it had instead adopted a major restructuring
and recapitalization program that might include a sale of some of
its major businesses.
   Interco's products include Ethan Allen furniture, London Fog
overwear and Florsheim Shoes.
   Interco Chairman Harvey Saligman said the restructuring plan was
worth $75 per share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
