<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ElectricBoat 1stLd-Writethru f0265 10-11 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Electric Boat, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0265,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EB Workers Ratify New Contract</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE union voting to accept pact,
picks up 5th graf, pvs `The wage...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking nuclear submarine builders at
Electric Boat voted Tuesday to accept a new four-year contract
almost identical to one rejected in August, ending a 103-day
walkout without achieving many of their demands.
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' said Joseph Messier, president of the
10,200-member Metal Trades Council, which represents 10 trade
unions. Union members voted 3,752 to 1,822 in favor of the new pact.
   ``There's going to be a lot of animosity in the shipyard,''
Messier said.
   The agreement, reached after four days of negotiations, provides
a 3 percent pay raise in the third year of the contract and bonuses
in the other years.
   The wage and benefit package is identical in dollar value to the
one union negotiators rejected in August and refused to put to a
vote of the rank and file, a company spokesman said.
   Before walking off the job July 1, workers voted 4,921 to 3,140
to reject Electric Boat's offer of lump-sum bonuses in lieu of wage
increases. The union insisted on a three-year contract with a 5
percent raise in the first year, and 4 percent raises in each of
the next two years.
   A number of recent developments in the 14-week strike put
pressure on negotiators to get the strikers back to work, including
a finding by a National Labor Relations Board official that the
strike might be illegal because the council failed to give the
required 30 days' notice before calling the walkout.
   More than 300 union jobs, including machinists, grinders and
laborers, have been permanently lost to replacement workers or
subcontracting as a result of the three-month strike, union and
company officials said.
   Electric Boat, a division of General Dynamics Corp., is a
builder of nuclear-powered attack submarines and the sole maker of
Trident ballistic submarines, the nation's largest.
   It had sought to limit percentage pay increases and pay bonuses
to reduce costs and remain competitve for submarine contracts with
rival Newport News Shipbuilding & Drydock Co. of Virginia.
   First-class mechanics, a classification that covers about 85
percent of Electric Boat's workers, earned $12.02 per hour under
the old contract. The new contract provides for workers to receive
as much as $2,250 in bonuses within about a month of returning to
work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881011-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyLaundering 2ndLd-Writethru f0276 10-11 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Laundering, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0276,0908</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Banking Firm Named In Indictments In
Money-Laundering Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th, `In addition...' to INSERT that
arrests followed enticement to fictitious wedding; picks up 9th
graf pvs, `A federal...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank holding company with branches in 72
countries was indicted Tuesday in what federal agents described as
the first drug-related money-laundering case involving a global
banking institution.
   William Von Raab, head of the U.S. Customs Service, called it
the ``first corporate raid,'' adding ``we have given new meaning to
the term `hostile takeover.'''
   ``For some international banks, their sleaze factor is higher
than their interest rates. That's what we're talking about here,
just pure greed,'' he said.
   In a two-year undercover sting dubbed ``Operation C Chase,''
from the C in C-note or a $100 bill, Customs agents were able to
infiltrate powerful Colombian money-laundering syndicates and help
launder an estimated $32 million in drug proceeds, federal
authorities said.
   The money was intended principally for Colombian drug
traffickers, including the Medellin Cartel, Customs said.
   Indictments unsealed Tuesday named nine banking officials along
with a Luxembourg-based bank holding company, BCCI Holdings, as
well as two subsidiaries, Bank of Credit and Commerce International
S.A., which has operations in the United States and England, and
Bank of Credit and Commerce International (Overseas) Limited,
organized in the Cayman Islands and operating in France, the
Republic of Panama, Colombia, Bahamas and the United States.
   In addition to the indictments, the government filed civil
complaints seeking forfeiture of individuals' property and funds as
allegedly representing drug profits, and it also seeks forfeiture
of BCCI assets.
   The announcement of the indictments followed the arrest of 11
people here Sunday after they had been lured to a fictitious
wedding, which one official compared to ``a Cecil B. DeMille
production.'' Invitations were sent and seven were nabbed en route
to a bachelor party.
   A federal judge late Tuesday lifted a restraining order that had
been issued against the bank and allowed the bank to resume normal
business after BCCI put into escrow $14 million, the amount the
government alleged the bank had laundered. Before the escrow
deposit was made, the bank had been restrained from conducting all
but routine business without clearance from U.S. Marshals.
   Altogether, 85 defendants were named in indictments returned in
Tampa, New York, Chicago, Detroit, Philadelphia, Houston.
Additionally, five other warrants were issued in Miami, Los
Angeles, London and Paris, with two in London.
   At least 40 people have been arrested around the world,
including the United States, England and Argentina, officials said.
Among those indicted was fight promoter Felix ``Tuto'' Zabala who
was ordered held without bail in Miami Tuesday on six counts of
marijuana smuggling and money-laundering.
   ``It is the first time an entire international financial
institution and its important members have been indicted,'' said
Von Raab, who appeared at a news conference here with high-ranking
customs representatives from England and France. Drug agents from
England and France participated in busting the ring.
   ``Colombian traffickers are really looking to Europe to improve
their markets,'' Von Raab said, saying cocaine prices are double
there. ``But they can't without help from financial institutions _
that's why this case is important.''
   The holding company, prosecutors said, is the world's
seventh-largest privately held financial institution. Most large
banks have publicly traded stock. While prosecutors couldn't be
reached to elaborate on the bank's size, a spokesman for the bank's
lawyers said it was an apparent reference to the geographical size
in the number of countries served.
   The trade journal American Banker said Bank of Credit and
Commerce International ranks as No. 326 among the world's biggest
banks, as measured by deposits, and No. 378 as measured by assets.
   The bank said in a news release that its officials and lawyers
had not seen the allegations and couldn't respond.
   ``The bank is wholly unaware of any violations of law that
allegedly have been committed,'' the release stated, adding that it
was confident ``the outcome will be satisfactory.''
   Beginning in July 1986, the undercover agents dealt primarily
with Gonzalo Mora Jr., who controlled a laundering network in
Medellin, Colombia, home of the Medellin Cartel, to service
traffickers John Doe, also known as ``Don Chepe,'' in that South
American city and Roberto Baez-Alcaino in Los Angeles, the
indictment said.
   Undercover agents received the money from various defendants and
laundered it for a commission, officials said. In most instances,
the money was deposited in bank accounts in Tampa, then transmitted
to Mora in Colombia via blank checks drawn on the Tampa account,
prosecutors said.
   Officials estimated that $14 million was laundered through the
BCCI subsidaries.
   According to the indictment, agents first contacted BCCI
representatives in February 1987 and began opening accounts at
various branches in July.
   Authorities said the alleged scheme operated this way: Bank
officials placed the drug money in certificates of deposit in
branches in France, Panama, Uruguay, Bahamas, Luxembourg and
England, then created a loan at another branch and allowed the
trafficers to withdraw the funds. The bank repaid the loan with
funds in the CDs, officials said.
   The indictments alleged possession and smuggling conspiracies,
as well as conspiracy to defraud the IRS, launder proceeds of
domestic cocaine sales, and engage in a continuing criminal
enterprise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
