<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0192 10-11 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0192,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Trump Reported in Deal for Shuttle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with news conference reportedly
scheduled.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump was reported Tuesday to have
agreed to buy Eastern Airlines' Northeast air shuttle, with one
estimate putting the price at more than $350 million.
   In separate reports, the Miami News and the Dow Jones
Professional Investor Report said a deal had been reached and could
be announced as early as Wednesday. The New York Times in its
Wednesday editions quoted a source that it did not identify as
saying a Wednesday morning news conference had been scheduled at
New York's Plaza Hotel to announce the deal.
   Sources had reported last week that Trump was negotiating to buy
the shuttle operation, which links New York, Boston and Washington.
Sources also reported that Carl Icahn, the financier who heads
Trans World Airlines, was discussing a possible purchase of the
struggling Eastern from its parent, Texas Air Corp.
   Neither Trump, a New York developer who owns casino property in
Atlantic City, N.J., nor officials at Eastern's Miami headquarters
would comment on the latest reports.
   The News quoted an unidentified source close to Eastern as
saying Trump would pay more than $350 million.
   Dow Jones said Eastern President Phil Bakes was in New York, but
airline spokesmen declined to say why he was there.
   In recent court testimony, Eastern executives said the shuttle
was the only profitable Eastern operation.
   Texas Air, citing a billion dollars in Eastern losses over the
past decade, has said it must have labor concessions to keep the
airline going.
   Eastern made the shuttle into a separate division last year,
leading to speculation that Texas Air was considering selling it to
raise cash.
   Asked about Tuesday's reports, Norma Foerderer, spokeswoman for
the Trump Organization, said, ``I have nothing to say about this
matter at his time.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell also declined to discuss the
reports.
   Leaders of Eastern unions, who went to court to block an earlier
planned spinoff of the shuttle from Eastern to a new Texas Air
subsidiary, said they had no first-hand confirmation on the shuttle
sale but would fight it.
   Ron Cole, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association local
representing Eastern pilots, said: ``ALPA's position all along has
been we would oppose the sale. We will take whatever legal means is
possible.''
   Officials of the Machinists union, which filed the suit that
derailed the spinoff of the shuttle, were reported to be in an
arbitration meeting and unavailable to comment.
   That suit stemmed from Texas Air's announcement last February
that it planned to transfer the shuttle to a new subsidiary in
return for an infusion of $225 million in cash for Eastern.
   In March, U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt blocked the plan
with a contempt of court finding against Eastern.
   A federal appeals court reversed Pratt's contempt order in June,
but left the door open for the unions to mount another court
challenge. The following month, Eastern announced that the plan was
off.
   In recent weeks, reports surfaced that the shuttle again was for
sale _ this time to an outside buyer.
   Trump's desire for the shuttle became public knowledge last
week, and then Icahn was reported to be interested in buying all of
Eastern. Union sources said that they had met with Icahn, and there
was speculation Icahn would make an offer for Eastern only if the
unions agreed to concessions in their pay and work rules.
   The Miami Herald reported Tuesday morning that Eastern's unions
were continuing talks with Icahn. The Herald, quoting unidentified
sources, said Icahn wanted the pilots union to accept 15 percent
paycuts while the pilots offered to freeze their salaries at
present levels until 1992.
   Cole, the pilots spokesman, declined comment on the Herald's
report.
</TEXT>
