<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0291 10-11 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0291,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Tumble, Dollar Higher In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei closing,
comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
while the U.S. dollar inched up against the Japanese yen in
Wednesday morning trading.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 211.33-point winner Tuesday, was down 212.69
points at 27,256.91 by the end of Wednesday morning trading.
   Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities said many investors stayed
on the sidelines for a variety of reasons, including the precarious
health of Japan's Emperor Hirohito and the upcoming release of new
U.S. trade figures.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is scheduled to release monthly
trade figures for August on Thursday in Washington.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened at 131.12 yen, down from
Tuesday's close of 131.15 yen, and drifted higher during the
session. The dollar was trading at 131.20 yen by midmorning.
   Foreign exchange dealers said uneasiness over the trade figures
also pushed the dollar down, but compared to Tuesday the pressure
was lower. On Tuesday, the dollar had fallen 2.35 yen for its
lowest closing since mid-July.
   Market sentiment shows investors expect the U.S. trade figures
to widen from the previous month, a dealer with a major commercial
bank said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
